name: Fly Away
description: Nice and easy problem. Makes for a fun route. Just make sure you have good handholds and avoid grabbing smaller ledges as the rock is brittle in some places.

name: Heel hook
description: Pretty easy route. The crux is the getting to the top ledge. As the name might imply, a heel hook makes this route quite manageable.

name: Huntsman’s Hideout
description: Stand start on the left sidepull and right hand around the arete. Work your way up the arete to some good jugs and out of the small roof to the mossy top out. Watch out for the spider hide-out.

name: Indian’s Crack
description: Really nice crack climb. The crux is the start as there’s only one good place for foot placement at the start. You can either do left hand in the crack and right hand on a small crimp to start or both hands in the crack. Either one makes for a fun and slightly difficult climb!

name: Just one more
description: Very fun problem that took me quite a while to figure out. Start right off the ground with two nice handholds and decent footholds. You’ll have to move in such a way to get your right foot into the pocket your left hand starts out in. Once there, you’ll have two crimpy holds, and must traverse to the left then take the obvious route up. Crux is definitely the middle section of getting your right foot set into the pocket and traversing to the left.

name: Last One
description: This route starts off with an overhang. You’ll have to climb over the lip of the rock and go straight into a deadpoint. This route looks like it’s only 15 feet or so from the picture, but the top section slopes backwards for another 10 feet or so.

name: Short Stop
description: Stand start on left sidepull and right undercling. Head directly up this short wall to the top out. There’s some nice movement in this problem that makes me wish it went on and on...

name: Crash Landing
description: Start in the middle of the Airplanes Boulder.  Climb up the short ramp, past slopey ledges to a vertical seam.  Continue to a tricky and committing mantle that guards the top.

name: Bobcat
description: Proud line going up the steep face of the bobcat boulder. Start on good pockets down low and move up to a tough undercling move. Shift right to the arete and pull one more hard snatch move before the slopey topout.

name: Catalytic Cat
description: Start in the good jugs down low, working up into the seam of the dihedral. Layback and balance your way up small feet and progressively smaller holds to a good layback in the big runnel. A small right hand rail secured the top out moves for a heady finish.

name: Dirty Rubbers
description: Start with a left hand on the arete and a right on a sloper. Poor/crumbly feet exist, but use caution. Smearing works well. Use the left arete and stay on the face of the boulder, working towards good ledges and slopers on top.

name: Temporary Joy
description: Start on a small crimp on the slabby face just above the lip.  Climb onto the slab and top out above.

name: The Wind Through the Keyhole
description: The obvious splitter crack on the left side of the tunnel as you walk uphill. Begin with a couple of tense face moves to establish at the base of the seam. Secure laybacking and jamming, with tenuous smears take it to the top.

name: Creeky
description: Creeky emerges from the creek below Taratula. Makes a great warm up and has a lot of variations. I like to start my day at the lakeside set at Creeky, followed up by Tarantula and work my way boulder to boulder back to the truck.

name: Dirtbags (Direct)
description: Sit start on the obvious crimp jug (same start as dirt bags and dragons) middle of the boulder, compress and move straight up to the sloper, top out.

name: Dirtbags and Dragons
description: Far right at the Lakeside set, in a hole, really close to the road. Also the home of a frequented geo cache.

name: DynoWing
description: In a hallway of doom and mosquitos a very unique problem lurks. The first visible boulders as you round the top of the hill from parking.

name: Mammoth
description: Mammoth is a large boulder hosting multiple lines of varying difficulties. Not a fun hike, but a very easy hike. Head towards Zanesville (river on your right) until you see a large boulder over the guardrail on the right.

name: The Rug
description: Around the corner on the Tarantula Boulder. Start on the bottom left arete and move up and right to "The Rug". Just wipe your feet off or mom's gonna kill me!

name: Slip-N-Slide
description: The name says it all. Slip-N-Slide. Small holds, balancey moves and so much moss. Usually it’s green and actively growing moss. But once in a while, on a cool fall afternoon, after some careful brushing...it goes!

name: Snowblind
description: Reach up to some incut holds facing the wrong way. Pull on and make big moves up the steep wall. Committing finish.

name: Tarantula
description: Reachy, powerful moves on a steep overhang with few usuable features. Powerful compression moves to start, entering the crux almost immediately once you pull on the start crimps. Tarantula is nestled into the hillside and has an interesting walkable/climbable cave system underneath. Very fun. Very unique!

name: TrillZilla
description: Yeah it’s roadside, but the hike down 146 still kinda sucks. But this boulder problem doesn’t! Well it’s not the best, but you’re in Zanesville climbing so chill and have fun.

name: White Freightliner
description: Begin sitting with a right hand flat undercling, left hand pocket/crimp, and a high right smear. Two moves get you established on the start of Tarantula. Do the first few moves of that problem, and move right through underclings to finish on the Snowblind dyno.

name: Winter Sun
description: Climb the arete next to DynoWing on the Hallway boulder.  Sit start, couple of bumps and some voodoo take you to the lip next to the tree. Good clean fun.

name: A Shoe in the Bush...
description: Big move to the ledge under the roof, and then get into the business in the crack above.  Some jams are sinker, some not so much.  What is a shoe in the bush worth exactly?!  In the hand?

name: The Baguette
description: Start with your hands in a slot deep under the roof with your feet on a ramp.  This is the same start as Contortionist.  Climb towards a round pinch ledge in the middle of the roof, possibly using holds on Contortionist, then go big to the ledge.  Perform a high heelhook to get to the lip and mantle over at the corner of the boulder.

name: Barbaric Yawp
description: Start standing with the ledge straight under the little chossy bat cave feature. Climb up to the jugs at the cave, lock off to the pinchy sloping left hand sidepull and fight the barndoor to stab right hand to a juggy scoop/hueco. Easy finish from here.  Im short and used a kneebar for the first big reach.  Looks like it should be super easy but it gave me fits.  Getting into and maintaining the crux left pinch while finding the right balance to stab to the good right hold was powerful and techy. .. took more effort than "psych" but not saying its harder.  Could be easier with different positioning. You decide.

name: Burdens
description: Start standing left of savage verse 10ft-ish.  I started direct, avoiding the dirty and more friable stone to the right.  work through slopers and edges to gain a horizontal ledge system at mid height.  For the last pull to the ledge use the fattest part of the hold at the lip.  The thinner section may snap off.  Balance off the rail to a difficult right hand sloping hold and do a big and somewhat insecure lock off to a thin horizontal crimp slot.  Without a good matching option, there's another long reach to the lip rewarded by an easy mantle.  Like with the neighbors, the upper rock on this is really good.  It would get all the stars if the start was more singular and the lower lip holds were not suspect.  Re: grade: Harder and less secure lockoff than savage verse with easier set up moves.  Could be harder than 7, but my radar is way off.  The last established 7 i did was covert direct in the red. In comparison, this was two full grades harder for me but FAs always feel harder, so...?

name: Contortionist
description: Start in the big waist-high pocket on a sloping ledge and head up and left through another big pocket.

name: Contortionists Traverse
description: Starts on Contortionist, moves left and links up with Grunt and Go and ends with Into the Sun

name: Fallout
description: Start on sidepulls on either side of a protruding block.  Climb up on slopey holds, then make a big sideways move right to a good crimp, and then top out on the slopey slab.  Avoid taking a direct approach by grabbing the good holds along the lower lip next to the crack.

name: French Fries
description: Start on a rough, protruding knob at head height.  Climb up on deep, slightly slopey ledges to a tricky topout that lacks feet.

name: Friends
description: Start on double underclings and make move to an angeled slot.  Keep going up and right, on a bad slot and poor pinches to a gaston before the top.

name: Grunt & Go
description: Start from a stand on deep incut slots. Make some big moves where cutting feet may be easier.

name: Into the Sun
description: Sit start on a long ledge close to the ground.  This shares a start with Mail Slot.  Make a big move right to a small slot, then move up and right on more slots, before a big move to a slopey ledge just before the top.  Top out.

name: Junk Mail
description: Starts left of mail slot on the two slots then finish same as mail slot. Added this variation due to the undercling start hold being snapped off of mail slot.

name: Just the Crust
description: An eliminate.  Climb the baguette without using the good stuff (the rail with the crimp pocket, slopers and edges) to the left for hands or feet.  You essentially go from the hand jam start straight to the little dogbone tufa crimp and lock that straight to the sloper pinch,  then dyno or campus still staying off that big sloer rail with your feet.  This takes a great line (baguette) and swaps stars for v grade points, but I just wanted to see if i could pull on that crimp and get to the pinch directly... a test for my shoulder recovery... and a personal challenge, not a classic addition.

name: Lazy Boi
description: Start on a slopey ledge and climb up into the layback crack.  Preform a tricky mantle to gain the top.

name: Lunar Eclipse
description: Start on a large horn immediately to the right of a tree, just left of the start of Psych.  Traverse right on holds about head-height, before angling up and to the right.  Finish on a large hold just below the blank headwall

name: Mail Slot
description: Sit start on a long ledge close to the ground.  This shares a start with Into the Sun.  Flip to an undercling and make a big throw up to a wide, deep slot.  Continue on slots to a long, sloping ledge just before the top out.

name: Psych
description: Start on a good ledge shoulder height.  Climb up on crimps to a seam before the roof.  Jump back to the large jug, then discover trickery to reach the top...  Be sure to scout the top, as it is high and gets dirty easily.

name: Raid the Castle
description: Hop up to a high, good ledge.  Mantle up, then climb to the lip using bad smears and sidepulls.

name: Savage Verse
description: Amazing line just left of the tree, left of psych.  A couple dynamic moves to start then a big lockoff crux using an amazing edgy pinch just above the midway jug ledge.  I started with a scooped right hand sidepull/undercling at about chest height for a direct start and to avoid lesser quality rock and dirty holds to the left.    Regarding grade, I certainly gave it more than v7 effort, but my suspicion is that someone with more reach may walk it.  My wingspan is 5'8" ish and I really had to finger crawl for the crux lockoff.  Dialing that move took a bit more work than the long move on 'the drip.'  Whatever the grade, however, the holds are very cool and give rise to great moves.  I know this has been cleaned and worked by others so if someone did it previously please chime in.  edit:  i've plugged in a name.  for what it's worth, it comes from a yawpers song, mon nom, that was in my head around this time:       Watch the fire consume it      And cry a savage verse.      Watch the better angels of nature      take a dive for the earth.

name: Slugfest
description: Boulder up good edges and then use a large ear like hueco to get you to the top.

name: Slumber Party
description: Start low in a large two-hand slot and work through some crimpy pockets in a shallow crack up to where it widens into a pair of hand sized slots. Jam or lie back and reach high to finger lock in the parallel crack, and then go for the top out.

name: Smear Campaign
description: Start on a slopey ledge and smear up the wall to sidepulls.  Top out above the water grove.

name: Solar Eclipse
description: This is an extension of Lunar Eclipse, starting as a lowball traverse and then taking it to the top for an exciting finish. Start on the large horn just right of a tree, and traverse right ~10-15 feet staying low and then trending up and right to the finish hold of Lunar Eclipse.  Keep traversing right on some slopers to a good pocket and head for the top, just left of the tree.  This one builds on you, getting progressively harder and a lot more exciting...

name: Tree Hugger
description: Start in underclings and move through the crimp to sidepulls and high feet till you reach the pipe hold than pull the lip, or tree hug it.  Shares upper side pulls and top out with Friends.

name: Wild Rabbit
description: The furthest left boulder problem in the West Side Boulders. Tight sit start from flat sloper both hands. Grab right pocket and long reach to jug sloper on the edge. Traverse to right on the corner and enjoy crux sloper section to the top. You won’t use any “Junk mail” jugs. I felt harder than V6 and easier than V7.

name: Artificial Sweeteners
description: Start on good crimps on an orange colored ledge.  Climb through some always wet pockets to crimps.  The original version finished on a shelf above the cave.As of 8-7-2020 the topout is cleaned.  The topout is heady, but mild, and makes this short boulder feel more complete.

name: Closeout
description: Another short fun one up the big roof on the far right side of the Wave Wall.  Climb a short pock-marked face to a roof, and then follow a sloping rail to get up into the business. Go for the lip and then use the sidepull/undercling on the face on the left to heave up and over into easier climbing to the finish. (There is slightly easier beta going right after the lip, but the moves and rock are lower quality. Go left for full value!)  This is a new route, and some of the rock on this one might be a bit friable, so use caution (belayer especially!). The shelf just below the roof is questionable, as is some of the rock out right.  I knocked off what I could but more may yet still break.  Climb gingerly.

name: Drip
description: In the cave adjacent to the wave wall. Start sitting on a good edge and the handle bar hold. Tense, crimpy undercling moves lead slightly left to a reach dependent move to the jug rail. Traverse left to one more big move off of crimps to finish in high horizontal just above the apex of the cave. Drop off, though a top out would be reasonable with some cleaning

name: End of the Road
description: The furthest right boulder problem in the cave adjacent to the wave wall. Start sitting at a rail with a variety of crimps. Without using the massive pedestal foot to the right, make one reach dependent move to the higher rail, and traverse left to finish the same as Drip. At least as long as some of the sport routes in the area

name: Get Pitted
description: Sit start a few inches right of the pinchy ledge where get railed starts. Power through 2 incut Pockets then make an easy hop to a good diagonal edge with good holds above. I did not top it out but you definitely could if you spend enough time cleaning the upper slab.   Moving from the first pocket to the second pocket was the Crux for me. It took me more effort then get railed but if you're good at powerful moves between good holds it might not feel difficult at all. I'd be curious if this is an established line. I assume it is because it was clean and had remnants of chalk on it. whomever did it first please chime in.

name: Get Railed
description: Start at the far right side of the rail. Bust some sequential moves up to the end of the rail, hit a left hand slot crimp, and dead point up to a better slot. Move left to a jug. Drop off or continue up the tall, slab.As of 8-7-2020, the topout slab is cleaned.  The topout doesn't add difficulty but provides an enjoyable sequence and satisfying fishing to the boulder.

name: Hang Five
description: Fun little route on the right side of Wave Wall.  Start with a couple of big moves up to a techy finish in a dihedral with some finger jams.

name: Hit and Run
description: Start as for Get Railed, but bust up and right from a pair of jugs in the middle of the rail. Make a precise, dynamic right-hand move for a Spock-pocket and then make a couple of deadpoint moves on crimps. Finish on a sloping jug in a horizontal crack as you wish that your spring break trip to Joe's hadn't been cancelled. Not a bad climb if a pandemic prevents you from climbing anywhere else. Here's a fun video.As of 8-7-2020 the topout is clean.  While it doesn't add difficulty, the moves are enjoyable.

name: Hot Pants
description: Start on left hand edge and right hand undercling. Figure out impossible static beta, or set feet and fly out to flat shelf. Traverse left and up a few moves and drop. Someone who's inspired can clean the high slab topout.

name: Revenge of the Sloth
description: Engaging climbing with some excellent sequences.  Often wet in the spring, get on it in the fall

name: Short Stop
description: Ends on Get Railed. Start on sloper rail, make a few moves up semi bad holds straight up and end on good jug. Short and sweet

name: Tsunami
description: Climb a steep opening with excellent movement to a series of small crimps.   Then either get dynamic to get to the anchors or figure out how to crimp on a sloping rail. Often wet, but a great route if you can catch it dry.

name: The Tube
description: Climb up a crack to an ear feature and launch into the ever steepening wave where you make some desperate moves to a fantastic friendly jug.  Shake out, because it is not over; it will take a blind throw from a thin crimpy rail to get you to the clipping jug.

name: Ants in Your Pants
description: follow up on the sandstone, 4 bolts to anchor

name: Change of Pace
description: Fun!  Are those pockets big or small?  You figure it out. The first half can be a dirty or crumbly in places, but the finish is quality. Start next to the tree.

name: Cop a Feel
description: Thought provoking moves through the roof.

name: Get Over It
description: Climb the face left of the crack, head toward the big slot, and then traverse left under the bulge.

name: Get Over It and Deliver
description: Follow the crack between "Get Over It" and "Stand Up and Deliver."  At the V, move right to finish on the "Deliver" chains.  First trad route at Marne Wall (to my knowledge).  Bolts?  Who needs bolts?!

name: Give, Don't Take
description: Bouldery start to pull the first bulge, and then a little second overhand with poor holds to contend with.  Got a bit harder after a hold broke at the second lip!

name: Hot Choss Buns
description: Another fun one with juggy holds, until they're not.

name: Mantlepiece
description: Perhaps it's not a masterpiece, but it's close.  ish...A fun little route with some good stemming and mantling and a couple distinct cruxes."5.8 trad or 5.11 sport"

name: The Phoenix
description: right of the crack

name: Sign of the Choss
description: Pretty similar to the ones next too it!

name: Stand Up & Deliver
description: Start right of the obvious crack, next to a tree.  Reachy start, move right, and then find the hidden hold... exactly where you want it to be!

name: Brownsville Boogie
description: Start in a large water runnel under the crack, stemming and chimney up the crack using large face holds on both sides.

name: Chickenhorn
description: Climb through a series a bulges, some easy, some hard.  The last one will likely give you pause and require a pretty good reach. Take it all the way to the top on some easy but insecure slab.

name: Comfortably Numb
description: Start just right of a broad shield and work your way up a vertical face.  Stand on a ledge, set up and pull through the cruxy bulge up top.This route and it's neighbor to the right were bolted in the dead of winter.   There was a steady stream of water dripping down on the developer making it a pretty wet and miserable.  However, some imbibing of "Hot Stuff" whiskey left the developer comfortably numb.

name: Dusty Squeeze
description: Great off width! Very fun with great placements. Start in the OW with good pro or climb the 5.7 face to the right with no pro to the first ledge. After the small tree mid route squeeze your way and stem up the crack. To finish, top out with a well protected but thought provoking crux. Bolted anchors in place.

name: The End of Poison Ivy
description: A previously bolted route that's really a trad route.  This thing eats gear and the placements are just downright fun.Starts in a large flaring off-width, although you can also start on the face immediately to the right (steeper, but on good holds).  Stem and chimney your way to the top.  Continue past an old rap anchor to the top for a cruxy but rewarding finish and the real anchors at the top of the cliff. Enjoy the well-deserved view!So much fun!Note that if you are expecting to find some old bolts still in place, you'll have to trust your cams I'm afraid. The bolts have been pulled.

name: Hot Stuff
description: Climb the vertical face to a good-sized roof/bulge.  Finding the right holds and a little technique keeps the difficulty at it's suggested grade.This route was bolted with it's neighbor to the left in the dead of winter.   The developer kept the cold at bay with some "Hot Stuff" whiskey.

name: Katz Corner
description: Another easy line with big holds and fun movement.  Start in the large crack, then follow the jugs through the steep stuff.  Can finish straight up staying next to the big crack, or move left into the flake to go to the upper set of anchors.  Great kids/beginners route.

name: Katz in the Cradle
description: Follows an angling crack up a slab.

name: Katz out of the Bag
description: Vertical climbing on good but small crimps to start, followed by some thought-provoking moves up top on slopers.  Don't blow it trying to clip the chains.  If getting on it early in the season, convince your buddy to climb it first and brush off the finish hold for you.

name: Leaves on the Breeze
description: A fun full-length route that takes you to the top of the cliff. A nice variety of climbing moves with a few thought provoking sequences along the way.

name: My First Time
description: Starts on a well featured vertical face and climbs a series of small bulges.  Most of the climbing is easier, but one big move over a pretty featureless bulge will present some difficulties, especially to those with limited reach.  Easier climbing to the top.  "My first time was fun, but I wish it had been longer and I was able to do a few more moves when it was hard."

name: Scaredy-Katz
description: Right side of the wall immediately to the left of the very low angle slab routes. Techy vertical climbing on small but positive holds to a very balancy crux.

name: Silver Streaks
description: A very fun climb that follows the obvious line up the middle of the crack/chimney. Pull the initial reachy bulge to get started, enjoy easier ground through the middle, and then work through the last tricky bit of stemming before you clip the chains.

name: The Basket Case
description: Easy climbing on jugs to the last ledge where you might find yourself searching for the easy beta to get to the anchors.

name: Born on the Fourth of July
description: Start on the bouldery finger crack, move into pockets, then start the business moving through the big crack in the roof.  Work the off-width (5.12?) or move left onto face holds to gain a large ledge.  Walk a few feet to the right and finish the upper crack to the anchors.  Awesome moves to the ledge, and fun to the top.Note: It is possible to protect very well throughout, but if you sew it up down low, the rope drag up top will be ultra heinous. So you choose: run it out down low or suffer at the top!  Either way, long slings recommended down low!  You can always puss out and clip bolts on sport line to the left.You could also imagine a number of fun variations.  1)  Just climb the overhanging crack start, and then lower off the anchors for "Just Say No to Crack."  2) Make it a mixed route and start up any of the three sport routes to the right of the off-width and then go to the top on gear to make the line a bit less winding, although rope drag may be problematic nonetheless (back-clean 1st draw or two?)   3)  Climb the overhanging wide crack, but then move left to go to the top via Wet Dreams.

name: Broken Dreams
description: Start in the cave with an exciting and steep start to get things going.  Continue past the steep stuff to more moderate vert terrain.   Pull a move to gain the slab face and continue to more vert terrain.  High clip the last bolt if you can and launch into the crux that will test your reach or lock off strength.   If you fall, join the list of people with broken dreams of sending.  Grade probably height dependent.

name: Bush League
description: Fantastic movement packed into a short climb! Starts with a bouldery sequence off an undercling to a rail. Power through to the good holds, get to the large shelf hold, hit the pocket and crank up and throw for the lip. It's not over yet though... A last crux awaits you as you try to pull onto the face.

name: Calf Ripper
description: Start under the big roof with a finger crack, move onto pockets, then traverse right into the crack to pull the roof.  Stem to the top.

name: The Deep End
description: Once you managed to avoid sinking and swim to the anchors, you’re ready to head to the deep end.  This one will challenge your campus, mantle, and slab skills.   Well worth wading into... just don’t get in over your head!

name: Don't Break It if You Can't Buy It
description: Mantle up, milk the jug, and then figure out how to get the to lip.  Once you pull that one, another one awaits with easier moves... if only you could see the holds!  Try not to break anything.

name: The Final Exam
description: Masters of slab, this one is for you.  Despite a couple of substantial roofs along the way, the difficulty increases the more the angle eases off!Once you've gotten (into the) "Ivy League," then you can see if are ready to pass "The Final Exam."

name: Ivy League
description: Begins with a tricky boulder problem with a sidepull to a big reach and limited feet.  Regain your composure under the big roof and then jug haul your way to the lip. As you go to pull onto the face above, you may find yourself looking left... or was it right... for some decent holds. You'll figure it out!

name: Jugs for Thugs
description: Climb on good rock and holds through an extremely steep face requiring some core strength and big moves.    Very fun, and climbs longer than it looks due to the steepness.

name: Just Say No to Crack
description: Easy intro climbing leads to a nice boulder problem which is harder (and more fun) if you avoid the crack.  Finish up on jugs.

name: Landers Last Gander
description: Start just left of the off-width roof crack and work your way right of the crack and up the steepness that requires some core fitness to get you through the roof.  The finish is no gimme to the anchors.  Clip the old rusty bolt and hanger as a directional only.

name: Leaves of Three
description: Start up the right side of the low scoop.  Pull the start and make some easy moves on jugs.  Lock it down and finish it off.

name: Ninja Skill Called Trad
description: Start in a small dihedral with a finger crack (often mungy), crank through the two roofs, and then whip out some ninja trad skills to pull up through the slot.  Be sure to clip the bolt on the LEFT just below the slot -- the old one causes a bad rope line as you climb above. Then enjoy the steep but brief jug haul to the top.

name: Roofs for Goofs
description: Improbable climbing for the grade takes you through a series of horizontal roofs where your playgrounds monkey bar skills may pay off.  Unfortunately, just when you’re starting to enjoy the climbing, you’re at the lip and the ride is over.   Grade may be height dependent.

name: Sink or Swim
description: Just like swimming, this one is easier if you keep moving.  Enjoy a nice flow of movement on good holds.

name: Wet Dreams
description: For the true all-arounder!  Starts off steep with jugs and big throws that will make sure the traddies work for their beer, and finishes up on a vertical but pretty featureless flaring crack that is guaranteed to befuddle your buddies who only know how to clip bolts.Shares a start with Jugs for Thugs through the first three moves, then goes straight up (slightly left) on the vertical face above the roof, toward the huge flaring crack. Walk up the ramp and then stem/shimmy/butt-scum/jam/whatever your way up the flaring crack.  Don't let you guard down until it's done.Recommendation:  Stick-clip the 2nd bolt of Jugs for Thugs to protect the start, and pre-hang the first draw on Wet Dreams. Climb to the lip, clip the first draw of Wet Dreams and then back-clean to minimize rope drag (easy to do from the last big jug at the lip).

name: Between a Flood and a Lockdown
description: More of a "lying down" start than a sit start... but starts on the small ledge/crack at the bottom of the left side of the large crack.  Work your way up the left side using ridges and bumps and a hidden crimper pocket.  Finish on the large horn before the rock turns to crap.  While you get a starting foot on the right side of the crack, that's it!  After that, left side only y'all.

name: Built for Business
description: Start on the large cheater block or jump start to a large slot in front of the tree.  Traverse left through the roof and move onto the pockets above.Route names stems from the difficulty and the fact that it was obviously "built".

name: Casual Business
description: This is a route where you actually get to feel like you are really rock climbing.   A retro-bolt and extension of an old unknown sport line.  This one is super enjoyable with a few cruxes to make things interesting.This route was bolted after work one evening in the summer.   However, the developer forgot to bring a change of clothes and bolted wearing their business casual work clothes.   Hence the route "Casual Business" was established.

name: Closed for Business - closed project
description: Alternative finish for Built for Business take a direct line up from the sloping ledge.

name: Diversion
description: Start low and make a few delicate moves to reach a stance under the 1st bolt.  Begin in earnest with a powerful move to get going and cruise up to the ledge.   Hit the timer and launch into the overhanging face above where it is a race against the pump clock.  While no move is particularly hard, you also don’t get much of a rest until the anchors.This route was named with a double entendre in mind.   If you look closely at the top you will see the water diversion shenanigans to keep the route dry.  It also became a route to keep us entertained with climbing after COVID shut down the world.

name: Genesis
description: This route is perfect for the boulderer with 3 distinct sections separated by good rests and progressively harder cruxes that will test your pocket pulling and crimping strength.  If look closely, (not really that closely-it's pretty obvious) you'll see a large dark outline just above the ledge that used to be an enormous flake.   Incredibly the entire flake broke off when the far left side was attempted to be trundled with a large crowbar.  You'll see some of the large pieces of it below that have been repurposed for cheater stones.The route was the first put up on the wall, and thus became the genesis of a new wall of climbing.

name: Give Thanks
description: A powerful sit start on slopers leads to better holds and fun moves up the arete.  The left side of the crack is off!  Be aware that the large block capping the topout ledge is awfully hollow, but can easily be avoided.  Probably OK, but I sure wouldn't yard on it...

name: Merci
description: Sit start on the large sloper on the right side of a large crack.  Throw to the hold above, and then traverse right to a large sloper rail.  Then go up to a highly textured hold before hitting a series of crimps.  Tops out on the holds at the large ledge.  NOTE:  This route has been revised with this better start making it worthy of more stars.  Original route started on the large rail directly.  Also, downgraded...

name: Mungdungus Corner
description: This is a mixed route.  Start 5-10 feet left of the obvious dihedral on a sandy rail (same start as Genesis) and traverse right through the steep bouldery section before mantling only a ledge.  A bolt down low protects this slightly chossy (but very fun!) start.  Then move into the mungy dihedral with a widening hand crack.  Pull the lip and move left on the slab under the giant block and climb (gingerly) the crack to the chains.   DO NOT PLACE GEAR BEHIND THE FLAKE!!!  There is a bolt just before anchor to use instead.  The block at the top is solid and shows no signs of movement, but it might just come off some day, and it ain't gonna be pretty.

name: Murphy's Law
description: Start low in a thin, sloping slot with a poor left foot.  Climb up through textured sloping ledges to jugs at the top.  Drop from an incut ledge just below the first bolt.

name: Pipedream- Closed Project
description: Desperate climbing up the steepest part of Genesis wall.This project was named for the obvious pipe near the top that helps keep the route dry and the difficulty vs fitness quotient that makes sending a "Pipedream"

name: Pound of Flesh - closed project
description: Closed project. Mid 13?This projects name stems from the developer getting his hand caught between the rope and draw while bolting the line.  He could unweight the rope to get his hand out and instead it ripped out a "Pound of flesh" from his finger.  (Ok, maybe a slight exaggeration... but it still hurt like hell!)

name: Slanderfest
description: One of the steeper routes on the Genesis wall.  Better holds with some big moves and a finish to make you earn the grade.

name: Slippery When Wet
description: Fun route with some cool moves and one hold that's awfully slippery when it's wet!  Starts in a big textured slot and goes up to a big ledge and then to a shelf (same opening as "Thankfully"), and then follows the arete up through pockets and slopers trending right to the lip.    Pad 'er up -- it's tall, and there is a big pointy rock in the landing.  Yes, you can hit it...  "A knock to the head, that's all it takes"

name: Thankfully
description: Start in a large and highly textured slot before moving up and left onto a juggy rail. Traverse left through a series of pockets and finish on the holds at the big ledge.  It's really a fun little warmup problem, although the first hold can be a bit wet when things are seeping a lot.

name: Thanksgiving Parade
description: Tired of all those brown stains in your drawers from the highballs on the west side of the crag?!  Come try this amazing lowball traverse: a quite long sequence, with very cool moves and everything from crimps to slopers, rails to pockets,  jugs to pinches. Get your heel hook on! Crux comes about midway through.   Sadly, a few of the holds in the 2nd half tend to seep, so moisture is likely to be an issue in the wet season.

name: Witless & Fitless
description: Fun continuous climbing on good crimps and pockets.  Figure out your beta or you might find yourself crossed up.  Named for the FA"s COVID era lack of fitness and the their propensity to grid bolt a blank wall.

name: Crown Jewel
description: This problem sits atop the hill, and commands the area like the center jewel on the crown of a king. Sit start with a tooth-like pinch and work into a undercling dish. Another strenuous move to a crimp followed by a committing bump and core intensive footwork eventually leads to easier ground.

name: High Dive
description: This easy highball follows the swath of pockets up the right side of the tall and attractive face that is central to the Diving Board Boulders.

name: Poo in the Pool
description: On the second "tier" of sorts there are 3 or 4 in-place, attractive boulders that upon closer inspection lack any obvious lines. This problem is on the right side of the steep wall that lacks holds besides a few honkin' jugs. Anyway, this fun problem begins on low flat jugs, moves up and right to a circular pinch hold, then to a solid iron crimp rail and a fun mantle.

name: Pool Party
description: This problem climbs up the arete, left of poo in the pool. Stand start, left hand on undercling jug, right hand on undercling ledge/pinch. Climbs straight up the arete topping out directly over the arete.

name: Stabin' Shack
description: Sit start on the dagger-like jug 5 feet right of Crown Jewel. Climb straight up on crimps.

name: [Redacted]
description: Sit start on large holds left of the arete. Move up into underclings, and then a distant hold on the top of the arete.

name: Armada
description: THE problem at Hozaks! Sit start beneath the awesome, rounded arete. Climb up to good holds, the figure out how to manipulate a slopey dish and  foot smears to reach the high sidepull and top out jug. An excellent boulder problem requiring some funky body tension.

name: Stumped
description: Start low on crimps, climb straight up through slopers and top out.

name: Arrowhead Arete
description: Sit start on the under cling on the left and heel hook the right side of the arete. Find the slopers  and a super easy top out. Hardest part is the first two moves.

name: Aztec Warrior
description: Climb the rails and jugs on the slab to a nice top out and enjoy the view.

name: Backbend
description: The variety of holds and quality of movement make this one worth checking out. Start in the low dual pockets and work your way up a sloper and crimp rails to gain the slab face. Proceed straight up to the ledge under the wave face where you'll understand the problems name. Traverse left along the ledge to walk off.

name: Bad Company
description: A fun, but contrived power problem. Sit start on the short steep face on the backside of the Hive Boulder on two chalked sloping crimps. Avoiding the large holds out left, move up and right to a sloping pinch/crimp, the fire up and left for another slopey pinch. Definitely an eliminate, but still fun.

name: Cloud Nine
description: The tall attractive lakeside arete. Start on underclings with a large ledge foot and figure out how to reach distant holds higher up on the arete.

name: Fear Factor
description: Start by climbing up the part protruding from underneath the boulder so you can reach good crimps. Slightly traverse right on decent feet and figure out how to use the diagonal rails to reach the huge jug slightly beneath the top. Be Careful topping out.

name: Good Fortune
description: Trends left on the side of the Hive Boulder. Sit start on low jugs to the right, then follow good holds up and left to a top out at the apex of the boulder.

name: Have Horse, Will Travel
description: Starts sitting on huge jug beneath the crack splitting the tall face. Work up into the crack and make a few more moves to an easy heady topout

name: Headless Horseman
description: Sit start left hand on small knob like feature, right hand on pocket. Straight up through crimps and over the ledge. Top out through the grass or traverse left and out once over the ledge.

name: Hive Face
description: Steep, solid rock that offers the best warm ups in the area. As its covered with all sorts of holds, it is hard to define individual problems, but I've had hours of fun with this one just making up eliminates and trying hard.

name: Hodor
description: If you understand the reference, this arete lives up to the name

name: Horse Head
description: Climb the tall boulder starting a little bit right-of-center and use the small ledges to top out. Lots of potential on this one & many different ways to climb it.

name: Iron Arete
description: Starts on a bean shaped iron feature on the right side of the clean white face. Climb sharp holds to an easy topout.

name: Iron Resolve (Project)
description: With rock reminiscent of Coopers, this problem will be an Ohio classic once it is sent. Sit start on sculpted underclings, figure out how to get your butt off the ground, and follow sculpted crimps and slimpers to an easier topout. Grade is an estimate.

name: Iron Sides
description: The slab on the right side of the Iron Resolve boulder. Use cool vertical iron features to climb the short slab.

name: Jane Doe
description: Same start as John Doe, but after establishing yourself beneath the roof, climb to the right and out the imposing bulge. Big holds and some air under your feet.

name: John Doe
description: Semi-reminiscent of Dial 911 at Rocktown, only easier. Start beneath the large overhanging boulder at the shore line on the lowest large pocket jugs. Pull on and climb up and left, surmounting the roof and climbing the steep face using "choose your hold" tactics.

name: John Doe Traverse
description: Start the climb around the corner from Jane Doe, as far right as you can on the long, low, flat edge. One of the cruxes is not dabbing at the beginning.  Traverse the face, and move around the arete and finally finish with John Doe.  Super great/pumpy climb for the area.

name: LEDGEnd of Salt Fork
description: A few different routes on this one. Can climb up the side ​where there's a crack, or can start on the side and traverse left onto the ledge and top out.

name: Lichen It
description: Climb up tallest part of boulder to top out for a beautiful view.

name: Photo Op
description: Clean arete face with a beautiful background for that perfect photo opportunity. Sit start low on two pockets right side of arete. Utilize crimps and pockets to climb straight up the arete to an easy top out.

name: Rock and Roll Fantasy
description: Sit start and pull a high foot and continue straight up until the top out. Avoid the aretes.

name: The Roost
description: Pull past a hand ledge and navigate big pockets to an easy top out. Try not to disturb the bird nests!

name: Tom Clancy Traverse
description: Traverse the jugs Splinter Cell style. Work your way up to and top out to the right of Jane Doe

name: Chem Trails
description: Use "natural" features only. The crux is the last move before the top. Top out to finish. It's definitely more friendly to lengthier folk. If you don't use the slopey jug rail on the right a few feet above the start holds it's a bit harder.

name: Cling in the New Year
description: This "all natural" (no plastic holds) problem starts on the back face of the bouldering arch.    Start/finish (see picture): Hands start on the torso-height ledge and left side-pull in a low crouch. Follow the edge of the arch up to the bomber finish hold about a foot above the arch's apex.

name: The High Five
description: Natural features only. For the 5.10b grade, the route must be climbed without using the arête to the left or the crack to the right. Start on the face, left of the crack on the south end side of the wall. Work through the first couple of reachy holds to some thin leaning crimps. Pull through the crux about two thirds of the way up to a balanced finish at the anchors.

name: Jeni's Double Dip
description: The crack climb at the wall. The two cracks are a little uncommon because they flare out on the inside allowing for fist stacking and even full arm jams. Proving to be for fun experimentation as well as technical crack climbs. The crux is actually at the top just past the last bolt making it difficult to clip the top anchors without using the holds.

name: Long Distance Relationship
description: Climb 'all natural' (not using any attached holds) and without the door on the traverse. Start on the north/northeast side of the boulder (indicated with the start hold picture) on the undercling and the jug. Then, start the traverse around the corner. From the corner, stay low and continue traversing to the arch.  Climb the arch and down climb to the nice undercling rest. Then traverse under the arch and begin up the other side of the arch to the somewhat high finish. This climb takes some endurance!  I'm just trying to give climbers some more difficult options at Scioto Audubon, because it can be hard to identify new lines. I am very new to developing/grading routes, so please comment your suggestions for difficulty because I could have completely missed the mark.   This is a really great longer project if you climb at scioto a lot!

name: Middle Spire
description: Start near the left side of the small arch on two pinches and make it back to the same start! This problem is easier to do when the auto-belays have been taken down. Take a no-hands rest near the easy auto-belay halfway through and get ready to get low and make it under the arch to the finish.

name: Peek-a-Boo
description: Start on the boulder spire, on the obvious ledge where you climb up to set up ropes. Climb under the arch and work up the slight overhang to a top-out using only natural features. Crux for me was the transition from the arch to the face. Don’t have any grading experience so I‘d love to hear what others think, although I haven’t seen many others try this specific route.

name: Saturday at The Shoe
description: Long pumpy route over the large arch of the wall. Its a good climb for endurance but not too heavy on the technical climbing aspect. Primary done with holds but always interested to see if someone can complete it with just features/natural (it would definitely increase the difficulty without holds).

name: The Thurmanator
description: One of the most difficult climbs at the wall when only using the natural formation. The crux is definitely between bolt 3 and 4. Without giving too much beta the main lines run up the bolts as well as a full arm length to the right of the bolts.

name: Afternoon Delight
description: Far right, through a ravine with a small waterfall, up a choss pile to a small landing. Only large enough for one pad (with another small pad folded under the back for support) and one spotter. Watch for choss on the top out as the hill has a lot of runoff!

name: Bat Crack
description: Use the obvious finger crack and few other small features. Try to stay in the crack as much as possible. Watch for bats about chest high. I skip the crack there and choose to crimp a bit higher to let the little creatures sleep in peace.

name: Dos Doggos
description: On the left face of the boulder. Stand start using a left hand undercling, right hand on a small crimp. Stand up into the first long reaching move into a right hand pocket, just right of a book size slot (slot is off unless absolutely need due to height). Left hand to a good slope pocket above. Establish high feet. Tops out directly above.

name: Dunk’n
description: On the right side of the same small bluff the holds Lowball Rave and Crackbaby.

name: Inches and Fractions
description: Hefty compression problem. Solid problem from beginning to end.

name: Jedi Smoke Tricks
description: Start low on the arete. Pull through the crux in the first few moves to a nice small rail on the corner of the arete. Continue up the arete and out to some jugs before pulling the last couple heady moves out under and over the nose to top out.

name: Lowball Rave
description: From Near Death Experience (directly across from the yellow hydrant on 666 at the pin) hike uphill to the right about 150yds. First line on the left at the top of the ridge with a landing built on the left.

name: Near Death Experience
description: Big flake line on some ok stone. From the North parking area by the guardrail, hike south about 400 yards on the road. Upon reaching a yellow hydrant, hike up hill and slightly left. It’s the closest large boulder to the road.

name: Something Fuky
description: Left from Near Death Experience about 250yrds with a log stack landing.

name: Squeezebox
description: Stand start on left side-pull and right arete. Squeeze up the prominent feature to the ledge. Drop off or traverse left to downclimb.

name: Weagle Leed
description: Sit start, far left, on the large boulder. Start matched on a large shelf about thigh high. Right Heel hook with your matched hands, move hand left. Using a series of fair crimps, work your way to standing on the right foot on the large shelf. Work up the small holds and techy movement until you reach a big black bulb of rock. From there the climbing eases and it’s a walk to the top.

name: 1886 Arete
description: The left nose behind the large sycamore tree.

name: After Hours
description: Start on Dynoman and head straight up and slightly left after the opening boulder problem.  The route finishes with crimping at a bit of spice to keep your attention.

name: DynoMan
description: “If you can’t reach, just dyno man” By far the most climbed line at Mollies. Usually shaded and dry even in sub prime conditions.  Grade is height dependent.   Consider pulling through the first moves to use a a warm up or if it you are on the shorter side to enjoy the rest of the moderate route that is 5.9ish.

name: Fat Dudes & Mopeds
description: This is easiest route at Mollies and probably the only one without too much of a low crux though it does require a bit of a reach or good footwork.  Traverse the slab to the left to the first bolt.  Continue up through a couple of tough moves to gain a stance.  Finish up on easier terrain to the anchors.

name: Feet of Clay
description: Start on Dynoman and after pulling the initial crux trend left to the line of bolts right of the arete.  Climb to the ledge, clip high and then get ready to make a few sequential moves up and left to the anchors.  Alternative start: Stick clip the second bolt and then start on 1886 arete.   Put a directional on the first bolt of 1886 arete and pull it as you traverse to the right.

name: Highway to Hell
description: Climb through some excellent movement on the slightly overhanging face to a good rest before the roof and catch your breath.  When ready, launch into a full body length roof where good footwork will help.  Finish with a burly mantle to a no hands stance at the anchors.  Most decide its probably better not to clip them to save your rope, take the whip and then clean the lower draws on TR.

name: Impaler
description: Far left in the corner. Watch for broken glass and choss! Big ledge marked with X is off (the impaler ledge).

name: Kill Shot
description: Big moves the whole way! Control the pump!

name: Ohio Climbing Disorder (aka OCD)
description: The steepest route at Mollies and it packs a punch for the 40 feet of climbing.  Enter in from the slab under the roof and reach out to some pockets at the lip.  Grab the jug and cut feet to pull on to the face.  Climb the steep face where a bouldery crux awaits.  Originally sent directly through the bolt line, an easier version traverses just right of the line at the 3rd bolt skipping the hardest moves and goes at 12a.  Finish up on jugs to the anchors.

name: Pussy
description: Great dynamic and powerful problem! Sadly defaced by some punk kids, but simple to spot and quick to be named. Fairly sustained. Hard moves from the beginning to the end!

name: Shake & Bake
description: Start at the edge of the roof about 10 feet to the right of the arete. Climb through the overhanging face with a smack down crux going to the anchors just waiting to deny your send.

name: The Wave
description: Great traversing/switchbacking line with awesome features. Small feet on some questionable rock. Just remember to use those feet! A high foot with a low gastone right hand make for an exciting crux move!

name: Amoeba
description: Mushroom shaped boulder with two gems! Don’t forget to set your feet up to make the long reach over the lip to a half pad crimp!

name: Background Radiation
description: Underneath all the white noise is cosmic background radiation. Same start and finish as the burly V8, but stay low. Work through the side pulls and crimps to the powerful top out.

name: Bat Magic
description: Start on a head high hueco and traverse left into Voodoo.  Move into the crack whenever possible and top out.

name: Big Tex
description: Behind the Crimp City boulder is this large jug filled wall of fun holding all kinds of interesting problems. The most obvious, Big Tex. A favorite of children and beginners, but not for the faint of heart. The airy top out brings little security at close to 20ft off the deck and I have personally watched ankles snap from this route. Pad that shit up and don’t forget the spotter if you’re unsure! No shame in keeping your ankles together.

name: Boombox
description: Sit start, big semi narrow left hand pinch with a left heal hole slightly under it, right hand in an orange sopey slot. Power right hand to a good sloper, left to a wide pinch. Stand into the large hueco and top out on some fair slopers.

name: Cold Toast
description: Sit start on the far right. Traverse the rail of jugs and slopers toward the tree growing around the rock. Find a few good holds through the large hueco, topping out on slopers just right of the tree.

name: Crimp City
description: At the top of the approach trail, left of the tree growing around the rock. Sit start under the colorful orange and black nose using pinches and horrid pockets for undercut feet. Work the low crux of crimps, pinches and awkward movement over the nose. Once mantling onto the nose step out high left on the steep ramp to some dark jugs leading to the top and friendly crimps.

name: Fireball
description: Right from White Noise, start in a small side pull. Work into a small iron slot with a right crimp, left working the arete. Top out is mildly heady with small holds to top out.

name: Jeffs Arete
description: Right of the tree, small log landing. Fun line with a lot of variation.

name: Jeff’s Thingy
description: Right most line on the Big Tex boulder.

name: Lil’ Tex
description: Behind the Crimp City boulder is a nice jug filled wall full of fun!! The most obvious line going up this wall has a large hueco that is kinda shaped like Texas. From this, we got Big Tex...from this, we got Lil’ Tex. The much less obvious line using only small mono pockets, crimps, the smallest chips for feet and nothing else. Make it as complicated as possible. Have fun!

name: Longhorn
description: Far left line on the Big Tex boulder.

name: Longhorn Direct
description: The slab to the left of Big Tex. Stand start with your hands in the low pockets. Find your feet up the slab to mantle off the high knob. Proceed up the low angle slab to walk off the back of the boulder.

name: Mad D Batteries
description: Sit start under large hueco, left hand pinch right hand flat ledge, pull up and through the hueco, bring a high left foot to mantle up and then walk the easy top out

name: Off The Handlebars
description: Start off on two large handholds that have a few okay ways to be held, feet start on a rail to the left and a dish to the right. Work your way to the right through a series of side pulls on the handlebars while walking your feet along below you. Reach for a solid undercling in the big pocket. Find an okay sloper for your left hand, pop up to the slot with your right and get good feet. Reach for the book-sized pinch and pull yourself up using the tension between your right foot and hand. Get a foot out to the right and pull yourself over to the ledge and walk-up the finish to the right.

name: Pimp City
description: Sit start on two good angled slopers, with feet on the semi crumbly orange and black rail below. The entire jug rail is OFF. Crux- Power to a rail center face, establish feet. Stand up using two small holds in a seam just above. Tops out straight to a small rail and slopers.

name: Randy Traverse
description: Behind Big Tex is the coolest lowball of all lowball traverses. Low and short, crux is keeping your ass off the ground.

name: Snail Rail
description: Middle line up the Big Tex bloc. Have your wits together as you pull over the mantle and onto the ramp.

name: Through The City
description: Start on the right far right of the boulder, traverse left and then up when you hit the big hueco, top out

name: Voodoo
description: Really fun line up a long sloper rail. Condition dependent!

name: White Noise
description: Like slopers? Come get some. There are three known methods to climb this boulder.   The OG beta- Stand start using a left hand side pull sloper, right hand pinching  bowling ball hole like pockets, feet on small chips. Throw to the victory jug out left to top out. The Low stand- start with left hand on a sidepulling sloper, just above a small knob. Right hand far right on the arete. Bump right hand high on a very steep sloper with a tiny dish, full compression, bump left hand up to an open hand crimp and one more time to the victory jug.

name: White Noise Sit
description: Sit start on the low left side of the boulder. Using a right hand side pulling crimp, a left hand pocket jug and solid feet on the shelf below, stand up to a small incut slot with a slopper on the outside. Traverse left, crossing the bowling ball pinch. The crux begins when you’re set up directly under the steep sloper. Right hand on the arete, left on a side pulling sloper above a small knob. Set feet, Power the right hand into the sloper, bump the left hand up to a good open hand crimp, collect and throw further up left to the victory jug. Tops out with a small foot chip just under the jug a bit.

name: Afroman Project
description: Start under the roof with your left hand in the pocket and your right out on the arete just below the tree. Climb straight out the roof however you can.You might want to tape your pinky up for this one. The big move to the pocket feels like a jam when you hit it and feels a little sharp on the pinky. Feels fine with tape on.

name: Nae Nae's Belly Button
description: Start low with a right hand on a small knob and a left on the slopey feature. Make a few smeary moves up the slab avoiding the holds on the surrounding aretes.

name: Slam Dunk
description: Start on lowest holds on face. Climb obvious line of weakness through jugs and sidepulls, making a fun move to the large round hold before topping out.

name: Wind Chimes
description: Start low on the arete and climb it till it runs out. Avoid stepping onto the slab when topping out. Tops out just to the right of Slam Dunk.

name: The Big Easy
description: Start as low as possible on the arete. Climb it till it ends and top out.

name: Pip Squeak
description: Start with one hand on each side of the chip and a right heel hook down low on the arete. Climb the arete till it ends and top out.Amazing technical sloper arete. This little bugger packs in close to 10 moves from start to finish and is most likely unclimbable on warm days. Best thing here in my opinion.

name: Pip Squeak Jr.
description: Start the same as Pip Squeak but top out early using the undercling rail on the slab just beneath the chip.

name: Easy A
description: Climb the flake's crack to the top. A slight overhang makes it fun.

name: The farmer says ow
description: Not sure who bolted this route but adding it since it isn’t listed on Mountain project. This is the second of the two bolted routes on this wall. This is the right-hand route while facing the wall. This route has fairly solid holds and is bolted about every 5 feet. it has 6 bolts and triple bolted anchor. The hardest move is the ledge to the roof. Not positive of the rating but it feels 5.10 ish, please adjust as you see fit.

name: Real boy
description: The left most of the two bolted routes in this area. I do not know who bolted this or when, looks to be put up within the last year. I'm adding it since the area is not showing any sport routes. Feel free to change if you are the bolter. The route felt like a 5.10 but feel free to adjust if you feel otherwise. This route was very sandy and did not feel comfortable trusting hands or feet. Bolts are solid regardless of how sandy the rock feels.

name: Beneath The Bow
description: Start on two small knobs and make a big move to the eye socket, match, turn it unto a undercling and figure out how to go underneath the small roof with some tricky toe/heel hook beta  and then up the vertical face on the other side using the arete and good crimps.

name: Killroy
description: Start on same knobs and low insecure heel hook as "Beneath the Bow". Make a tricky body tension move to a bad thumb-pinch sloper. Use intermediates to and bring feet up to get to big undercling in order to set up for the crux to the hidden jugs several feet up.   Good jug over the lip. Careful topping out on this one.

name: Warm Up
description: Start with left on crimp and right hand/heel hook match. The crux is making the first two moves. Good crimps, just maybe too small for a newbie. After the crimps, reach for the huge jugs and make an easy top-out.

name: Far for the Short
description: Stand start on crimps with very good feet. Work your way up sculpted crimps/ledges until the holds obvious holds disappear. Use a small side-pull crimp to keep balance and bring a very high left foot up about hip height, rock over and carefully go for the lip.  (Avoid topping out left on the huge jug)

name: Una Pierna
description: Start low with a left hand on the lowest crimp and a right on a diagonal crimp. Use slopers and underclings to reach a shallow pocket. Figure out beta to get a nearly chest height foot and stand off that one leg(crux) to then finish by climbing the slab.

name: Red Fox
description: start in low pockets, climb up the overhang, and traverse out left near the top

name: 2 Pump Chump
description: Under long hand start a long with a single left footLeft hand to crimpRight hand topSolid right foot top out

name: Cheese Grator
description: FLAT slab of iron deposit thats at an 85 degree angle, couple of nipple pinch crimps, with lots of jugs at the top.   DONT FALL YOUR KNEES WILL BE SHREDDED LIKE CHEESE

name: Crackhead Clam
description: 3 moves but i like it!   top out is funky

name: Diagains Alley
description: That right toe clingAnd that right hand, right angled edge with pulling pressure feels so good

name: DYNOmite
description: start on smaller boulder and dyno left to ledge that has 1 jug and rest sloper

name: Gieco CaveMans Cave
description: crimp left hand start   top out is rough...   heel hook up or mantle.

name: Iron Nipple
description: Knee Bar, Sloppers, Crimp, Side Pull, Heel Hook, Finger Pocket, Long Stretch    This problem has it all    start as low as possible   then Knee Bar the chimney   Nice 2 finger hold far right   Heel hook the iron nipple    DO NOT TOUCH THE OBVIOUS LARGE LEDGE!!!!

name: Kalashnikov
description: side pull match to left hand crimpright heel hook

name: Kick Back Sum Cold Ones
description: Right hand makes 3 jumps up

name: McChicken Circumcision
description: Sit-start on crimply ledge Bump up the arete to a solid hold where you can knee-bar the area between the rocks Use only the left rock for hands, right for feet all the way to the top.

name: Out of the darkness
description: Sit startLeft hand on sloper right hand on crimpBump right hand to Arete with a heel hook right in front of right handget both hands to the top point and top out

name: Shallow Water Dyno
description: nice 2 hand side jug   upper left ledge

name: Tweedle Deah
description: long reach   then a nice heel hook

name: Alter boy
description: The crux is most likely the top out...

name: Baptism of desire AKA Parish Swagger
description: As it is a crack it is entirely finger size dependent.

name: The Cascade Crack
description: a fun short off width crack.  Just a body jam and muscle your way up. once you get the top you get to another flat platform of ground with a very obvious second crack directly in front of you. climb the second crack and top out and walk back down around back.

name: Evasion Invasion
description: A real fun flake going straight up the cliff, the moves are really reachy and fun with alot of side pulls.  You can set up toprope off the tree directly above the route(be careful walking above the cliff the dirt is slanted and loose, also be cognizant of not walking up to high above the cliff into people's backyards) or place some protection in the cracks.  The crux is towards the top of the flake where there is a very long reach to the next possible hand hold.  A bit chossy in some areas but overall a pretty fun route

name: Fractal Fingers
description: really great problem with a lot of possibilities for moves.  Depending on how you move you can make this boulder relatively easy or as hard as you want.

name: Layback King
description: No obvious crux, unless trying to climb up to the tree anchor. Very blank face after the ledge. Climb the obvious, sharp crack. Laybacking will get you to the top ledge. Good feet, good holds, just sharp and dirty. Some moss in the upper part of the crack. Different variation of finishes, I traversed right at the end of the crack.

name: Love Handles
description: A fun crack to the left of the Cascade crack just inside the dihedral.  Not the cleanest rock ever but fun hand and arm jams up the crack to top out.

name: To Lay or Not
description: A bouldery start. Depending on which style of climbing you're more comfortable with, the crux can come early or later. Crack lovers will find the wider crack after the ledge enjoyable, albeit short. Very dirty, hence slippery. This route needs a lot of cleaning.

name: Zigzag
description: A fun very easy diagonal lay back all the way up to the top.  once you reach the top top out and climb over the edge and use the holes on the backside to get back down.

name: The Club
description: It is only ~9ft high .. just don't fall wildly as some people have tweaked their ankles in this fashion.

name: Crack Traverse
description: start at far left side of crack and traverse up and right to high point of boulder.

name: Ibuprofen
description: blockey left hand with sit start. Slap up to the big sloping top and mantle.This problem can be very frustrating for the open-hand challenged.

name: Ball Breaker
description: two crimps to the top.

name: Mr Hero
description: Not hitting the tree and successfully pulling off the mantle.   --   Start on the high crimps and work to dyno into the large diagonal hold. Reach to the lip and mantle the slab to top. Scary because falling from the mantle would land you on the horizontal tree. Repeated once.

name: Seams Easy
description: Finding it .. The rock is good, though it probably could use a cleaning.

name: Easy Sleazy
description: start on a flake left pinch and obvious right hand placement right toe then pop straight up to the first ledge then a nice heal hook to pop to the next ledge

name: Grey Paint
description: Follow underclings and edges next to seam, large moves punctuate the top of the boulder.

name: Lumberjack
description: Find the line of bolts on the far end of the boulder. Around the corner, climb up through the marginal face holds to the top, avoiding the arete

name: On the Cross
description: use up above stars and bars up until second rail then go straight up the highest point of the boulder of this side of the arête

name: Pulp Enema
description: Look right of the grey paint seam and find the arete next to the water with the broken tree at the base. Climb on.

name: Slap Chip
description: Start seated on the right side and traverse around to the beauty slopers out left. Throw up to the chip and mantle.

name: Stars and Bars
description: Sit start to grey paint, start on the left arete and move low to the right into the start of grey paint

name: Up above the stars and bars
description: Sit start with a knee bar for the first move following the arete up about four feet to the start of the line of crimp running to the right to a crack in the boulder topping out on what i think are the last sequences to stars and bars

name: Imaginary Line
description: Start on the Hogshead hold and chuck way up and left to finger jug edge on the slab. Finish up the slab, but carefully. 27'

name: Jiveturkey
description: Start at the left side of the wall, hugging thin edges and finish up through crimps to slappy finish

name: Orogeny
description: Find the angular platter size block on the right end of the long boulder.

name: Sophie Incarcerated
description: Start in the vary shallow arete and follow up to the dyno finish.

name: Whiskey/Ginger
description: dihedral climb it and top out to the right

name: Jailbreak
description: Use the 2 crimps to gain the upsidedown T shape then dyno to top. Manufatured by the quarrymen, but surprisingly good.

name: Kill La Kill
description: Crux is trusting the constantly wet feet and gaining a higher jam. The crack is always a bit dirty, but is good enough for a jam

name: Quagmire
description: nice warm up

name: Sex & the City
description: overhung angular prow- start on corner sidepull and left hand gastone- up to edge and mantle

name: Can't finish the salad
description: Crux is finding good feet

name: Half-n-half ladies
description: The route, a crack route. Its right near the waterfall so its often wet. there is opportunity to extend the route to have an overhang involved in the start. It is sandstone so careful of the possibility of broken holds. The crux: prob the 1st and 2nd moves. Otherwise its a finger and hand crack

name: A Summertime Christmas
description: Start on the lowest flat sloped ledge. Continue up  blocky slopers to top out. A bit dirty, and could use some traffic, but fun movement!

name: An 8th of Crack
description: Sit Start with hands jammed in vertical crack big move out to overhanging crack to top out.

name: The Arrow of Light
description: Split start with right hand just below crescent shaped indent on the right arete, and left hand on a poor slopey ledge low on the face. Work up the right arete using the obivous slopy crimp in the center of the boulder near the top.

name: Arrow's Edge
description: Work your way up the left side arete of the boulder using the obvious incut feature in the middle to start on.

name: The Arrowhead
description: Starts the same as "The Arrow of Light", but eventually bumps out to the indent feature of the left side. Finish by riding both aretes in a compression to the top. May be harder for people under 5ft. 7.

name: Big Sky
description: Start low on crimps to throw out to jug on arete to topout.

name: Bonsai
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Boyscout
description: Start with right hand on corner of the arete where there should be a crimp, and the left hand on the obvious pinch in the center. Work you way through both aretes to a juggy topout. The starting foot may have to be dug out, as it can get washed over with sand.

name: Cig Arete
description: Same start as "hallucinogens", but move out right to the lip, then work your way up the slab.

name: Eco Terrorist
description: Start on left hand undercling then move up sparse crimps to large lock off move to the top crimp

name: The EGG
description: SDS left hand on thin undercling, right hand on arete. bump right hand up arete and hope you have good foot work and core strength to keep yo feet on, left hand throws out to the flat corner of boulder, keep compression and launch for the lip with your left hand. top out

name: Feets of Contortion
description: Start low on jugs on far left side of boulder and move up to a slabby topout.

name: The Gymnasium
description: Start at the obvious jug down in the little cave. Climb up and out to a moderately tall but easy top out.

name: Hallucinogenics
description: Start on the two holds down in the crack and work your way up To the mail slot. Then stand and smear to the top.

name: Honey Mustard
description: Start on the first right hand of Los Nuggets. Traverse right to a small ledge, bring the left hand into a pinch, then throw to the arete. Follow the arete to a top out.

name: Hurtful Things
description: To the right of Thugged Out Since Cub Scouts.  Starts under a low roof and climbs out and straight up small crimps.

name: Hypocrite
description: Crouch start with your left hand in a good slot/crimp/rail down in the roof and your right hand on a bad undercling crimp near the lip. Work your right hand up the arete, find your footing, climb up and top out. FA by Dave Schultz in March of 2019

name: Icebergs Away
description: Start the same as "A Summertime Christmas", but traverse out left on sloping ledges. Continue up to the top on more slopers. Could use traffic, but it will clean up nicely.

name: Indian Guides
description: The double handed sloper matchLeft handed crimp jug to top

name: Jackie Chan
description: Climb right arête

name: Left Sauna
description: Start left side of boulder on crimps make way to topout.

name: Leopard Slug
description: Start on the left side slopey crimps, traverse right to the prow and top out.

name: Locker Room
description: Start low in the Gymnasium cave, once you hit the lip move left through the sidepulls until you're under the slab, get a high right foot on the only thing there and work the last two or three moves up the slab

name: Los Nuggets
description: Sit start on 2 crimpy edges, go straight up.

name: Money Moves
description: Sit start, climb directly up the arete.  Really nice climb- juggy and overhung. Crux is the endurance required to top out, as this is a long route.  Friendly reminder to wipe your shoes thoroughly before getting on any boulder! The ground beneath this boulder is rather muddy and the starting foot holds are caked with mud.  climbchippewa.com/problem/m…

name: Monkey Swing
description: start down and right on face, move left through slopers, and very crappy feet, right hand to good roof rail, match and go right to sloper lip, continue one move right and mantle up

name: Perfect Sunday
description: Start on the obvious chalked jug, continue up and left through a pocket in a thin seam to the lip. CAREFULLY rock over the lip. Hike all the way up the slab to the top, and down climb off the back.

name: Plans to Commit Arson
description: Start on campusing crimps to high top out.

name: The Poo Arete Left
description: A very fun eliminate on the Poo Arete. Start the same as the V2, and avoid the Jug you usually dyno to, and instead go left on crimps and sloping ledges.

name: The POO arete
description: start low and left matched on good rail smear feet on and work holds to the right and set up for super fun dyno to top    WARNING: Ladder in picture is now broken therefore down climb is a bit more sketchy.

name: Power Ranger
description: Start low in deep pocket, move through intermediates to the crimp crack and high left crimp, deadpoint to lip. Topout is kinda spooky

name: Right Sauna
description: Start on obvious big rail and move up to topout.

name: The Rollout Traverse
description: Start at the left most crimps under the Rollout roof, with a far far left high foot. Traverse right keeping your feet in front of you. Just before rounding the arete, grab the lip and top out.

name: The Rollout
description: Start at arete with right hand on the right arete, and left hand on left facing sidepull. Get a heel hook on the right, and cross to the lip. Ride the lip left to "Rollout" on the slopey section of it.

name: Shelving Unit
description: Very easy edge traverse route. Only about 10ft long. Top out.

name: Space nuggets
description: Start the same as Los nuggets, but finish by moving out right instead of going straight up.

name: The Star Arete
description: Start on obvious right hand undercling-sidepull, and left hand on bad crimp. Bump left up to a good hold, proceed to the lip.

name: Thugged Out Dyno
description: feels like your face is going to cheese grate the wall but your goodsolid top ledge

name: Thugged Out Since Cub Scouts
description: Start low on underclings to lockoffs to topout.

name: Unnamed 2
description: Easier version of Feets of Contortion

name: Bruce Lee
description: Prow at The Hanger with the high stand start (has a sloping rail for the left hand).  Get on, squeeze and make one move to the jug (or bump your hands up through nothing holds).  Top out.

name: FingertipLip Traverse
description: From left to Right, has an incredible edge for flat finger crimps, schmeary feet, some good blade and features to get toes onto. You can make some nice movements.

name: Hang line
description: Scramble up easy moves to the obvious roof crack, climb crack out roof 12ft to big move at the lip and few easy moves on the head wall to easy top out

name: illusions of bouldering
description: What rating do you call an undercling jug, with schmeary feet, traverse to a couple fun reachy feet right, and back up for lots of fingertips? LMK  There is room for to progress past this and enjoy more difficult climbing.

name: illusions of grandeur
description: Start under roof on obvious jug, pull up to slopey feature, try to climb feature to thin crimps to a jug top out

name: No Chomos
description: Big undercling start hold at waist height, move right to crimps in face, long move to slimper over lip and jump to the slopey ledge. Easy but dirty topout.  Not sure of the grade but it took me many more tries than the egg or illusions.

name: ill communication
description: SDS left, climb sloper lip and holds up and right, feet are sparse, so hold on tight!

name: [Redacted]
description: Up left arete to topout.

name: Brick Work
description: Crimps to jug top out    the wall oozes iron deposits and looks like the mortar for bricks    (please leave comment if name is wrong)

name: Bunny Slab
description: Climb the little slab on the back of the Bonsai boulder. Easy but would be crimpy and technical for a newbie.

name: Core Sample
description: The feet work, thumb catch and top out ooooof

name: Drill bit
description: Start left hand side cling, right hand in quarry drill slotMatch, move left hand to crimp, bump up to v pocket ledgeMove right foot to left foot, Move right foot up close to areteMatch hands on side pull ledge and send it upNice jug on top

name: Fight or Flight
description: Hitting the sloper on a low gravity day and a lower humidity day.

name: The Gem
description: Finding it, since in all likely scenarios, the base of this is washed out for a while ..

name: Heel Hook
description: Start low and to the far right of the boulder using the rail to traverse towards the arete. Move up the arete to top out.

name: Key Hole
description: dont forget to toe cling the arete

name: Left Handed S.O.B
