description: Start in an undercling on the center of the boulder, then traverse through another unercling and small to almost non-existant sloping crimps out to the arete where you finish off by linking with "Left Handed Whore"

name: LIMee Hole
description: Start low on side pulls/pinches to top.

name: Lumberjack
description: Traversing problem on a sloping edge to an easy topout.  Start on far right of boulder.

name: Lumberjack  3
description: Sit-down start on the obvious sharp pocket on the bottom left of the lumberjack boulder, with very low feet. Line goes up to the small rail then merges with Lumberjack SDS on the right after some creative footwork.     DON'T GRAB THE ROCKS ON TOP OF THE BOULDER.

name: Lumberjack SDS
description: Sit start in the center of the boulder and reach up to very small holds to balance your way to the sloping edge.

name: Mother Goose - Warm Up V0
description: Fairly juggy but extremely fun and good warm up.     Perfect place to bring new outdoor boulders to learn how to spot, climb, and top out safely.     Several slightly harder routes and 2 fairly harder routes.     Down climb can be a bit tricky but throw a pad down and you should be golden.

name: Pinch Arete
description: Avoid catching your ankle in the crack and missing / not committing to the move to the sloper.

name: Prickly Pickle
description: This route is directly above Key Hole Boulder. Start from the ground and use leg bracing to make your way up. You can top out on this route and walk back down to the start area. Moss can be slippery, be careful.

name: Raining in Bleautimore
description: Start big left hand side-pull, right hand sloper.    Big reach to small crimp (avoid using the drill slot),    move right hand to other sloping crimp,    reach to lip and do the tenuous top-out.    v2-3 depending on height and style.    Good variations exist: from start head slightly right and up,    using an undercling at mid-wall height (slightly easier, v1/2).

name: Spaceneedle
description: Sit start with left hand on crimp and right in CD slot, move up using the little arête and the big smile

name: Spider Pocket
description: Start and move in pockets to topout.

name: Takeoff
description: An eliminate on the "flight" boulder. The same undercling start, but go straight from the left hand pinch on up to the top jug, eliminating the middle right hand

name: Thin to win
description: Start in an undercling (the same one as "Left Handed S.O.B", but farther to the right), then move straight up on small crimps and smeary feet to a crimp rail right before the lip. Traverse out left to some really good hidden holds over the top lip of the boulder. Be sure to clean off the top really well as it gets dirty very easily.

name: Unknown
description: Sit Start on rail to topout.

name: Unknown 2
description: Start fart left on ledge go right to rails and jugs to topout where mantis does.

name: Unnamed 3
description: Underclings lead to matching sloper to topout.

name: Unnamed 4
description: Easy jug haul to the top of the boulder.  Most dangerous part is topping-out.

name: Blood Gnome (Sit Start)
description: Sit Start to crimps up.

name: Blood Gnome (Stand Start)
description: Start on undercling or crimps to up.

name: Boo Ya Arete
description: Start on low jug, up arete.

name: Cess pool
description: SDS on sloper, through up to slopey lip and climb the slopey arete up and right 8ft then top out

name: Cincinnati Party God
description: Start with a left hand side pull and right hand undercling on tricky feet. Work the left side of the arete to throw into a powerful right hand side pull. Then, try to avoid being spit off this dirty rock when going for the next crimp.

name: Militant Recht
description: Desperate times. Same start as Racist, but trends right climbing the face only (left arete off) and exits with a punch out right to a large horn. There's room for another compression variant to the right for those with albatross wingspans.

name: Racist Arete
description: Sit start on arete and right crimp and on up.

name: The Rib
description: Start on flat ledges of the lower rail down to the right, and work your way up the arete using an undercling/ sidepull on the roof side to get to the top.

name: Unnamed Dyno 1
description: Two big jugs chest height to big move to top.

name: Warmup
description: Start on upstream side of Racist Arete boulder and top out on jugs and edges.

name: Calculus
description: Rock is pretty dry even in rain.    Latitude: 41° 7' 14.87" N   Longitude: 81° 29' 22.65" W

name: Darrow the red
description: The crux is lower, pulling longer moves on sharp crimps, the climb eases as you continue higher, don't blow the moves up top. The rock quality is terrific on this one.

name: Diamond in the Rough
description: Not yet climbed.    Latitude: 41° 7' 12.6" N   Longitude: 81° 29' 29.268" W

name: Diff EQ
description: Rock is pretty dry even with rain.    Latitude: 41° 7' 16.28" N   Longitude: 81° 29' 22.23" W

name: Flatface
description: Not yet climbed.  Pretty dry even with rain.    Latitude: 41° 7' 15.94" N   Longitude: 81° 29' 26.052" W

name: Gates of Heaven
description: Not yet climbed.  Rock can be wet after rain.    Latitude: 41° 7' 29.37" N   Longitude: 81° 29' 13.692" W

name: Geometry
description: Rock is wet after rain.    Latitude: 41° 7' 13.96" N   Longitude: 81° 29' 27.012" W

name: Hang On!
description: Probably unsafe due to unstable rock above.    Latitude: 41° 7' 3.32" N   Longitude: 81° 29' 34.92" W

name: Iron Woodle
description: Rock can be wet in rain.    Latitude: 41° 7' 15.87" N   Longitude: 81° 29' 22.512" W

name: Ironface
description: Not yet climbed.    Latitude: 41° 7' 27.23" N   Longitude: 81° 29' 16.818" W

name: Junebug
description: Rock is a little wet after rain.    Latitude: 41° 7' 14.96" N   Longitude: 81° 29' 25.638" W

name: Long Walk
description: Boulder traverse    Latitude: 41° 7' 12.61" N   Longitude: 81° 29' 28.362" W

name: Off the deck
description: Right line. The route shares the same start with "Rivers Run" from here chug out right through a bad slope rail or a very large committing move to a crimp follow this to the top right corner.

name: Pedestrian life
description: Start on the same holds as Typical Boulder beta, trend right and out of the roof along the right side. After the start hope your foot sticks and you're accurate on your bumps, otherwise the ground for you. Once you get established on the right of the roof continue up the sandy dirty ledges to the top.

name: Peerless Scarred
description: A pristine route through and through, the climbing is relentlessly delicate. The crux is low but the entire route will keep you guessing on the send.

name: Rivers Run
description: Fun problem start on a ledge and make a large lock off move to a good crimp rail, match the rail and finish on the jugs up top. River Run is the left line.

name: Sling Blade
description: Rock quality is good, delicate moves about the arete. Fun climbing all and all.

name: Texas!
description: Rock can be a bit wet in rain.    Latitude: 41° 7' 15.76" N   Longitude: 81° 29' 23.958" W

name: To the Depths
description: The crux is a small crimp rail at 3/4 height. If you fall here, you are falling to a ledge 10' down or the depths about a 25-30' fall. It would be wise to brush the route and suss it on TR first...

name: Trigonometry
description: Rock is wet after rain.    Latitude: 41° 7' 14.43" N   Longitude: 81° 29' 25.23" W

name: Triple left
description: Good jamming, leads to a ledge, down-climb or drop from ledge. Surprisingly great rock quality.

name: Triple Middle
description: Begin up Triple Right and finish on Triple Left, avoiding the top crux of Triple Right.

name: Triple Right
description: Only use the right crack, hard up top.

name: Tuck Everlasting
description: Probably not safe due to unstable rock above.    Latitude: 41° 7' 28.2" N   Longitude: 81° 29' 15.972" W

name: Two Face
description: A little boulder problem.    Latitude: 41° 7' 12.71" N   Longitude: 81° 29' 29.73" W

name: Two-Step
description: Rock can be wet in rain.    Latitude: 41° 7' 16.78" N   Longitude: 81° 29' 22.212" W

name: Typical bouldering beta
description: Traverse along the base of the roof, is it a hand-foot match? Start in two forever crumbling holds near the right center of the roof. Stay low? Stay high? Enjoy figuring it out...

name: Unnamed
description: There isn't really a crux on this one, other than the top.

name: Unsafe
description: Probably not safe due to unstable rock.    Latitude: 41° 7' 14.18" N   Longitude: 81° 29' 19.542" W

name: Bobo no more
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Dreaming of the NRG
description: The crux may be getting into the crack. The crack needs cleaned up before the send.

name: Shard Boulder
description: Shard is the red text. Good quality boulder problem, lie back or compression movement to the top.

name: Sliver
description: Sliver is the blue line. The crux is a long move two moves in.

name: Batman
description: Batman is a boulder problem just West of Zorton.  It is named after the small "bat cave" in the center.  Start low and then go high above the cave.

name: Bus Stop
description: Not completed yet.

name: Donatello
description: A short bolder problem looking slightly like the ninja turtle, Donatello.

name: Gamma Ray
description: Gamma Ray is a 50 foot traverse in the center portion of the Secret Sandbox.  The crux is a move to transition from the middle portion pulling a crimp up high with a long reach with your feet to the end.

name: Krak
description: Krak is located in the middle of the South Face.  This is a nice warm spot to climb protected from wind if it is a cold day.

name: Magma
description: None.

name: Momma
description: None.

name: Momma's Booty
description: None.

name: North Face
description: This is a relatively long traverse with a lot of fun options to try.

name: Notebook
description: Notebook is a traverse located just east of North Face.

name: Peanut Butter and Jelly
description: Nice upward traverse.

name: Robin
description: This is a boulder problem just adjacent to Batman.  Starts easy using feet, then a dyno brings you to the end.

name: Secret Sandbox Area
description: Secret sandbox cave is one of the many bouldering spots in Gorge.  It has a lot of traverse bouldering options.  The length of the ledge is about 200 or 300 feet and about 20 to 30 feet high.  It is south facing and gets a lot of sun.  Most parts closer to the ground are dry and without moss.

name: Snapper
description: Not sure.

name: South Face
description: A moderately difficult traverse.  Start is easy, Krak is tougher.    Latitude: 41° 7' 26.4" N   Longitude: 81° 30' 17.412" W

name: Stradivarius
description: Short traverse with lots of options.

name: Triangle
description: Tougher traverse going over small cave.

name: Walk in the Park
description: This is a nice bouldering traverse for beginners or when your arms are tired from the other problems in Secret Sandbox.

name: Warhol area
description: Bouldering route to the left of Secret Sandbox.      Simple green (VB): traverse left to right moving around arete then finish on far right at ledge.      Immaculate Mary (V1+): low start with left hand side pull, right hand to small crimp ledge, traverse right, feet on ledge, heel hook to finish on right ledge.

name: Where the Sidewalk Ends
description: This is a fun boulder problem with close resemblance to "Where the Sidewalk Ends".

name: With Momma I can fall
description: The crux is near the top, getting the correct hands and comfortably downclimbing or falling.

name: With Momma I can fly
description: The crux comes after the crack begins to peter out, before you get established on the crimps up on the headwall. You should be extremely comfortable in the grade if you plan to boulder this, otherwise you can string up a top rope for the route.

name: Zorton
description: Start low on ledge and work your way up hanging and using feet for anchor.

name: Daphodil
description: Sit low with hands on small rail, move high left to another small crack rail, establish good feet and move through the last few intermediate slab moves to the top

name: Geranium
description: Start on waist high jug rail, move right into overhang, reach out of the roof into the crimps on the face and top it out. Watch out for loose sand and rocks

name: Pat's Roof
description: Ledgy steps up to an overhang. Can easily be top roped using trees from above.

name: Pocketsand
description: Start low on left arête sidepull, move right into crimps and up

name: Snapdragon
description: Follow the obvious incut jugs moving from bottom right to the middle top. Good hands bad feet, pretty fun

name: Squid Squad
description: The first few moves are a bit tricky with bad feet. After getting past the start the route is really simple, essentially a ladder with a slightly slabby finish.

name: Super Geranium
description: Start left hand on the top left most pocket in the left side of the boulder and right hand on either of the two pockets about 1.5 feet about the "CTP" carved into the rock, traverse right through the middle section of the rock trying to avoid the extremely massive feet, and eventually finishing on Geranium

name: Just for the Fun of It
description: Fun route with a crux about 1/2 way and an easy finish if you use the correct hold.

name: Practice Route
description: Name says it all.

name: Shining Knight
description: May be some loose rock, has an R rating.

name: Anxiety
description: Start between the 2nd and 3rd drill marks (count the drill marks half way up the climb) from the left on The Left Main Wall. Climb the face along the first two bolts using the drill marks, then pull the mantel under the third bolt. Finish on the ledge.

name: Beam Me Up, Scotty
description: Start at ground level just to the right of the large V-shaped chimney (chimney is about 1/2 way up the climb) on the left side of The Left Main Wall. Climb to a spacious ledge under the V-shaped chimney then climb the wall or corner to the right of the chimney. The first part of this climb was originally known as CAPTAIN KIRK

name: Frodo Lives
description: Follow the bolt line using the arete to the right and drill mark to left as needed. Do not go around the arete. Start by climbing the face, making good use of a few small holds and a drill mark to gain the first bolt. From here, look for some holds to the left and work your way to a stance. Climb up, aiming for a nice horn like jug. Mantle up using the jug and a nice, but small ledge to gain a stance. Make one or two more moves over the blank face to reach the overhang at the top and shuts.

name: Nicholas is a Weenie
description: Start between the 2nd. and 3rd. drillmarks to the left of OPEN BOOK. Climb along the 3rd. drillmark past the 1st. bolt then climb along the drillmark above past the 2nd. and 3rd. bolts

name: Open Book Variation
description: Start under the1st. drillmark to the left of OPEN BOOK.   Climb the lower wall and drillmark, continue along to shuts above OPEN BOOK.

name: The Open Book
description: Start in the obvious right facing inside corner that is located in the center of The Left Main Wall. Climb to the open book, then stem out the open book, continue to anchors.    "Todd McCormick and I were working State of the Artless, so named due to our creative pin scarring a la Jim Bridwell, Todd tried to lead it first, fell from the top of the book, ripped pro and landed in the pond. He suffered compression fractures in his back and as far as I know pretty much quit climbing soon thereafter. I went up later and lead it. The funny part is that the pin scars were not needed after all. A lesson best learned while young." --Sean Cobourn's comments on his first ascent of the Book in June of 1987.    Rich Rice is to be credited for inspiring many others to lead The Open Book in recent years. His 1994 free ascent of the Book was an inspiration to all of the Logtown locals. Rich used small stoppers and sliders to protect the book then a larger cam in the horizontal above, this was the first time that adequate protection had ever been used on the route. To date only a few other climbers have lead the Book on gear.

name: The Quest
description: Start the same as FRODO LIVES. Climb FRODO through the first mantel, step right around the corner, climb to the next good stance, traverse left across the foot ledge under the mailbox slot high on FRODO and climb to the anchors, 45 ft. More like 11a than 10b.

name: Scooby-Doo
description: This route was established in the late 90's and climbs up drill lines to a good left crimp and a big reach to a small ledge and then joins Nichols is a weenie.

name: Shattered Image
description: This route was established in the late 90's and climbs a thin face/arête to a small lip and then shares anchors with The Open Book.

name: Slippery as an Eells
description: Climb to the right of Beam Me Up Scotty, using the bolts on Scotty.

name: Tendinitus
description: Start at the 5th drill mark (count the drill marks half way up the climb) from the left on The Left Main Wall. Climb along the drill mark using tenuous lay-backs to get to a ledge. Finish up on the top wall to get to the Terrace, 45 ft.

name: Coordinate Covalent Bonding
description: This is one of the nicer climbs in the area. I'd recommend stick clipping the first bolt. Climb straight up the arete to gain the first bolt. Continue past 3 more bolts using the arete and face holds on the right of the arete to reach the shuts.

name: Covalent Bonding
description: This is the same climb as Coordinate Covalent Bonding with two exceptions.  1. It starts farther right  2. At 4th bolt go slightly right and then up to the ledge Probably closer to 11a than 10a

name: Dean Was Here
description: Climb the arete and ascend the right side of the overhang, continue to the end of the good rock and then lower down from anchors on FOOTLOOSE AND FINGER FREE.

name: Footloose and Finger Free
description: Right most sport climb on Right Main Wall. Start on the face just to the right of the 1st drillmark, 10 ft left of the left facing inside corner where Dreaming starts.

name: Jesus in Tevas
description: This is another that you probably want to stick clip the first bolt.  Climb up to gain the first bolt.  From here, smear your way up until you can dyno for a great hold (crux).  From here, pass a nice mail slot hold and reach the final face.  2 crimpy holds on the final face allow you to make a reach to the big ledge at the top.  Brush this route if you want a sporting chance of getting it clean.

name: Learning to Fly
description: Climb past the face to gain a blank section. Make a big move to an excellent hold. Make an interesting mantle and head to the large ledge at the top with anchors.

name: Nick of Time
description: Climb up the face, passing a few good shallow horizontal holds to reach a stance.  Make a few slabby moves to reach the 2nd bolt to the right of the small overhang.  Make some reachy moves using some slopping holds to gain a stance above the overhang.   Continue on easier terrain for a few moves to reach the anchors.

name: Nightmare's Right Side
description: This route is located on the far right side of the right wall and climbs passed 3 bolts on a short textured wall to Broadway Ledge and shares anchors with Spock Lives.

name: Spock Lives
description: From the guidebook:    Start between the start of DREAMING and NIGHTMARE. Climb stemming out between the two vertical surfaces of the wall on the left and the dihedral on the right to Broadway Ledge, 20 ft.

name: A Little Something
description: A Little Something 5.9- Starts right off the ground with a solid jug in the lip of the drill line and follows a few thin moves to a two finger pocket in the drill line and a high step and throw to the ledge. once to the ledge easy climbing to the ring anchors.

name: Always Saturday
description: Climbs up a few good holds to a long reach to a good crimp at the base of the drill line in a obvious corner / book, From this point pull you feet up high to a good ledge and find a few good crimps on both sides of the small corner / book. Many options from this point right a little, left a little or straight up all lead to a mantel with great protection and easy climbing to the anchors.

name: Beach Party
description: Start to the left of the pit and its the second bolted route. under a light band of rock, climb straight up following bolts. First crux is getting to Broadway Ledge. Second crux is the blank face about mid way, small footholds and hands on a ledge to match on, power up to reach a good handhold and finish route. Note: 2001 Guidebook has it rated as a 5.6. Over the winter (2014/15) a block sluffed off and eliminated a foothold making the crux harder.

name: Block Party
description: Start at the flake between 7th and 8th drill marks to the left of the pit. Climb the flake up to the big ledge. Continue straight up to ring bolts.  Route is well protected with good stances for clipping.  Crux is the start on the flake, smear and stem off drill grooves to reach ledge and mantle up.

name: Boulder Problem
description: Start between the 4th and 5th drill marks near a nice little pocket climb straight up to  ring anchors on right going over a slight roof, or go left and follow 3 bolts to another set of ring anchors climbing up a small arete. The anchors are about 6’ left of last bolt. The roof and arete are both cruxes, the arete has small foot holds but a good ledge to hold on.

name: Bugs Bunny
description: Start between the 1st and 2nd drillmarks to the right of the arete. Climb the right side of the arete and flake on the right, mantle up to Broadway Ledge.

name: Easy Does It 5.5
description: Easy Does It 5.5 - Is a great addition to Logtown Quarries and a good warm up. This route climbs a short easy slab section with big holds and great protection to a high step and mantel at the crux and finishes with easy climbing to the anchors.

name: Fireplace Route
description: 4 bolts to anchors

name: Husker Do
description: Start in the shallow left facing inside corner to the left of the Pit, climb the left facing inside corner.

name: Obession
description: Originally it was a top rope route throughout the 80's that saw two additions of bolts by the FFA, the first to open the lower section in the 90s to open it as a mixed route and then the second to make the route more user friendly.  The route starts 12-13 drillmarks (60 feet) to the left of 'The Pit', in front of the lower quarried wall between the 3rd and 4th drillmarks from the wall's left end. Climb the flake between the two drillmarks to get to Broadway Ledge, 15 ft.

name: Obsessed
description: Start 10’ to the left of the sport route OBSESSION where there is a finger pocket literally inside the drillmark. Climb using the finger pocket and to get to Broadway Ledge, 15 ft.

name: The Overhang
description: The Overhang 5.7- Starts below a 2 foot block with a finger crack and then climbs up and left on good holds through a small overhang to a well placed bolt at the mantel crux from there climb up and slightly right to the anchors.

name: Overhangs
description: Start to the left of the Pit where there is a ramped section of rock and a series of overhangs, climb through the ramp and through the overhangs.  This climb no longer exists. There was severe rockfall here several years ago which changed the route completely.

name: Bursitis
description: Climb the crack system, move right and climb the roof-crack in the overhang to finish up on the ledge above the overhang. Continue to anchors near top.

name: Bursitis Direct
description: Climb directly up the face to use the roof-crack to surmount the   overhang of BURSITIS. Variation: Climb the BURSITIS DIRECT start then move left and do the overhang crux of WICKED FINGERS.

name: Classic Corner Crack
description: Start in the East corner.

name: Dreadlock Holiday
description: Start to the left of center on the fractured Southwest wall (road side) of The Pit. Climb the fractured wall.

name: Gun Control
description: Climb the wall, do a hard mantel move then pull through the roof.

name: Highly Sellassie
description: Start in the East corner of The Pit. Traverse left a few feet and then climb straight up.

name: No Compassion
description: Start the same as CLASSIC CORNER CRACK. Climb the right facing inside corner to a pedestal then climb the smaller right facing inside corner and the overhang above.

name: Overhang Boulder Problem
description: Start 25 feet to the right of The Pit where the overhanging prow is next to the path which leads to the cliff top. Climb the prow shaped overhanging boulder at its widest point, 15 ft. Walk back down the path.

name: Rastafaria
description: Start in the altar-like area of the Southeast wall of The Pit. Climb straight up the wall.

name: Reggae Got Soul
description: Start on the left side of the Southeast wall The Pit. Climb the bulging wall without using the corner crack.

name: Rockfall
description: Climb the wall with crescent shaped left facing holds and overhang above. A rockfall in early 1992 removed a ledge and helped to make this route.

name: Satisfaction
description: Start the same as BURSITIS DIRECT. Climb the wall to a point under the overhang that is about 2 feet left of the roof-crack. Without   using the roof-crack, surmount the overhang.

name: Wicked Fingers
description: Start the same as BURSITIS. Climb the crack system to the roof and surmount the overhang at the point where the crack meets the   ceiling.

name: Artists Only
description: Climb up blocks to the roof.  Pull it through the middle to the top.

name: Astroboy
description: Climb the akward corner to a ledge.  Follow the crack to the top.

name: Back Door Love Affair
description: Climb to the obvious horizontal slot in the wall.  Step up to a flake and traverse to Dog Job ledge.  Finish to right or left.

name: Blast from the Past
description: This route climbs pass an old broken drill bit with long reaches pass 4 bolts to the anchors.

name: Cave Traverse
description: Pull out of alcove to ledge on right.  Mantle up and traverse to end.  More of a boulder problem than a route.

name: Dick Rock Direct
description: Climb overhanging crack through the broken center of the face to a ledge.  Finish to left or right.

name: Dick Rock Route
description: Climb up corner to ledge.  Move up and right to the top.

name: Dog Job
description: Climb the corner, pull the roof to ledge.  Finish on Direct or Indirect.  Named after a pulp porno novel found on ledge on FA.  Yes, it was about "doing" dogs.  Pretty funny stuff when you are 15.

name: Dog Job Direct
description: Dog Job and Dog Job Direct are now a mixed line that climbs the thin book like corner to a large ledge and then climbs the overhangs pass 4 bolts to ring anchors

name: Eric's Overhang
description: Pull series of overhanging blocks to the top.

name: Follow The Folly
description: From ledge, traverse right onto the main wall.  Follow shallow crack system up and right to top.

name: Horn Traverse
description: Climb the corner to the horn on the left.  Pull up to ledge.  Walk left until ledge ends.  Traverse to and finish on Dick Rock.

name: Indirect Finish
description: Climb up ramp to the left to a small corner below a roof.  Go out left side of roof to top.

name: Mr. Greenjeans
description: Climb straight up through roof to the top.

name: Out Come The Freaks
description: Pull straight out of alcove to small flake to ledge.  Crank through roof to top.

name: Return to Sender
description: This is a fun little route with pockets reaches and even a mantel near the finished.

name: S.H.I.T. (Sean's Highly Intense Traverse)
description: Climb Dick Rock Route to a ledge.  Step around left to the main face.  Traverse left over precariously perched block and go to top.

name: Save The Wails
description: Climb up blocks to a crack.  Pull the overhanging block to the top.

name: Shane's Traverse
description: This is a right to left traverse of the Middle Cliffs.  Begin at intersection of trail and right end.  Follow mid-height ledge system to Dog Job and belay.  Move left into Horn Traverse.  Follow it to Dick Rock ledge and belay.  Do Sean's Highly Intense Traverse (SHIT).

name: Short Stack
description: This route climbs past a slightly overhanging large stacked blocks pass 3 bolts to a finish.

name: Superman's Revenge
description: Climb the ramp through the shelves to an alcove.  Pull out of alcove and follow crack through overhang above.

name: Waves in Stone
description: This route climbs pass a large mail box "like" pocket to a few good holds and the a long reach / leap of faith to some good holds which lead to a hard roof move and mantle to the anchors

name: Toblerone Right Arete
description: Layback your way up the right arete and the slot on the right side of the slabby face. There's the little flake for your feet at the start, and some more foot options toward the top.

name: You don't deserve this big Toblerone
description: Slabby side of the Toblerone. Previously coated in moss, but has since been scrubbed clean. Crimpy-ish underclings and some 1/4 pad sharp pockets. Aretes are off.

name: Quack Attack Crack
description: Sit start with hand jams, then pull and stand up on the big foot ledge to reach some holds inside and along the edge of the crack. Get another good hold on the right edge, then reach the lip. Topout.

name: Refrain
description: Start pinching the bottom of the pie and the X under the roof. Feet straddle the crack. Bump out to the pinch on the outer ledge (use your thumb to stick it)and a side pull on the right side of the crack. Pull up to the top of the middle segment, work the hands to find positivity, then top out.   Other than the bottom third of the rock, the left side of the crack is off.

name: Sustain
description: Up the left of the crack (right side is off). Starts matched on the pie that sits in the crack, moves out to a ledge, then a throw to the top of the middle segment of the boulder. Once standing on the ledge, the last move is pretty easy.

name: Bear's Den
description: Start in a sandy two-handed slot to the right, traverse leftward along the mid-roof ledge, then make a big move to an edge and then the lip. Mantle/muscle-up and topout.   First half is chossy, but the last few holds and moves (almost) make it worth it.

name: Rocket
description: A compressy overhanging arete. Start hanging on the rail, pull to the ledge, then make use of some dimples on each side of the arete to work your way to the top. Topout's chill.

name: Unknown Den Problem
description: Start on a ledge in the middle of the cave where the vertical wall meets the roof. Come straight out using the rail, jug flake, and pocket above the roof. Mantle/muscle-up topout.

name: Caffine
description: Start on a sloper in the roof. Come out with some challenging moves, then get up on the ledge and enjoy a chill topout.

name: Maku
description: Sidepull up some cracks and a pocket. Use the tree to top out.

name: Token Hueco Problem
description: Start with underclings on the roof under the bulge. Reach up then stand up on the bulge, go to the hueco, then work up to the corner for a mildly heady topout (not helped by the moss).

name: Coughing Fit
description: Nice warmup. Side pull standing start filling in crimps, side pulls and jugs to a decent top out. Trust a high foot for a low risk top out. After topping out, walk back toward the entrance for an easy down climb.

name: Coughing Fit Traverse
description: Start with a tough undercling up to your preferred ledge before traversing to the original Coughing Fit to top out.

name: ... The Horn
description: Start on edge far out right (same as Vegan Stout) and traverse your way left into the roof. Top out left of the tip of the horn. Downclimb through the hole.

name: Face
description: Start on the undercling rail in the roof, then work up the juggy pockets. The last two holds are a little crimpy, and it's a bit dynamic to the finish hold.

name: Ride the Lightning
description: Start on the ledge under the overhang. Come out through some crimping, then work up the right side of the seam. Finish is up right.

name: Vegan Stout
description: Even shorter than Marthas Bunion! Start on the edge and go straight up. Should be topped out, but might need cleaned a little.

name: Ape
description: On the right side of the cave, start on the rail and try to fit your feet on, then go back to the sloper. Throw out left to the other juggy sloper. Bump into the sidepull if needed for the reach, then bump up to the top.

name: Get out of there!
description: Crawl down onto the tall rock under the left side of the roof, pull on the rail, and core up to get off the ground (barely). Out to the big sloper, then the far crimp on the corner. Powerful move up to the jug before the rest of the roof, then out to a couple of slimps (the right of the two is a good pinch), then pull up to the top.

name: Jelly Fish
description: Sit-start with outward pulls, moves on to a crimp and slightly tricky feet. Then, a throw to a finger jam in a partial pocket (like trying to hold the open part of a "C"). You could also try to crimp or undercling it, but it's a pretty solid lock that you can easily get out of if you need to. It's jugs from there.

name: Marthas Bunion
description: Short little warmup. Starts on left side of arete (sit on the slanted rock on the ground, hands on crimps, left foot on ledge & right foot smeared onto corner) and goes up.

name: The rock ballerina
description: Start out on small jug on far right side of traverse.

name: Snagglepuss Arete
description: Great highball(ish) easy climb.

name: Steps Taken Forward
description: Easy balancing up to a big undercling, then a slighlty slopey top-out.

name: Strafe
description: Very positive holds up an interior corner (featuring a crack) and the narrow face to its right. The top is slightly overhanging. Try to only use the narrow face and avoid stepping into the dihedral, for some challenge.

name: The Art of Zen
description: Start as far back as you can in the roof like overhang on a jug (your feet might be over the river). Work through great jug shelves to a reachy crux just below the lip. Easy top out.

name: Dr. Jones
description: Start matched on the far right small crimp rail. Work left past some sharp holds with bad feet and high tension heel hooks. Use the arete all the way on the left to top out.

name: Fortune and Glory
description: Start left on a sloping shelf, and work right through a cool ledge feature, topping out up a sequential shield, awesome movement!

name: The Pharaoh
description: A great problem, but very height dependent, and poor rock quality. Start at the base of the block, and use compression to get to the obvious jug shelf on the left. Bail onto that shelf if you don't want a high top out, or continue to the top for the full problem.

name: Slug Bucket
description: Direct start to Fortune and Glory. Start on two sidepulls below the cool ledge feature. The left hand is almost always wet and slimy. Work up to the ledge/ rail feature, then finish up Fortune and Glory.

name: Snake Eyes
description: Start down and right on the lowest jug. Work up and left through a series of jug and sloper shelves to top out at the arete all the way on the left.

name: The Spider Dojo
description: Start way back in the little cave on the farthest jug on the left (often slimy). Work out a jug shelf to some tough compression moves getting over the bulge. Juggy top out.

name: Steel Head
description: Start on the same hold as "Temple of Hank", the sloping jug on the far left side of the boulder. Power straight up through some committing moves on holds that take some skin, with a balancy move just before the lip.

name: Temple of Hank
description: Begin on the same hold as "Steel Head", and work right, beginning with a big move. Power through sloping ledges and some big moves to be rewarded with a juggy top out.

name: Unnamed V2
description: Start on some gastons just right of the right side arete of the boulder. continue up the arete using sparse holds on the face to eventually reach the top of the triangle. Top out.

name: Unnamed V3
description: Start on small crimp left of the main arete with good foot. Make hard reach to good rail, then hike your feet up and continue to the top.

name: Unnamed V4
description: Fun little powerful problem. Often referred to as "That undercling problem" because of the powerful first move to an undercling. Start with a bad right hand crimp on the arete, and a left hand side pull crimp way down low. Throw a series of powerful moves to the lip generally following the arete, and top out.

name: 50 feet for better health - traverse
description: There an obvious slopey wide area to the right of the whole rock face, Skipped that, started to the left of it. Left face of wall has a bunch of great holds, Shelves in the middle.

name: Warmup Easy Traverse
description: Can climb multiple combinations in tennis.

name: Buzzards Roost
description: Exposed edges climbed regularly by kids in tennis. Confidence in climbing shoes...

name: Fledglings Next Traverse
description: Always take assistance rating, Easy enough to traverse in tennis, Need to be strong enough to hold on, For the schmeary feets.  Increasing variability and difficulty,  Weeerk those heal hooks.. I'm not so inclined.

name: Snakeskin
description: Sit down start on the rock jutting up and match hands above you. Start pulling up to reach for the multiple roofs to touch the top. You're able to get on top, but there's no where to walk off. Downclimbing is only good way down, the deck is a bit sketchy.

name: Angels Arete
description: Rarely climbed anymore .. there is a large series of trees blocking the start.

name: Beer Can Alley Traverse
description: Realizing how high you've become and staying on the rock.

name: Gumby Crack
description: Mostly face climbing with some cracks for gear.  At the bottom it is easier to traverse left then right to get to the bottom of the crack about halfway up.  Some of the topout is a little mossy.

name: Ounce and a half.
description: The full grunt.

name: Racoon
description: There are many classic problems on the Racoon Boulder ..

name: Unkown Dyno..
description: Just after the Keyhole Crack the cliff breaks down, follows the trail down.. there is the face of Beer Can Alley. This is a small dyno and face.

name: Widow Maker
description: Opposite Angels Arete .. possibly have someone show you.

name: Old Man's Variation
description: Start the Old Man's Variation low and left by matching on a jug and planting a left toe. Stay low while traversing right until the right edge of the boulder is within reach. Reach for the large and obvious bucket to pull over the top.

name: Bubble Bath
description: The moss.. clean the moss. Try and climb it. Come back when it is dry. Clean the moss.

name: Cheese Grater Traverse
description: Traverse left from the crack keeping feet *above* the obvious line ~2-3 feet from the ground.  Crux is about half way (10 feet) from start. No idea if this had been attempted before (though imagine it has). We (Johnny Arnold and I) decided to throw down a little challenge while climbing the Christ Died Crack by adding in a long traverse. If bouldering, Route would end at He Had a Lot to Say; if using as an add-on to Christ Died Crack (or HHALTS or C!MITMW) beware of the LONG pendulum from being roped into the crack anchors (including the potential for plowing into your belayer, the tree, decking on the boulder right below HHALTS, or if your lucky to peel off further along, the long swing (hopefully) between the tree and wall. Would give this a “PG13” add-on if using as an addition to the crack.

name: Christ Died Crack
description: Short crack to small overhang.

name: Good Morning Sunshine
description: Start with a pinch down and left. Climb up and right as you navigate through pockets and pinches. Slopes and jugs await as you top out.

name: Nut Cracker
description: Named because of the large Beach Tree that was growing right behind the crack. It could be a challenge to climb on a windy day,    with the tree swaying back and forth pushing the climber into the crack. The tree is now gone. Unfortunately the crack  is almost    always dirty.

name: Professional Chair Tester
description: Boulder problem that starts in the low pockets of "O" wall and traverses right to a large sloping pocket. Using an undercling pocket continue straight up through small crimps and pockets to the break.

name: Slippery When Wet
description: This is the longest trad route we have found at Whipps.  Start on an overhanging, usually wet, crack on the main corner left of Christ Died.  Once through the overhang, delicately traverse about 10' to the right then up a fun 5.6/5.7 hand crack to top out.  This route is pretty fun, and when combined in a day with leading the Hinckley Crack and Christ Died Crack makes a good day of cragging for a trad leader.  Note: we haven't been able to dig up any FA info other than ours, please let us know if you have been leading this route for years!

name: Sunshine
description: Three common variations: Left Sunshine goes at about 5.9, Center variation 5.10b,  Right variation 5.6 or easier.

name: Sunshine's backside
description: Variety of boulder problems on Sunshine’s backside.

name: Unknown
description: An easy slab problem that goes straight up the middle of the face. Name?

name: Cigarettes After Sex
description: This is the problem that starts in the small cave working out the roof.. up the face.

name: Unnamed Traverse ..
description: Not hitting the rocks on the ground when the rock breaks on you.

name: Dave’s Left
description: Moss. This crag has moss.

name: Underclings, jugs and ledges
description: It’s a great climb up. Just what it says, Underclings, jugs and ledges. Staying right is easy, Up and over.

name: Warm up Easy
description: Fun and easy enough loop. There will be moss...

name: One More for the Road
description: Start under the middle of the roof of this beauty with 2 jugs and feet down low. Keep your back off the pads while you work out and up onto crimps and slopers to finish.

name: 7UP
description: Originally done in converse.

name: Holding Space
description: Perfect hand jams take you up to a ledge. Traverse left and mantle over a block to finish.

name: Island Access
description: This route is often wet and falling at any point is not advisable.   Start on the face holds surrounding the crack. Follow the crack up towards a pin underneath the roof. Extending this draw will greatly reduce rope drag. Traverse left to clip another pin. Continue up to where a large camalot (#4-#5) may help reduce the "R/X" factor of this top section. Once finished, there are many trees / bolts available for rappelling back to the ground.

name: Island Access Traverse
description: Cruxy turning corners,  or reaching past blankish sections... NBD

name: The Orgator
description: This is located close to the Island, but not on the Island proper.    No specific crux .. just a classic boulder problem. The name comes from “ORGATOR”, carved on the backside of the boulder (facing the Main Wall).

name: Sandbox Arete
description: Straddle the arete all the way to the finish horn using pockets and edges.  Crux revolves around a small sidepull/pocket on the left side of the arete.  Descend off to the left.

name: Sandbox Direct
description: Start on large sidepull in the middle of the wall.  Line is straight up to the right most portion of the mid-wall ledge system.  Traverse left along the ledge around the corner to descend.  Crux move is the last lunge to the jugs on the ledge off of two crimps with high feet.

name: Sandbox Skyline Traverse
description: Start on pockets mostly to the right of the wall.  Ascend directly to the high ledge.  Traverse the full length to the left.

name: Oopma loopma Traverse
description: Traverse, traverse, traverse, Squat, look, step up, repeat.. Some many cool finger crimps, And nothing holds :)

name: Woooop
description: Mind crux for the newb...

name: The Cave
description: Sweet problem / TR. The erosion has taken the ground and lowered it ~one foot.. your mileage may vary on getting started. Originally done via a running jump to the suit case handle. May need cleaning before climbing.

name: The Crack
description: Crux varies for everyone until you have it dialed. A Hinckley Classic.

name: Double Layback Crack
description: Making sure your gear stays in the crux if you lead it .. otherwise it is smooth sailing.

name: Grooves
description: Short, fun climb.

name: Keyhole Crack
description: Obvious crack the splits the upper part of the wall. Towards the top of the crack there is a keyhole looking feature.

name: Smart Woman
description: Solid V2. Low traverse trending left of the crack.

name: Tall Man
description: High traverse tending left of the crack.

name: Tina Turner
description: White slightly overhanging face.

name: Warm Up Traverse
description: A nice way to occupy your time while waiting for your friends to arrive.

name: Native American Pow Wow
description: Start under jawline about a foot and half from Arete, moving up along prominent nose line, over cheekbone to the corner of eye/headdress, to top!   Slipping feet, easily recoverable. A couple holds are kind of long and reachy.

name: Two Percent
description: Start with jugs on the face. Climb diagonally up and left through a small split to reach the ledge finish.

name: Whole Melk
description: Start on 2 pinches underneath the overhang. Reach out and pull on to the face to start working your way left and as low as possible.. staying off the jug rails overhead. Cross, pinch, and crimp your way to the top of the ledge to finish.

name: Cobaltic Leap
description: Sit start on left flaring splitter. Work up to a left handed 2 finger pocket, and throw to a right handed 2 finger lock. Gain one of the small ledges on the left. Finish with a right handed throw to the horn. High step and mantle finish. Red Gully holds are off.

name: The Crimson Trail
description: Western Wall. Start on the Northwest Arete. Then move climber's left to right along the entire Western Wall, and onto the South Face. Start on the crimson rock band - balance with poor hands but great feet on the ledge. At mid-wall-point, transition to good huecos, with feet on small ledges. Work over to the Southwest Arete on slopers and wrap onto the facade of the South Face ledge system. Then finish up to the top of the ledge on the mini-upward-right-flaring-dihedral.

name: Flapjack Traverse
description: Move laterally across the east face of the Mini-Island, half way up the wall. Initially done climber's right-to-left. Down climb southeast corner arete.

name: Free Arc
description: Meant to be freed with no pro or spotter. Side-winding nature of the route over uneven terrain precludes protection.  Foothold assurance important.  Can be done 2 ways.  1) Start at the base arete and pull left following the beautiful upward left flaring eponymous arc.  Face climb up over left side of ledge and traverse left on upper face approximately 8 feet. Then up and over the next upper left ledge, keeping to the face. Rating: V2  2) Same start as method 1, except stem off the rear rock and the face of the arc to the first ledge. The remainder of the route remains the same as method 1. Rating: V1

name: Red Gully (A Homage to Crestone Peak)
description: Fun, easy route. Sit start at left flaring splitter. Angle right into the hueco field in the horizontal crimson ribbon. Solid feet on positive ledges and good pockets. Climb through the notch up top as the wall tilts slights past vertical. Mantle on the top out. Excellent warm up route.

name: Shifting Sands - Left
description: Sit start, with one hand on each side of the bottom fin. Pull up the middle of the face, shifting to the left arete for the last move and top out mantle.

name: Warm Me Up Scotty
description: Straight forward warm up lap option to start your climbing session. Top is approximately 18 feet off the deck. FA done without any protection (no crash pad). Horizontal shelf holds are numerous, positive, and provide several warm up options for practice. Top out mantle can get the heart pumping a bit for those not used to runout.

name: Journey to the Sun
description: The wetness.

name: Moonlight
description: The slab of Moonlight Buttress.

name: Swingles
description: Start wherever (low) and slap high. Rock has the etching of "Swingles" on it at the base of Journey and Ultimate Journey.

name: Ultimate Journey
description: Same start as Journey to the Sun, second move goes straight up instead of dyno right.

name: Direct Route
description: Direct variation.  Sit start on huecos under the triangular overhang. Find vertical jugs on the right to top out. A nice warm-up.  Please let me know if you know the FA or if this route has a name.

name: Easy Walking Ascent Loop
description: Fun to run up the lines,  Always tricky when you’re   unprotected.

name: Heal hooks, Up and over
description: Heel hook transition to up and over practice. Nice. Let the moves heal your ails.

name: Feather, Bone, and Glass.
description: Start with stemming feet and finding wider hand jams. Intermittent holds for hands and feet allow you to choose to jam or stay out on the face while you take your pick of textbook placements. Mantle onto the large ledge and then choose whether to continue up right or left to a large healthy tree for anchor building. Cord or long slings are useful here.

name: Phantom Plank Traverse
description: The crux is being off the ground.  If you go up and right,  its like walking a plank.  Up and left, You're settled back close to land..

name: Walking Through the Park
description: Start with feet low and hands matched on the jug circled. Good crimps and jugs take you up to a shelf, where you can mantle to a finish.

name: The Easy Cheez Traveez
description: Lots of different holds, for good practice and easy enough traversing, Many variations available.  Add a heal hook or two, Crux depends on you. Left to right or right to left and back of course.

name: Easy Peasy
description: Depends on your hand variations,  increases your grade.  Walk this one up over the left side, Over the top and down the other side, Reconnecting to the beginning. Go again if you like, Forward and back.

name: Horseshoe Boulder Traverse
description: Mossy moss moss... Loaded up and started around the left, Work your way all along the most exposed posterior edges, to dismount on the right. Get creative, forwards and back. Bonus if you can connect this piece, and ring this one round the front.

name: Unknown Name
description: ..It's v0. There isn't much of a crux. Pull up, cheating left or right is.. well, cheating.

name: Moving West of the Butt-traaass
description: Another traverse line,  Bout 40 feet

name: Up next
description: Been enjoying a mix of small finger pockets and pinches, with crimps. Vary em up.

name: Unnamed  1
description: The route is on Yellow Wall in the center. Sit start on the ledge and go straight up a series of crimps. The problem ends right beneath the capped roof. It will almost always have chalk on it.

name: Unnamed  2
description: Same start as Unnamed #1 branch left on the sloping side pull with a heel hook. Latch a two finger crimp scoop with your left hand and get to the ledge directly above the left hand.

name: Z's Go with the Flo Traverse
description: Start on the Boulder to your left,  enter the lower rail, flail if you like,  on to a squat juggy ledge,  and matching traverse,  around some sloping engagements,  working your wavy way through, on to being tougher than I thought,  with a nice ...

name: Hand-Over-Hand
description: Follow the arete  on large holds to the top of the ledge

name: Monkey Bars
description: Follow the three obvious two handed pockets to the top of the ledge and top out.

name: One Move Wonder
description: Start on two small pockets and make one move to a matched hand finish.

name: Traversion Aversion
description: Follow the thin, horizontal finger crack to the top out finish

name: Great Swamp
description: A simple and enjoyable fun problem

name: Whitehouse Full Traverse
description: Good pump generating traverse. Be extremely careful to test each hold as the wall is full of loose rock, especially the top out on the left side of the wall. Begin traverse far right on blocky blunt arete. Stay off the ground and stay off the top loose holds and move left over some bushes, poison ivy and possibly water (during the first 7-8 months of the year.) Entire traverse to the top out is approximately 80-100 feet, but I have not measured for accuracy. Its not great, but it is climbing on real limestone, in Northwest Ohio. Could certainly use some cleaning and clearing of the brush under the wall.

name: Anti-Shock
description: Start with a crimp and a sloper pinch. Move to the good crimp and flow through the slopey top out.

name: Bar None
description: Use jugs and underclings with a crag near the top

name: Bobcat Crack
description: Start below the crack and move into the good holds in the crack. Then follow the holds to the top out.

name: Broken Glass
description: Sit start, then use the arete and good crimps on the right to finish on a slab-like top out.

name: Bug Smasher
description: Start at the indent of the arete and find the good feet. Then follow the arete to the top out.

name: Copperhead Ridge Top Traverse
description: Follow the good jugs across the rock face. Great climb to do while waiting for a problem to open up. Also, it is good to work the feet and improve endurance.

name: Copperhead Ridge Traverse Lower
description: A fun and finger focused route also great options for feet.

name: Crusties
description: Begin with a match in a hand size pocket. Move up and left for good holds and top out at the peak of the boulder.

name: Cutleaf Toothwort
description: Begin with a sit start using high handholds on the arete. Then use a mix of good holds and good crimps to top out on the taller side of the boulder.

name: Dextrose
description: Start left of the mini dihedral and follow the slab-like rock to finish on the left.

name: Drop, Lock, and Pocket
description: Start with the crimps at the bottom and move to the left side of the pocket. The find the good jugs to top out right of the tree.

name: Fake Flake
description: Follow the flake to a top out left of the tree.

name: Fire in the Hole
description: Follow the jugs to the mantle top out.

name: Flakey
description: Start with a two-pocket start and use good crimps to the top out.

name: Food Evolution
description: Start with a match on a low ledge. Move through the crimps and towards the pocket. Then use the good jugs to top out.

name: Free From-
description: Begin with a sit start and move up and over the bulge to a sloper section. Then use the good handholds and fun slaby footholds to top out.

name: Green Carpet
description: A fun matching start in a medium-size pocket. Then finishing on a jug and sloper to top out.

name: Heart Shaped Box
description: Sit start in the obvious pocket and work a couple moves to the solid top-out. Watch out for the rock close behind your head.

name: Hot Pocket
description: Use the crips to the horizontal flake then go for the jugs for a top out left of the tree.

name: I Don't Want No Scrubs
description: Same start as Slope Star, finish with a top out using the upper crack.

name: Kid Mode
description: Start with a low crimping side pull and a high left crimp. Move up the sloping arete to finish by using the footholds on the overhanging face.

name: mini dihedral
description: Start in between the two rock faces that are divided by a small crack. Then enjoy the smallish holds and steeming moves to the top out towards the right.

name: Muck
description: Begin with good crimps and follow them to the jug line. Follow jugs to top out left of the tree

name: Pocket Putty
description: Find the good feet to start. Then move to the pocket for a finish with nice jugs moving left of the tree.

name: Pot O Gold
description: Climb the good holds to the slopey top out.

name: Sage On The Stage
description: Start underneath the roof on the smallest block feature. Move underneath the roof and out on to the ledge of the roof. Then find the good hold in the crack to top out.

name: Slope Star
description: Sit start under the low shelf. Then move high and follow the traverse to a good ledge for the finish.

name: Spoons not forks
description: Start between the two cracks and follow the crimps to a top out on the right.

name: Spring Beauty
description: Sit start with good jugs on the bottom of the arete. Then move under the mini roof to the slopy top out.

name: Three Star Face
description: Start with a match on the lower flake then move through the slightly overhanging face with jugs for the top out.

name: To Slot or Not
description: Face climb with an arete

name: Triple Jalapeno Popper
description: Use the two pockets at the start to move to a pocket on the left. Then bust a move to the jugs for a top out right of the tree.

name: Turkey Tail
description: Use the ledge to start and follow the crimps to move towards the arete. Then use the jugs and finish on top of the arete.

name: Two Old Women
description: Start at the bottom of the Arete and follow the good holds to the top.

name: Whale Belly
description: Begin with a sit start under the rock on the left side of the boulder. Find the good holds to pullup and out from under the rock. Then finish with a slabby jug hull to the top.

name: You Got Me Sweaty
description: Find the low side pull then move through the middle using crimps. Then enjoy the juggy top out right of the tree.

name: Around the World
description: Start on the colonnade and then move left to the jug and traverse left, topping out left of Dope Nose/Three Times a Lady.

name: Bird's Nest
description: SDS on colonnade and work up the slopers on the left side to a throw for a few slopey holds and the top out.

name: Daw's Jaws
description: Start on a pockety ledge and then move up to a frictiony and balancy top out above.

name: Dope Nose/Three Times a Lady
description: Climb up the colonnade that Bird's Nest starts on then move out left to the obvious jug.  Top out directly over the jug without moving back right towards Bird's Nest.

name: Long Duck Dong
description: Start on the colonnade, same as bird's nest, then move right using the sidepull to stand up on right side of the colonnade then top out the same as for Bird's Nest

name: Tarzan
description: Start in the slopey pockets to the right of the colonnade.  Move up on bad feet to top out over the lip above.

name: Daytrippin
description: Start on the finger size seams and move up and left following the crack and eventually top out on the ledge up and as far left as possible.  Watch out for the fecal matter on certain portions of the ledge.

name: With a Brush and a Vengeance
description: Start below the hueco on jug underclings, head up and left into the hueco.  Reach up and left for a sidepull pocket before heading up onto the edge and up and right onto jug holds to top out.

name: Bones
description: SUS and climb the face via crmps and edges, goes up and through the small bulge/arete.

name: Boulder 1
description: SDS on sideways jugs under arete.

name: Boulder 10 - Project
description: SUS in dihedral under the roof and figure out a way to get to the top.    Project boulder, unsure of grade or if possible.

name: Boulder 13A - Project
description: SUS and climb the less than vertical face through less than quality rock.

name: Boulder 13B - Project
description: Climb the arete feature that starts above the ramp. This line will need heavy cleaning.

name: Boulder 14A - Project
description: Possible roof crack problem, it has been aided.

name: Boulder 15B - Project
description: Start on the same jug rail as 'Light Show' and work right up through the weakness. Heading right then back left will probably yield the best results.

name: Boulder 2
description: SUS on sloper. Head straight up.

name: Boulder 3
description: SDS on jugs near choss.

name: Boulder 8
description: SDS on gritty rail and move straight up to a six foot top out.

name: Crack Face
description: SUS and climb the finger crack. One of the best problems in the witches.

name: Double Down
description: SUS to ledge just below the boulder that perches on the edge. Make a dyno or figure out how to avoid it. Tops out on the perched boulder.

name: Hand Grenade 14B -  Project
description: Climb the left crack system with some hand jams, fist jams, funkiness and thrutching to grab the FFA!    Has been aided, C1 rating.

name: Light Show 15A - Project
description: Start under the roof right of the prow on the large jug shelf. Work left off the rail to prow, then up through the pockets for the best possible path that will lead to a send. This line is very tall, with a slightly sloping land, so bring several pads and a good spotter.

name: The Lightbringer
description: Low start on a bad left hand and right 2/3 finger pocket. Make a couple of desperate moves to easier climbing.

name: Party Cave
description: Located on the right side of the cave behind the small boulder that sits in the fall zone for this problem. SUS at a jug at head height, make moves out to the roof above the boulder. This one can be dirty quite often, so brush the top out if it has rained at all recently.

name: Proctologist
description: SUS in right pocket and left rail. Make an awkward move to reach the slimpers.

name: Rails
description: SUS on sloper rails and move up the face directly across from 'Crack Face'.

name: The Skull
description: SDS on jug under roof and move up through the skull that is chiseled into the rock.

name: 50 Grit
description: SUS Crimps lead to large move to good edge followed by another to the amazing topout.

name: Balance Slab
description: SUS Climb to the right of the crack and left of arete up the slabby dihedreal.

name: Boulder 12
description: Climb the angled arete on this free standing boulder to a slabby top out.

name: Boulder 14
description: Same start as Lip Traverse. Instead, travel up and over to the top. Awkward moves followed by slabby top out.

name: Boulder 19
description: SUS and climb the arete to the top.    Traverse into Witches Backside for something extra.

name: Boulder 2
description: Climb the arete to the top.

name: Castles Made of Sand
description: Climb the broken crack system to better holds.

name: Climbing Class Mantel
description: Easy mantel practice.

name: Drew Arete
description: SDS on right side of arete. Make use of limited feet; if you get off the ground you've down more than most.

name: Duck Bill
description: Mantel on the flat feature to an easy top out.

name: French Press
description: SDS and work into a shouldery move. Then reach for the top.

name: Key Hole Arete
description: SUS Climb the left side of the arete through a pocket to the top. Requires a lot of slow movement and balance.    (Variation 2, V2: Climb the arete with out the pocket for the Keyless  Entry.)     (Variation 3, V4: climb the face through the pocket without the arete for  The Lock Smith)

name: Lip Traverse
description: SDS on jug and travel left around the prow. Utilizes same boulder as Route 12.

name: Low Blow/Joe - Project
description: SDS on Low Ball and mantle on small block.    Boulder project, so rating is undetermined. V7 is a placeholder.

name: Nintendo Thumb - Project
description: Climb the near blank arete to the top.    Rating is V?, unsure of exact difficulty.

name: Pillow Fight
description: SUS and climb through slopers to the lip.

name: Prego in a Dress
description: SUS on the right and traverse to the other side.

name: Route 23
description: Climb the slab with feet, no hands or knees. Anything else is cheating!

name: Route 6
description: Climb the wide crack and its sides to the top.

name: School House Crack
description: SUS. Climb the easy crack system.

name: Thumber
description: Work from start up ride side of the arete to awkward undercling (Thumb-dercling) then to slopey mantel.

name: Whale Sex
description: SDS on Witches Backside and move right after second hold, move across slimpers and other trash to reach a weakness in the topout.

name: Witches Backside
description: SDS in large pocket and move straight up into trough like top out. Used to be easier, but broken jugs are challenging.

name: Witches Brew
description: SDS in large pocket and make move left to tiny sharp   crimp pocket, move up and left and finish on 17#

name: Witches Traverse
description: SDS right of tree and cling to the lip as you move right.

name: The Crest
description: Stand up start, climb straight up the side of the boulder to a easy top out.

name: Horse Deuce
description: Start standing up, work your way up the crack to a top out

name: Sir Bark A Lot
description: Stand up start and work your way straight up the problem, the holds are good and fairly easy but the top out can be quite tricky.

name: Back to Reality
description: Start on two crimps, paste foot on boulder and make big move to good hold and top out. Video Link

name: Cascada Traverse
description: Start low on seam on the far right of the cascada boulder and traverse into La Cascada. Great problem and great rock quality. Video Link

name: Cascada Traverse (Full)
description: Start five feet to the right of the original Cascada Traverse, just below lip on right facing seam/edge. Make a couple moves on slopers to start of Cascada Traverse and follow lip to arete and top out.

name: Castle Made of Sand
description: Starts high on good edge. Make dynamic move to top and top out. Video Link

name: Controlled Erosion
description: Start low on slopers. Follow arete to mantle top out.

name: L.R.J.
description: Starts on a crack under the cascada boulder. Pull a couple moves then do a kind of tricky mantle to top out. Video Link

name: La Cascada
description: Starts on a slopping edge on the left side of the boulder and goes left making a shouldery move and match to mantle and top out. Video Link

name: Pilot
description: Starts far left on good seam and uses good slopers to go up and right to the top out. Video Link

name: Versicolor
description: Start compressing on to bad slopers with right heel and slap your way up the arete. Video Link

name: Black Widow
description: Climb up the first and most distinguished crack of the wall.

name: Spider Man Traverse
description: Traverse that works head height right to left utilizing pockets and knobs (which are my favorite). Start right in these two pockets and work your way left across the crack and into the pockets on the other wall. reach the far left jug pocket and that is the top out.

name: Spider Monkey
description: Sit start on the left side with having your hands matched on a distinguished sloper your toes in two small pockets right off the ground. Work your way up to the right using some small crimp ledges. Reach high for the horn up top and that is the crux. Continue up a little more to the right and get both hands into the pockets and that is the top out to Spider monkey.

name: Evolution Center
description: Start on the jugs on the right of the boulder. Climb up and left to the dirty shelf where u top out. Video Link

name: Evolution Right
description: Start on the jugs on right of the boulder and climb straight up and top out.

name: Evolution Traverse
description: Starts on far left of boulder and traverses right until you are on the backside of the boulder. Video Link

name: Krav Maga
description: Start on small holds left of center. Make big move to jug and continue up to the same top out as Evolution Center. Video Link

name: American Breakfast
description: Start on the low incut crimps. Climb the arete to the top.

name: Beginners Pedestal
description: Easy problem; good for new climbers or a fun warmup.   Start by balancing on the obvious ledge at the base of the pedestal. Move up to the left-hand side pull to reach high with the right to the big horizontal crack. Top out the same as Traversia.

name: Rated E
description: Climb the good holds in the middle of the pockety face to an easy top out. Video Link

name: Seamstress
description: Follow the easy seam making liberal use of face holds

name: Silica Rock
description: The first couple moves are the most difficult part, which are made up of mostly crimps. Once you get past these moves that holds are significantly easy. Climb about 10ft up to sloped/mossy finish.

name: Sliding Filament Mechanism
description: Stand start with left and right hands on opposing sidepulls, move to sloping dish, and then up and left to a good (but hard to see) crimp. Then straight up (without use of the right arete).

name: Traversia
description: Start in the middle of Rectangle Rock and work your way left across the rock and then up to a top out.

name: Triangle Arete 1
description: Good rock quality. Pull through small edges to a bit of a committing last moves. Video Link

name: Triangle Arete 2
description: Starts on low on crimps and traverses on slopey arete. Same top out as Triangle Arete 1 Video Link

name: Triangle Traverse
description: Traverse across the pockety face starting on the far left and finish by topping out Triangle Arete 1.

name: Unnamed V1
description: Start on large ledge and move up into the dihedral on crimps and pockets to a narrow top out climbers left.

name: Waffle House
description: Start in the back of the cave on a good side pull with feet on the left wall, work through the roof crack using flaring hand jams and strenuous side pulls before making the big move to the slot at the lip and mantling over

name: Egyptian Wingspan
description: Starts on a flat jug on the right side of the boulder and traverses left to a top out on the arete. Video Link

name: Mopers
description: Starts on right of boulder with right hand on arete and left on 'scar' side pull. Stand up and traverse through some slopers at the lip then press mantle to top out. Very balance oriented problem.

name: Under the Nose
description: Starts low on the left of Shipwreck boulder and climb straight up to top out. Video Link

name: Six Crack
description: Start in the back of cave on the crimps formed by the crack system. Move left along the crack to gain the jug. Follow crack all the way to the lip and finish on the jug/shelf.

name: Viceroy
description: Sit start on holds just above overhang. Follow holds right and top out in break in the cliff.

name: The Fin
description: Start on the sharp arete of the larger boulder. One hand on arete other on side pull work your way up arete to top out. Video Link

name: Guardian
description: Start on crimp rail to the right just under the arete. Slap up through slopers and top out. Be careful of the boulder behind you. Video Link

name: Lucifers Ledge
description: Sit start low on the obvious rail. Mantle up, working left and up the quickly thinning seam. Establish feet high atop the seam on small edges. Top out on a good ledge above.

name: Sol y Sombra
description: Start on crimps follow seam to lock off before the lip. Landing can be very wet as a stream runs along the boulder.

name: Sunshine Arete
description: Starts on large side pulls on the left arete of the boulder. Make big move up to good sloper and keep it together for the top out. Video Link

name: Sunshine Arete (Sit)
description: Start low on large slot just left of the arete above the overhang. Pull up through some crimps to the stand start and finish the same. Video Link

name: Unknown
description: Start on a good side pull and crimp on the lower left part of the boulder. Follow the obvious crack/seam across the face using some delicate foot work before making some tough moves to top out.

name: Right in My Eye
description: A one move wonder. Start on the low ledge/rail and make the bigish throw to the lip and mantle over, you can also move to an intermediate hold to the right and the grade feels about the same

name: Block Arete 1
description: Start on left arete on good seam. Continue up arete to top out. Video Link

name: Block Arete 2
description: Start low on right arete on pocket and undercling. Move up through the crimps to the top out. Avoid the tree. Video Link

name: Book, Chapter and Traverse
description: Start in the big crack left of center in the over hang area. Traverse left along the shelf and top out around the corner.

name: Book, Chapter and Traverse Var.
description: Same start as Book, Chapter and Traverse but stay on the low edge the whole time.

name: Lean Crack
description: Follow Crack until first mantle. On the far right of the Workout Wall.

name: Pocket Traverse
description: Start high on underclings and traverse right to the same finish as the pocket problem.

name: Stand Up Double
description: Start sitting down holding both jugs. Work your way up the problem with a few crimps and one finger pocket to a top out.

name: The Suspension
description: When you arrive in the Workout Wall area follow the trail directly left of the first boulder that you come to (Block Arete 1). On this trail about 30 yards away you will find a long wall and this problem will be on the far right of this wall closest to the trail.

name: Unnamed Crack
description: Start low on obvious crack right of center in the overhang area. Use finger locks and side pulls to get the jug finish. Video Link

name: Unnamed Pocket Problem
description: Start low on good pockets. Find the right pockets as you move up just left of the arete to the jug finish.

name: apple from the tree
description: small sloppy rails

name: Baby steps
description: Situated between Lichen and Leave it and Zumunda on the arête.  Make your way up the route in small incremental steps on thin rails.   Crux is between 3rd and 4th bolt.

name: Battle of the bulge
description: Work the corner on the lift of the bulge until it ends then traverce right then up to the shuts

name: Blood stains and beers
description: Dihedral corner

name: Classic Devo
description: First half of poison ivy up the flaks. Then the second half of poison oak the off with.

name: Cropdusting
description: Follow the bolts to two big flakes and then the crux is working yourself over a small bulge and to the right towards the anchors.

name: Crumb snatcher
description: climb begins on portion of rock facing the river.  Reach around left side to clip draws in.  Crux is approx. 3/4 of the way up the route where you work yourself out onto the wall containing the bolts.

name: Dirtyasscrack
description: up the chimey

name: Hannibal Lecter
description: Climb follows the first large crack on the south side of the wall.  Crux is about half way up route

name: Harper rose
description: fallow the bolt line

name: Milk Money
description: left facing dihedral offwith to the shuts

name: Ohanna
description: just to the right of milk money

name: Poise ivy
description: Start on flaks on right. Up to blocks in corner then up corner to shuts

name: Poison oak
description: Very steep off with

name: Rainy Day
description: dirty flak arching to the right

name: Sargent Hartman
description: start on the small huecos up to flake on left then right and up to ledge then straight up

name: Spider Cove
description: Nice liebacking up the first half of the route, where you meet the crux of the climb transitioning into a wider crack

name: Suckubus
description: get creative placing gear a little run out

name: tannasity
description: up the face on the right of tree

name: unnamed
description: up the center of the huge flak

name: unnamed offwidth
description: offwidth

name: violation
description: First route on the wall. South to north. Easy top rope

name: Zumunda
description: sloping wall with small rails to dig your fingertips into.  Crux is between second and third bolt.

name: Birds Nest
description: Start low on the left side of the boulder with low feet and off two pockets.  Pinch the pockets and make a big move up to a good ledge.  Pull the roof to slopers then to jugs at the top.

name: Easy Way
description: From the back side of the boulder (short side) this is the farthest left problem... The easiest way to the top.  Hop down from the boulder at this point, standard decent.

name: Peeler
description: This is the far right crack on the boulder... follow it to the top.

name: Perverse Traverse
description: Start on the hand rail in the middle of Birds Nest and traverse right all the way to Peeler and top out...  Good hands, little feet.

name: Super Stretch
description: Sit start a few feet right of Birds Nest. Work up a few feet then dyno/stretch out left to a far away pocket.  Side pull on the crack near the top and use friction to finish.

name: Bat Attack
description: Short, crimpy and slightly overhanging. Small roof crux right before anchor chains. Route arc's slightly to the climbers left.

name: The Catacomb Wall
description: This is an excellent wall with lots of foot and handholds galore!  The wall is flat until you get to the brain (approx 30' up) then it gradually pitches out.

name: Center Field
description: The left of the two cracks with a roof to pull near the start

name: Cracker Jack
description: Follow crimps and sloping pockets straight up the sandstone face.  Shares bolted anchor with Green Monster.

name: Green Monster
description: Climbs the wall close to the arete.  Route goes straight up the wall on crimps and curves to climbers left to anchors.

name: Left Field
description: Climb the wide crack with the large tree growing in the middle to a chossy thinner crack and top out.

name: Right Field
description: Start from a ledge and follow a thin finger crack up to a left leaning hand crack.

name: Doin' Time
description: Bouldery start up to roof, pull through the roof and continue up the easier slabby face.

name: Gargamel
description: Balancy bouldery start that leads to easy slab climbing.

name: Hot Monkey Love
description: This climb is slightly overhung and will dish out sloppers, monos, painful underclings and the like. Use the chicken head cautiously and enjoy the finishing crux. easy toprope access

name: Mono e Mono
description: Vertical face climbing up small edges and pockets.

name: Oh So Slippery
description: Climb the cracks up the dihedral.

name: S Crack
description: Start in the crack and follow it up the face.  Main crack tapers out near the top, traverse left to another finger crack and top out.

name: Shakey Dog
description: Follows a crack up to a small roof then out right onto a left facing sloppy flake.

name: Triangles
description: Follows a crack up a series of short triangular roofs
Start on pockets on the right side of the southeast face. Continue up the steep face on shallow pockets, thin rails and slopey edges.

name: Guantanamo Bay
description: Start low on the pocketed face in the center of the southeast side of the boulder.  Move left onto a rail and continue up the steep face on small crimps to larger ledges near the top.  Pull through the ledges and negotiate the tricky top out.

name: Hall Pass
description: Good foot holds, good hand holds, but has some variety including vertical pinches for the beginning climber or a warm up for others. It's a little mossy on top.

name: Hate Crime
