description: Start at the base of the arete on the left.  Smear your right foot and mantle up into a hand foot match on the lower ledge.  Climb the arete to a sloping ledge,  mantel up and get a high foot and step up to deep pockets on the upper left corner of the west face and top out.

name: Mean Gene
description: Work your way straight up the steep slab making use of good friction, shallow ripples and a few sloper pockets to a high chicken head and deep pockets at the top.  Top out in the grove.

name: Pickpocket
description: Start low on pockets in the center of the southeast face of the boulder.  Pick your way up heavily pocketed steep face and top out.

name: Smear Tactics
description: Start at the start for Mean Gene and friction traverse left into Hate Crime.  Smear your feet high and mantle onto the sloping ledge, press up into a hand foot match and reach up into good pockets above. Tops out at the top of Hate Crime.

name: Constant Gardener
description: Tall slab problem on the left side of the Garden Wall boulder.  Starts on underclings and moves straight up the face on small crimps to the top out.

name: Control Joint
description: Climb the fist and off hand crack in the middle of the Garden Wall boulder, follows crack to the top.

name: The Gate (project V?)
description: Start on two side pulls low on the boulder to the right of Control Joint and climb up to a chicken head. From there move up to the left making delicate moves on slopers to the top.  4/27/19 Chicken head has broken off, currently unclimbed with unknown new grade, currently a project please report any new  sends to update grade.

name: The Gate Escape
description: Start the same as for the Gate, once at the chicken head move right onto a series of good edges and follow to the top.  4/27/19 Chicken head has broken off of the Gate, use thin crimps/gaston in place of broken jug, now requires delicate high step to get onto the traverse ledges that lead to top out.  New grade V3.

name: Lake View Arete
description: Tallest problem on the Garden Wall boulder, follow the arete on the far left end and transitions onto the slab face near the top before topping out.

name: M.C.T.S.
description: Start on a good good edge and make a big move to a nice side pull.  Continue to top on crimps. (Only a select few know what the true meaning of the cryptic initials is).

name: Terrace Agronomy
description: Starts on low ledge to the left of Constant Gardener and move up and to the right following a series on big ledge on the steep slab.  Joins the top of Control Joint and tops out, watch out for the fern.

name: Big Red Snapper
description: The obvious arete route left of Blueberry Funk and Gingergay.  2 Bolts, 2 Bolt Anchor.

name: Blueberry Funk
description: The right of the two bolted lines that share anchors.  4 bolts 2 bolt anchor.

name: chiropterror
description: The southern most full-length route in the area starts below the vertical crack.  The easier face moves bring you to a small roof that requires fist and hand jams to bypass (this is the crux).  From here it is face climbing again.  Watch out for bats that like to catch rays on this rock face.  Also be careful tossing your rope down or dropping any gear, this route goes right over the main trail and is very close to the water.

name: Gingergay
description: Left of the two sport lines, shares anchors with Blueberry Funk.  4 bolts 2 bolt anchor.

name: Krepsik Problem
description: Steep cave problem on the right side before you reach the main buttress of The Rock. Sit start.

name: Ring Eater Crack
description: Chimney sized crack with lots of face climbing on edges.  Walk past bluff around first arete.  Crack will be obvious.

name: Unknown
description: This is the second crack you see after you reach the main wall.  Climb to the slabby face and sling the sketchy bolt with a nut.  Sack up and top it out.

name: Wasp!
description: Farthest crack to the right on this rock, next to the trail going to the top.  one well protected 5.8ish roof to a fun top out.

name: Backside Blue
description: Up! Top out could be crux.

name: Backside Red
description: Crux could be the top out. Don't fall.

name: Chossy Pockets
description: Furthest right line. Loads of pockets and good feet leading to the flat ledge top out.

name: Easter Island Arete
description: Sit start left hand in two finger pocket, right hand in good pocket bear hugging the arete and climb straight up.

name: Easter Island Blue
description: Interesting movement.

name: Easter Island Green
description: Could be tough for shorter climbers.

name: Easter Island Pink
description: Easy problem. Good for beginners.

name: Easter Sunday
description: Sit start low, left hand two finger pocket, right hand two finger divet. Move slightly left then up to a great shouldery undercling move and top out

name: Master Slabster
description: Amazing climb up the tallest section of the slab! Skate your way to the top, aiming for the two finger pocket as you go up.

name: Rev It Up
description: Sit start both hands on a ledge and small pocket on the narrow face of the boulder, climbing up the back face of the boulder through pinches, pockets and crimps. Make a committing move to the top. Stay off the front of the boulder until it’s time to top out.

name: Slab Blue
description: Just easy climbing to the top.

name: Slab Green
description: Crux is trusting your feet.

name: Slab Pink
description: Crux is getting off the ground and around the arete. Could be a big move to the top.

name: Slab Right
description: Work your way around to the right side of the slab. Utilizing feet on the back part of the slab.

name: Slab Yellow
description: Crux is down low. A few tenuous foot placements make things interesting.

name: Slabs Are People Too
description: Crux could be getting off the ground. Friction climbing at it's best! Finding the route might be your biggest challenge.

name: Acme
description: Stand start on two pockets bout chest high and climb up and right through pockets, topping out above the hand size crack. Fun problem

name: Alien Red
description: An easy slab climb. Nice warm up rock close to the entrance of the bouldering area.

name: Anvil Center Left Yellow
description: Easy climb up to a high traverse to the right.

name: Birds Nest
description: Start on a corner ledge, move straight up and behind you to get the demanding top out

name: Clinch
description: Climb through the flake to the good ledge, mantle over on to the blank slab and delicately climb through

name: Cracks So Easy Blue
description: Little Bit of Lie Backing up a short crack.

name: Fern Ridge Blue
description: Fun traverse starting at the left of the rock. Follow the ledge with under clings to its end. Then a 5 foot dyno to the left. Fantastic!

name: Fern Ridge Red
description: A little reachy for shorter folk.

name: First Ramp
description: Still up for grabs. Big moves to the top.

name: Get Your Rocks Off
description: Sit start very low two hands on a good ledge, bunched up, between some rocks on the ground (try not to dab the rocks!) head up the face through some pockets, heel hooks, and eventually jugs with an easy top out.

name: I'd Top That Red
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Instant Winner (red)
description: Sit start low right side of the boulder both hands on a good undercling. Move out left through ledges and pinches. Get over the lip in the center of the boulder and mantle up!

name: Instant Winner Blue
description: Starts with an under cling sort of pinch. A few moves to the left, then over a steep lip to finish.

name: Instant Winner Yellow
description: Easy gently sloped.

name: Long Haul
description: Fun traverse, a little pump.

name: Namco
description: Dominant line on the Pac-Man boulder. Compression style climbing with some techs moves on thin feet.  Sit start left hand on obvious side pull edge and right hand arete. Climb straight up the blank arete and top out

name: Pacman Direct (Red)
description: Move straight up the problem from a stand up start. First hold is usually chalked up and easy to spot.

name: Pacman Left Arete (Blue)
description: Move left from a stand up start towards the arete. Then move to the slab just left of the arete and to the top.

name: Pacman Right Arete (Yellow)
description: This is still up for grabs. Just work your way up the right side of the boulder, in front of the tree.

name: Pancake
description: Stand start on the good circular (pancake looking) hold, make a big move left to some sharp jugs and straight up

name: Pinch a loaf
description: There is a tree in the top for an anchor, great rock for beginners

name: Unnamed Red
description: A little high.

name: Infestation
description: Use the face holds and a little off widthing technique to gain a hand crack that will take you to the top.

name: Medusa
description: Good size hand crack that slants slightly to the left half way up the route before finishing at the top. Crux is the top just because of the balancy mantle move the gain the top of the wall. Crack takes gear well but can be a little dirty sometimes.

name: Two Screaming Nutz
description: Start on shelfs down low that take you to a slab face that leaves you searching holds. Once you balance your way to the finger crack, find a way to make your way to the top and claim victory.

name: (Dyno) Heaven is a Second
description: Start with hands as low as possible on the post in the picture, then dyno to the lip. Must be done in one move, without using crimps. I had to give the problem a rating but I have not sent it yet and am not sure what the grade should be because I didn't have a pad so I couldn't try it.     If you bad the FA, comment on this route and I will add your name for the FA. Please let me know your grade recommendation, as well.

name: Arch Classic
description: Work your way along the arch until holds no longer exist above the arch, then go up and over. Fun problem with one big, fun, shouldery move, but VERY slick, polished feet, which makes the problem very frustrating.     For a V4, follow the arch all the way to its end, using only holds on the arch.    NOTE: this problem was originally given 4 stars, however I have since then changed that. Its an OK problem, and although its a classic to the area, its a classic because of its obviousness as a boulder problem. 2 stars is much more suiting.

name: The Arete
description: Start as low as you can and work along the corner/arete of the concrete. Very self-explanatory, a bit harder than it looks.    NOTE: this is a four star because it is a classic that everyone climbs, it is a fun climb, but mainly its just something everyone seems to try at some point because of its obviousness.

name: Battlement Blitz
description: Start on the left face of the battlemount and traverse right. Two-move crux as you transition from the left to the front face with a difficult fall-in left hand to a crimp. Good holds at the start and finish.

name: Bauman's Problem
description: This problem is the left face of "The Arete", where you don't use the arete. Very balancey problem; it helps to attempt it when its cold, because it is very friction dependent.

name: East Arête
description: Highly balance-dependent slab problem that benefits from soft shoes and a good friction day. Similar difficulty to Bauman's Problem, but located on the right face of "the Arete". Arete is in.

name: Feels Like a Joke
description: Start in the pocket on the left face of the tiny battlement, move to crack on the rectangle parts of the battlement, then do fun move to the lip. Worth doing but not worth telling your friends about.

name: Full Arch Traverse
description: A classic to the area, this climb was attempted so many times that the flat, slopey feet on the arch are now extremely slick, making the climb basically a campus with annoyingly slippery feet. Personally, I have not found the climb to be much fun at all, especially since you are essentially down-climbing the second half of the climb (I should mention this is the harder half).

name: Gear and Beer
description: 'Trad' may be pushing it here - but if you're looking for a place to practice placing 2 pieces of gear, 15 feet or less off the ground, this is the route for you!

name: My Dirty Crack
description: Be a bold boulder-er and top out this high(ish) ball out or set up a top-rope and send it. Fun top out, which is do-able without grabbing the fence at the top.   Work your way along crimpy holds with some decent jugs up to the rectangular sandstone at the top. Watch out for a LOT of dirt near the top, which is required to top this out (pictured in beta photo).

name: Pocket 'n Lock it
description: This is the best bouldering problem in the area (in my opinion). Lots of surprisingly diverse moves that are fairly difficult.    Start two hands on a side-pull crack on the very left side of the Column. Work your way around the column (without using the rectangular bricks at the top of the column) on matchy crimps. Crux is either matching on a small crimp on the front of the pillar or going up with left hand to a jug up top (when rounding to the right side of the column). Tricky beta. Top out

name: Right Up
description: "This is the right dihedral formed between the main wall facing the road and the shorter, right white buttress (battlement). The wall height is low enough here to boulder if you are confident in pulling the top overhang."    Source: rockclimbing.com/routes/Nor…    Pretty good, easy holds on this one. A few interesting pockets. The corner allows for easy toping out. Holds are often wet after rain in this location. Watch for loose rocks at the top (shown in photo).

name: Sam's Traverse
description: Traverse Begins with hands on 2nd and 3rd blocks from turret. use blocks as the only handholds, either side pulling or just flat out gripping them. route ends with both feet on keystone. crux starts on the black rock, be careful coming off here and slipping your feet inside the arch

name: The Black Hole
description: Start low and left, move up on small ledges, traverse right up high to black hole.

name: The Cracken
description: Crack immediately when you turn the corner of the west-wall. Short bouldering problem with sadly boring moves. Lots of ways to cheat and not use the crack. Worth doing but nothing interesting here.

name: Spiderman's Traverse
description: AKA Ohio's Longest, Hardest Climb    This is a traverse across the entire West Wall. The route has only seen one confirmed ascent since it was established in 2009.   The crux is in the woods, so best to start there.    Expect to move up and down often just to find a better route. Bring chalk.

name: Unknown Right Lead
description: Follow crimps and crimpy slopers up and right to the first bolt, continue past to the top past one more bolt on jugs to the lip of the bridge.

name: Untitled Lead
description: Mostly crimpy holds, but there's a nice large square brick shortly after the first clip and an odd I shaped brick right before the last move that are nice and juggy. The top cap of the wall has 2 great holds to finish on as you transition to a top out or the fence to set an anchor. Some of the lower holds are a bit polished, but after after the first few feet they're good and rough.

name: Woodland Walk
description: Start on the two holds in the picture, do a few difficult moves up some small crimps, then the holds get really good and the problem is over. If its rained recently, look out for some gross holds at the top, the cracks can have water/mud in them... pretty gross stuff. Bring chalk.    Top out or just come down when you hit the limestone at the top.

name: Woods Traverse
description: Start on a rail and work along small crimps with balancy moves on one of the blankest of the wood sections.

name: #AdoptDontShop
description: Start sitting down. The crux in this problem is the throw/dyno to the left handed sloper depending on how long you are. Once you get his move you will continue working your way up the boulder using some pretty decent holds.

name: Blackfish
description: Start standing up with a double under cling holds. Work your way right and then up to a top out.

name: Blue Jacket
description: Sit down start, work your way up the boulder using pretty solid holds to a top out.

name: Chalahgawtha
description: Start down low on the under hang. The crux is the big throw with the right, followed by another throw with your left.

name: Eagle Powers
description: Start sitting down and work your way straight up the problem. Holds can be a little sandy and slippery.

name: Elm Traverse
description: Start standing up directly behind the tree. Move up and then traverse left across the face to a top out.

name: The Face
description: Stand up start, work your way straight up the boulder to a top out. Holds can be a little sharp and rough on the hands.

name: Frog Catcher
description: Start standing up and using the solid holds to work your way straight up the problem to a top out.

name: Green Tea
description: Start low and work yourself up the right side of the wall to top out.

name: Kerchak
description: Start standing up on the crimps. Then work your way up to the right. The crux is a big throw to a crimp.

name: Mossy Cleft
description: Stand up start then work your way up the route using a few crimps and mossy slopers to an easy top out.

name: Paint Street
description: Tricky start and first couple of moves. Traverse to the right and then up to an easier top out.

name: Roundabout
description: Start on the right side of the face and traverse low cross the entire face. You can continue traversing around the entire boulder or you can climb up for a top out. Nice boulder to warm up on. Nice problem to work footwork.

name: Shawnee
description: Start under the over hang and work yourself up. Once you get yourself up on the ledge work left and mantel to the top out.

name: Super Meat Boy
description: Start from the undercling pocket and crimp and make some big moves up to the jug for a fun mantle finish.

name: Tecumseh
description: Stand up start, work your way up to the right using a sloper and a crimp. Then a big throw to a nice hold. Continue to work your way up the boulder to a top out.

name: Bloody Arm
description: Start standing with left hand on side pull and right hand in the little pocket. Work your way straight up the problem. Using little crimps and slopers. Footwork is super important for this slab problem.

name: Chesnut Traverse
description: Start standing up, move from right to left to a top out. The crux is within the first couple moves when you down climb across the face.

name: Door Knob
description: Stand up start, the crux is the next move which is holding onto the sloper and then grabbing a little knob. Then you will have to almost mantle yourself onto the big sloper and then it is an easy top out from there.

name: Fish Hook
description: Start standing up, work your way up the problem with small finger crimps to the top out.

name: Horndog
description: Start standing up and move up and to the right. Grab the large horn and proceed to top out.

name: The Kimura
description: Climb straight up the problem. Problem is very mossy and dirty which makes footwork a little sketchy. Should clean up once climbed more though.

name: Main Street Traverse
description: Easy and fun warm up traverse across the boulder to a top out.

name: Patience
description: Start on the left side of the big boulder and traverse yourself across the face of the rock. This requires good footwork, finger jams, and presses. After traversing across, work yourself up the face of the wall to a top out. Patience is required to complete this route.

name: Scoliosis
description: Fun warm up route. Start standing up and pull yourself and work your way up the crack to a top out.

name: Zlatan
description: Start standing up and work your way up the side of the boulder to a top out.

name: Bubble
description: Start low on good slot to the left of the bulge. Make a big move right and follow jugs straight up to top out.

name: Kings Crown
description: Start with small crimps, move up using small crimps and mono pockets to small jugs. Small jugs and slopers to the top.

name: Mavericks Boulder, Gleaming the Tube V3+
description: The problem starts on the very left side under the bulge on the south face.  Its starts with hands matched on an obvious large pinch and works straight up using pockets to a great incut crimp and finishing the same as pulling tubes.  The crux will either be the star,t or once you are on the good pockets, stabbing up and right to the good crimp.  Beta Video Link  youtu.be/Moy0EMTiC_w

name: Mavericks Boulder, Pulling Tubes V6
description: On the south side of this boulder(facing towards Little Miami River) the rock appears to have a natural rip curl hence the name "Mavericks Boulder".  Pulling tubes starts on the right side of the south face with both hands matched on the same side-pull, and works left through small pockets and then climbs straight up the bulge on far left of boulder to good holds and tops out.  Good feet but small pockets on the face make for a fun traverse using only pockets to nice holds for the top out.    Link to video that climbs this problem:  youtu.be/6kyFKrZaP-U

name: Mavericks Boulder, Ripping waves
description: This problem starts on a small ledge/rail on the left side of the South face and works up and right to a somewhat reachy match on a bomber lip then high heel hook and top out.  The crux is going out to the bomber lip and matching, feet will cut!  Fun warmup problem.  Beta Video Link  youtu.be/RbBgkV243DA

name: Midas
description: Easy boulder up left side of vertical flake. Top out and climb down the other side.

name: The other proj
description: A sit start to a clearly previously climbed line. The first three moves on small crimps are rather thuggy and the redpoint crux seems to be a foot sequence of some kind but after that the top outs rather easy if a little dirty at times.

name: Over the River and Through the Woods
description: Starting from the left edge of the boulder at a hanging position then traverse across the flat face of the boulder to the section that juts out. Then climbing around, underneath the jut out. Move up the right side using the jugs climb left and top out where the top of the jut out meets the flat faced boulder.

name: Palm Reading
description: Climb from the right side of the vertical flake up then across to the left to top out.

name: Pride Rock Boulder, Swamp Ass
description: Starts in the cave on the left of the boulder on a small block. Use toe hooks to pull the lip and keep it together to get to the jugs and top out.

name: The proj
description: Starts low on a sharp crimpy match- toehook deep into the cave to get off the ground then the crux second move is one of the gnarliest lock offs out to the ledge of the small roof. Maintain body tension and get your other hand out to another tiny intermediate and then up to a jug and it should be pretty easy cruisin from there. Probably been climbed before but it's not on here so.

name: Anxious Arrival
description: Start with your hands in the crack in the middle of the roof.  This is the same start as Dry Route.  Climb left, following Dry Route, dropping down after the crux to link into Lunge or Plunge.  The hardest section is linking the problems, but there still is a pump crux at the finish.

name: Bangarang
description: Route was developed right before the Mad River Gorge was officially opened in May 2017. You might need to start off a cheater stone straight into the bouldery start. After earning the grade before clipping the first bolt cruise up some fun movements until the last few moves test whether or not you brought enough gas for the whole trip.

name: Blind Spot
description: Start same as "Lunge or Plunge" but make a few powerful compression moves out right to finish on "Dry Route".

name: Campus Ousside
description: Start with ‘what just bit me’ to the outside lip. Traverse the outside lip and top out at ‘Lukewarm sausage.’  This is very similar to 'Campus Traverse' except you make the leftward traverse on the lip of the cave, not on the inside. This permutation makes the climb a lot more core intensive since it's really difficult to keep feet on the for the lip traverse.   Unsure of grade here. It’s significantly harder than campus traverse but is also juggy through and through.

name: Campus Traverse
description: Start on What Just Bit Me to roof then traverse left on flake. Awesome transition to left wall and easy pull up to top-out.

name: Choss Direct
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: CTB
description: Historic route, and the only bolted line that existed on Amusement Wall before the Mad was opened. CTB has a colorful background story. Ask Jim if you see him out at the Gorge. ;)

name: Dingus Prince
description: Start matched under low roof with very strange feet-first bicycle on lip. Move out to little pinch at lip, bump and climb straight up to stance on face.

name: Double Blind (Blindspot Low)
description: Start all the way under the roof on left facing jug. Pull through crimps to block, finish same as Blindspot.

name: Dry Route
description: This route starts in the deep crack between Lunge or Plunge and Power Play.     Start with a hand in the crack and work your way left and up. Lie back and get creative with your feet. Pull up and out of the cave to finish.    Please comment with grade suggestions and if you know of a different FA.

name: Duplicity
description: Start left hand in pocket, right hand side pull. Move through pockets to deadpoint move. Finish on flat jug.

name: Easily Amused
description: Only wide crack on A.M wall. Yes... it was once filled with trash.

name: Everything’s comin’ up aces
description: Start on l “hey look ma I made it” then keep Traversing on the good jugs till you go around the corner  instagram.com/p/BxYXMdgBoqN…

name: Fable
description: Sit start on two small pockets with heel above hands, cross to good slot and traverse left to jug at lip.

name: Gateway
description: A low traverse that links up with the lowest sit start of Starter Pack. Crux is some tricky footwork leading into a left hand bump-drop into the starting crimps of the Starter Pack sit start.

name: Hang Ten
description: Sit start under Shimmy Shimmy Ya on the far left of Amusement Wall. Traverse right and up to the outside lip of the cave. Continue to traverse along the lip to top out on Slot Machine.  The line stays below the large ledge to the left of the cave lip. Although not an eliminate, the intent is to stay below the level of lip until the top out.

name: Hey look Ma I made it.
description: Eliminate boulder. Start on weird side pull and ok pocket at lip of the bottom roof then go up to the crack jug, then out to crimp and finish on the obvious  big jug before the arete.

name: Indoor v7
description: Start 15 feet right of "Pocket Rocket" matched on an obvious chalked up edge to the left of a crack. Traverse left, making some big, sequential moves on cool grips to the start of "Pocket Rocket". Dyno or crimp your way to the finishing jug and drop.

name: It’s Medicinal
description: Stand start on low left hand side pull and right hand pocket pinch on opposite sides of the arete. Climb straight up the arete, finishing on the jug just below the roof.

name: Knope We Can
description: Somewhat challenging start leads to fun climbing on the arete. Great warmup for other routes at Amusement Wall and generally fun climb.

name: Lukewarm Sausage
description: Start on good jug below yellowish spot. Cross into sidepull, finish up and left on crimps.

name: Lunge or Plunge
description: Start on blocky undercling, paste feet, and do a long move to a finger bucket. Work your feet and swing out to a sloper. Traverse a few moves left and finish on slot machine. Fun, gymnastic problem.

name: Lunge or Plunge Low
description: Start all the way under the roof on left facing jug. Pull through crimps to block, finish same as Lunge or Plunge.

name: The Monarch
description: Start on flake in middle of boulder make big move right to crimp and grab finish jug.

name: Pocket Rocket
description: One move wonder!   Start in the deep pockets at head height and get airborne, launching up and left for the massive ledge.    The ledge tends to stay wet days after rainfall.

name: Pocket Rocket Man
description: A few long moves on big ledges to bomber hold above anchors.

name: Pondering Physics
description: Start in the crack on the far right side of the boulder. Follow the crack up and left on good holds, then top out on dirty holds.

name: Power Play
description: Start underneath roof on good holds. Eventually bump your left hand to a good pinch in roof. Set your feet and do a wild drive by to a jug. Drop off, or if you are tied in continue up the sport route that starts on the finishing jug

name: Psychedelic Schoolteacher
description: Start low on two slots, move straight up using mixture of slots and crimps. Big move to jug. Finish through "campus traverse V5"

name: Rocktober Festival
description: Sit start below, and then climb to the start holds of Pocket Rocket. Find some long but static moves instead of jumping to the same ledge.

name: Scooby Doo
description: Difficulty depends on where you start. Eases to big holds at top.

name: Scrappy
description: Start as far back in cave as possible for full-effect. Some really nice moves on face, eases at top.

name: Shaggy
description: Knee-bar start.

name: Shimmy Shimmy Ya
description: Sit start on the corner, feet on detached rock. Work right on good holds then straight up to slightly dusty finish.

name: Skull Crusher
description: Start on a flat hold to the right of "Dry Route". Make a big reach to a slot at the lip, then core up and make some dead points to get to the jug.

name: Slappy McCracken
description: Slappey McCracken was developed in May 2017 and is located on Amusement Wall.

name: Slingshot
description: Great pockets help you get onto the wall and crux is getting over the bulge just above the second bolt. Watch out for mud on top, but key hands will help you get to the top. Really enjoyable moderate for the area.

name: Slot Machine
description: Start on low edge match, follow the slots up and swing out for the sloper. Grab the left hand under cling and make your way to the jug

name: Sparky
description: Pretty sustained 10ish.

name: Starter Pack
description: Sit start on the jugs and throw to a Gaston (V1). V0 stand start. My favorite warm up in the area. My climbing partner and I have been warming up here for a long time. Top out doesn’t add anything and is muddy. Not sure if we did it first or others. Feel free to pm me if you were the FA and want a different name!

name: Stella
description: Climb the same line as "Anxious Arrival", but instead of topping out "Lunge or Plunge" continue on and finish the same as "Campus Ousside". Climbs like a route.

name: Tastes Like Burning
description: This is a new route that was added in May 2017.

name: The Teets
description: Sit start with your hands on the ledge. Moving straight up, squeeze some beta out of the teets, gain some pockets, and then pull on crimps till you reach the jug right of the small roof.  The finish jug is above and left of the finish for Pocket Rocket/Rocktober Festival.

name: Three Blind Mice
description: Start on jug undercling under roof, same as Lunge or Plunge(low). Climb out the roof and right through the block feature avoiding jugs at the top of Blind Spot make big move to crimp and finish same as Skull Crusher.

name: What Just Bit Me
description: Start on flakey jug near the ground, then work your way up on to the roof using more flakey jugs. At the end of the roof take a poor match to move a heel out to the right and pull on that to a good side pull and finish on the next large flake. The route is a bit dirty, some shrubbery near the finish and top out.

name: Whatchamacallit
description: Left the old anchor intact . Don't know who climbed it...when,...if ..or in what style.Could be around the same age as the pitons in Dr. Evil.    Pretty tough sequence of pockets.

name: Wu Who
description: Nice crack route. Probably soloed along time ago..although topping out could be really sketchy. Can be led trad.

name: Baby's First Solo
description: Start low on slab section, mantle up midway to long moves and lockoffs.

name: Cave Cudi
description: Start with both hands on the vertical crack in the small cave area.  Move up to two large jugs accompanied by an optional side pull jug.  Make a dynamic move to the jug rail in the center of the face and then make another large move to jugs on the lip of the topout.  Great climb and very safe unlike most of the climbs in Back Alley.  Also this climb isn't technically really part of Back Alley and if anyone knows a better location for it (potentially furthest left side of Fern Buttress?) let me know and I will get it moved on here.

name: Open Project 1
description: Easy side pulls up to large edges, overcome the fear of the crap landing to pull through top.

name: Open Project 2
description: Crimp up to possible dyno out to horizontal flake (will test security on cleaning). Great feet to end

name: 12 Pack
description: Classic route. Begin on jugs to a technical middle section. Watch out for the run-out between the first & second bolt as there is ground fall potential. If you can pull the bottom moves though, the middle should be no problem.

name: 6 pack
description: Start is crux although the top is a little in your face as well.

name: Dear Jim
description: 1 bolt protects a hard to protect start and 1 bolt is up top to protect traverse to anchors. Climb crack in between. This route takes nuts and cams galore. It is a very good route for beginning tradsters comfortable at this grade.

name: Devine Root
description: Starts under first bolt and traverse left briefly into Root for Me. Clip 2nd bolt and trend up right to anchors. It is believed this route was bolted by Mike Johnson in the late 80s.

name: Diagonal To Nowhere
description: Begin climbing the crack for 20 feet on good holds and good feet. Beware of the loose blocks towards the middle of the crack while placing gear. Head right for the chains at the top of the crack.

name: Garbage Warrior
description: This is a great route! A sequential, powerful start leads to a surprise ending.

name: Greasy Spoon
description: Thin face to a tricky bulge then traverse to SWW anchors.

name: Kept to Memory
description: Nice pockets and features at the bottom lead to a blank middle section crux where tiny crimps and good balance are needed to get further up the wall.

name: Knuckle Up
description: Long moves lead to a good rest before run to the top.

name: Man with a Beard
description: Chossy start to stopper crux at 2nd bolt.  Find relief on small horizontal seems.  Follow crack up to anchors.

name: New World Order
description: Begin on small crimps with technical moves. Climb through several bolts to reach much easier climbing towards the top of the wall.

name: Nowhere
description: One set of anchors with 3 different starts. .

name: The Phat and the Dope
description: Beginning on some small pockets, crimp your way up this the route on tiny holds with some very physical moves to some slightly overhanging chains.

name: The Pinch
description: Probably want to stick clip 2nd bolt, or be REALLY strong. Originally intentioned to stay left thru micro edges as Man With a Beard.It can be done by trending right on bigger holds as The Pinch.

name: Recyclable Stone
description: Stick clip second bolt. Campus till you gain feet. Shake out at big ledge and fire through crux. Clipping anchors can be interesting if you choose wrong hold to clip from.

name: Recycler
description: Rumored to be the first route bolted in Springfield in the early 90s. Look for 3 stacked roofs with several fixed draws.

name: Root for Me
description: The start is not really in line with the rest of the routes difficulty, but its a good one nonetheless. Utilize the crack, balance up and over a few ledges and clip anchors

name: Sandy River Blues
description: Start below the bolts on "She Keeps It on the Mantel". Boulder up and into the crack. Follow the crack up and right using secure jams to gain the right facing flake. Continue up to the first roof moving out left to gain a large crack up to the second roof. Move left to clip the third bolt continuing to the anchors on "She Keeps It on the Mantel".

name: Sanford and Son
description: Recycler to 3rd bolt, move right on side-pulls and knee bar to clip 4th. Gain blunt arete using fierce pockets.  Clip 5th chest high then be rewarded with fantastic pockets at the roof.

name: Scrub-a-Dub-Dub
description: Great moderate route with a crux that makes you think about half way up. Since it is a brand new route, it is a little dirty towards the top, but that should cleanup with more climbers on the wall.

name: She Keeps it on the Mantel
description: Don't be tempted by the tree or anything left of it. Strictly off route.

name: Sifter
description: Great workout or warm-up when dry..

name: Slippery When Wet
description: Classic route. Begin on some moderate moves with some tricky feet. Continue through the crux as it becomes slightly overhung. Be sure to take advantage of the dyno up top, as this is what makes the route so good! This route stays fairly dry after a rain... except for one key spot (which explains the name).

name: The Snatch
description: Stick clip high first bolt. Figure out crux, Take a break at the  2nd clip before the exciting finish.

name: Springfield Arch
description: Undercling an arching crack to under roof. Traverse right to a bolt. Placing protection can be strenuous but crack eats up cams. Clip bolt and pull roof using crack. Mixed route.

name: Squeeze Box
description: Moderate face leads to a thin crack below big ledges.

name: Steve-O
description: Delicately balance and crimp your way up hidden holds to the roof and figure out how to clip anchors.

name: The Surprise
description: Bouldery start to a insecure slabby finish.

name: Top Heavy
description: Thin face moves to overhang crux. The 2nd bolt is too dicey to clip. I would haul up a stick clip until I come up with something better. The run to anchors from 2nd bolt is 5.5ish.

name: Trash Compactor
description: Great route! Sustained route to great finish.

name: Trash Talk
description: Start off cheater stone on two shallow pockets. Campus up to two hand ledge and use pockets and small edges to gain the face. A strenuous clip leads to the crux and then easier climbing up top.

name: Trash.com
description: Start on pockets off cheater stone. Hanging start. Make use of good pockets and small edges to anchors up and right.

name: The Underling aka Jim's Route
description: Using consecutive underclings and precise foot work, climb your way to a blind finish.

name: Chain Mail Hula Skirt
description: Fun route that takes big gear. Bring your wide toys, kids!

name: Cracking Point
description: This route goes up the center of the face right in between Lost Soles and Chain Mail Hula Skirt.  It's a great line but the gear placements can be tricky for shorter people.  Some easy face climbing brings you into a large indent in the wall where you can compose on decent hands and feet before continuing to the harder part of the route.  Exit the indent out to the right and pull your way up into the vertical crack where Lost Soles and Chain Mail Hula Skirt intersect to get to the anchors.  If you exit the indent to the left you will just end up traversing into the start/middle of Lost Soles which is considered to be off route.  The crux of this route involves a left hand pinch/sidepull that you grab shortly after exiting the indent out right.  From this handhold you throw for the crack with your right hand and then finish on easier terrain.  The safest way to do the route is to blindly place gear in the crack above you before pulling the crux moves which is why I mention that it may be difficult for shorter people because if you cant reach the crack from below the crux you will have to pull some decently hard moves without any gear in.  It sounds like blind placements would be sketchy but the crack above the crux is so perfect for .75 cams that you can confidently place them without looking.  I will say it might be worth taking a look at it on toprope before going for the lead just to be on the safe side.

name: Excellent Ella
description: Classic route. This route ascends face directly under chains. Highly featured with great pockets. Excellent first lead for a newer outdoor climber, or warm up route for the area.

name: J-Ella
description: Classic route. This route takes the line of bolts directly right of S Crack. Climb thin face moves to roof.

name: Jared the Juggernaut
description: Classic route. Climb arete using big pockets and cracks. Great first lead or warm up to the area.

name: Lost Soles
description: Lost Soles begins by walking up the sequence of ledges out left until you get high enough to place your first piece of gear in the crack.  Then traverse out right using the horizontal crack to place protection until it begins to run into a vertical crack that brings you to the chains above.  The horizontal crack that follows the traverse offers excellent placements and solid handholds for fiddling with gear.  Be very careful not to mess with any of the loose rock above the cave to the left!  I would recommend avoiding even going far enough left that you are standing under the loose rock (the red line in the picture goes further left than is needed).  The climb can be started as soon as your hands can reach the crack. The loose rock is avoidable but because of the potential danger this climb has been given an R rating.

name: Right Arete
description: Classic route, but not really climbed on gear much. Most folks stick to Excellent Ella and maybe do this as a variation on top rope.   The start is a bit run out but easy. Staying right on arete to begin, slowly trend left to anchors above Excellent Ella.

name: S Crack
description: Classic route. Climb "S" curved crack. Awkward placing gear but fun route and decent first lead. There is a top rope variation to the left of crack as well.

name: Super Dads
description: Classic route. Mad River Gorge's semi overhanging jug hall. Make big moves on positive holds.

name: Caller ID
description: Traverse with nice ledges for feet throughout the first half that disappear into quite small footholds that require some precision. Start with feet on lowest ledge, left hand on good crimp right hand up and slightly over on other good crimp. Use low ledges to walk left until they run out while walking hands left using side pulls and a gaston. Hands continue up to a nice jug then left following the small overhang using a series of good holds to finish. Finish far left, matching on the undercling in top left corner of picture

name: The Dirty Dozen
description: Start on obvious jug, move into two two-finger pockets.  Make a reachy move into a slot, continue left into a super deep pocket, finish on obvious jug. Stay underneath the rail the entire time.

name: Gettin' Dirty With It
description: Super fun sit start to two great jugs. Large reach up to decent ledge. Traverse left and top out WITHOUT the tree.

name: Renegade
description: For this boulder, don't use any of the surroundings for hands/feet.  This means that you will have to campus the first few moves until you get high enough to get your feet on the boulder.  Left hand starts on a decent pocket and right hand starts on a two finger pocket with a place for your thumb.  Campus your hands up until you can get a left foot heel hook on the large jug a couple inches above the left hand start hold.  Once you get the heel hook, get the best left hand you can find and stand up on the heel to grab a high right hand sidepull (this move is the crux).  After gaining the sidepull, you should be able to get your feet properly under you and find good hands top get to the topout.  There's a few different ways you can go at the top that are all fairly easy but I found that heading out right towards the spike at the top was the most secure and cleanest way to top out.  Maybe if some of the mud at the top gets cleaned off then topping out directly up the center might be preferable.  Just be careful at the top, the further left you go, the worse the rock quality gets, the muddier it gets, and the landing starts to get sketchy because of the rock behind/bellow you.  Check the photos and their descriptions for more information.  Also I just wanted to add that if you don't want to do the full topout, you can just climb until you get both hands either on or above the horizontal crack that goes across the entire boulder about a foot above the right hand side pull that you use during the crux of the climb.  At this point you have done all of the parts of the climb that give it the grade and can still drop off very safely.  There is a picture that highlights the more useful holds for the topout  and in the picture anything circled (except for the lowest circle, which is really a two finger pocket)  would work as a finish hold for a safe dropoff.

name: Breakfast Frisbee
description: Scramble up the slope to stickclip first bolt. Start low on the sharp sidepull. Getting a high left foot may be the easiest move. Sustained hard 12 crimpfest with little or no feet. May need to clean the ledge right of the anchors for this one to go.

name: Cautionary Tale
description: Start on obvious jug climb straight up through increasingly difficult move to crux finish. Finish on three finger flat pocket.

name: Fresh Squeezed
description: Obvious overhanging fin feature detached from the wall. Start under the feature compressing on on a slopey edge for the left hand and and the juicy undercling for the right hand. Figure out the feet and fire to a pinch. Slap your way up the rest of the problem and end at a sloper jug on the left side of the fin and drop off. You could continue up to the top on 5.8 terrain but the rock quality is questionable and the walk off lengthy.

name: Green Thumb
description: This is the 2nd route on the buttress. Balance up thin seam, trending left after the 2nd bolt. Keep moving up and left to finish on anchors of Where the Green Fern Grows. Cleaning can be a bit of a challenge. Be careful unclipping first bolt.

name: Properly Teased (AKA Freshly Squeezed low)
description: Start on the hueco jug out far right and low. Move left while throwing some heel hooks to the "juicy" undercling that is one of the start holds of Freshly Squeezed. Span the gap to compress the block and then climb Freshly Squeezed. I think this problem adds a fun move to the original and squeezes a little more climbing out the detached boulder. I have graded this v5 since I think the original problem goes at around v4. Also, let me know if this has already been done before or if I completely misread the original problem's description.

name: Spore
description: Sit start on jug just above lip, go left to small two finger pocket grab intermediate and make big move to flat jug. Finish up and right. Good holds to the left are off.

name: Where the Green Fern Grows
description: Classic route. Route begins under small roof with a few thin moves. Pull roof to easier climbing. Moving out right after roof makes it spicier and a shade harder.

name: Asymptomatic
description: Start on block left of prow. Climb right through sidepulls and good feet. Traverse out right and finish on flat jug.

name: Bend and Stretch
description: A fun traverse with good movement and a variety of holds. Start on jug side pulls, move right to slanted crimps with low smeary feet, up to a series of slopers, into a side pull to move around the small prow. Move right to "top out" on the starting hold for Bracken.

name: Bracken
description: Stand start on jugs climb straight up and finish on jug.

name: Garden Path
description: Stand start slab walk up good feet to gain side pulls and finish on flat jug.

name: Intersectionality
description: Start on block jug, traverse left under belly feature. Continue through sidepulls on smeary feet. Climb lay back feature making big move to finish jug. Flake at the base of the cliff under the prow is off.

name: Monologue
description: Start on block to the right of prow, same as Intersectionality. Climb left under belly feature and straight up prow, Finish on block jugs at top of prow. Flake at base of cliff under the prow is off.

name: Unnamed
description: Start on jug sidepulls and climb the flake to the 'faux' top out.

name: Lava Lamp
description: Sit start on good pockets. Bump left and match, swoop the corner and shuffle up and left on good feet.

name: Shag Carpet
description: Sit start on side pull and chickenhead, up and right on easy holds. Mind the moss.

name: The Dangler
description: This route starts with left hand on a large pocket on the face and your right hand on a small hold under the roof with your left foot heel hooked to keep you from touching the ground.  The easiest way to get out of the start position is to follow the large pockets and jugs in the crack that trend off to the right.  If you are having trouble with the boulder you can start with your hands switched and your right foot heel hooked.  It will drop the difficulty down to V1ish because it lets you skip some of the harder start moves.

name: Short Changed
description: Start with left hand on an undercling beneath the overhang and right hand on one of the larger pockets on the face. You will have to get a good right foot heel hook to stay off of the ground.  Move your left hand out to the lip of the face and then slowly bump your hands up with the small holds on the face until you reach the jugs at the top of the face to get to the easy topout.

name: Abominable Traverse
description: Start on low jug on far right side of boulder. Traverse left trough pockets and side-pulls topping out same as Zach Galifianakis.

name: Afternoon Delight
description: Super slimy if it's just rained, will need some cleanup. Start in the obvious jug at stomach/waist height and make the big move out left.

name: Afternoon Direct
description: Start in jug, same as Afternoon Delight, climb through a couple small edges and make big move to ledge. Continue to climb through good holds. Top out just left of arete.

name: In the Presence of Greatness
description: This short powerful problem ascends the prominent overhanging arete on the left end of the boulder just off the trail. If not for the bad landing, it would be a good boulder problem. But since we don't climb for shoe deals, we put a one bolt anchor.

name: Innocuous
description: Stand start on two opposing jug sidepulls, move through small edges to low crux. Moderate climbing on weird split finger grips to easy top out.

name: Offwidth Problem
description: Offwidth/layback problem

name: Ped Xing
description: Sit start on the jug rail and work your way left to the end of the boulder. A great way to play on the fun holds this boulder has to offer. Alternatively, one could split off onto Zach Galifianakis for a solid 25 feet of climbing.

name: Zach Galifianakis
description: Begins with two finger pockets and up to a flake. Then back into pockets. Top needs cleaning.  Update 5/27/19 Cleaned the top. Stays wet though.

name: (Closed due to loose rock) Tire Fire
description: *Route closed due to loose rock at top of route* Climb the shallow inverted dihedral, making liberal use of side pulls and shallow pockets, to a big move at the broken section of cliff. The top looks worse than it is. Beware of loose stone.  *Above information from Springfield Gorge Climbers Guide by J. Joshua Hellstrom (2013)

name: a calling
description: Work your way up left or right of the bolt line to figure out the crux. Enjoyable top. Bolted in 2019.

name: B's Wax
description: Thin face moves then big ledges to the shared anchors of Roadside-Disrtraction.

name: Crimp Slap
description: Begin with your left hand on a pretty bad low pocket and your right and on a perfect crimp with a spot for your thumb.  Begin the problem by slapping a sloper with your left hand and then bumping your left hand to a high sidepull.  The sidepull has a bit of a lip to it at the highest point that makes it a usable hold.  Next move your right hand from the crimp to a weird hold 2-3 feet directly above the crimp.  Then bump your left hand up to a pinch that can also be used as a sidepull and bring your right hand up to a two finger pocket sidepull on the right side of the arete feature.  After you get this hold and get your feet under you, grab the jug on the left side of the arete near the top and then finish the boulder by matching both hands on the jug at the very top of the arete feature.  Most people will probably climb this boulder different than I did but that's the beta I used.  There is a large hold in the crack just left of the first sloper in the problem  that looks awfully incising to try to throw to but I found getting out to it is harder than the route was intended to be and takes you pretty far off route to the left.

name: Drop Zone
description: Work straight up from the first bolt or use the right facing crack to gain easier ledges.

name: Meltdown
description: Climb straight up the black streak using small crimps to negotiate the roof.   *Information comes from Springfield Gorge Climbers Guide by J. Joshua Hellstrom (2013)*

name: Ravages of Time
description: To the left of Drop Zone. Followed muddy streak. Bolts removed, but route listed here for historical purposes.

name: Razor Ledge
description: Grab the large horizontal and work yourself into the depression. Smear and crimp thru the crux to reach larger holds and move right to pull the roof.

name: Roadside Distraction
description: West facing corner crack with huge roof before you get to Smokey.

name: Smokey
description: Classic route. Ease up to a great ledge then muscle the roof using a phenominal crack. Trend right after the 3rd bolt to finish on big jugs and bomber top just right of anchors. Take a sit down and enjoy the view..

name: thumber
description: Use small holds down low to gain good ledges for clipping stances. Work your way through the crux to the large ledge at the finish. Bolted in 2019.

name: White Lightning
description: Climb up short slab to below roof for exciting 2nd clip. Dance your way up and over roof. A precision move leads to easier climbing.     - Information from Springfield Gorge Climbers Guide (2013) by J. Joshua Hellstrom

name: You Sure?
description: Wide flaring crack. Takes pro easily.

name: Honey Pot
description: Go straight up. You may take a swing if you falter. Thin low and big pockets at top.

name: Looks Like Rain
description: Bring some small cams and tricams for the mail slots and bigger gear to build an anchor in the upper fist crack. Double up for the slight runout.Traverse to fixed anchors if needed.

name: Old warmup route?
description: Good right hand and three finger pocket left hand start holds. End matched as shown in photo.

name: Stout and Round
description: Takes small nuts and cams. Look for the bomber V slot on the right bulge below the big ledge. Take advantage of the super deep pocket on the upper face.

name: What Tiggers Do Best
description: Carefully balance your way to huge ledge under roof, and find the awesome pockets to get to the finish. Lots of fun!

name: 1.5 Kids
description: Start on opposing side pulls, crimp up and long reach to layback. Stay right of arete and don't use mossy steps on left for topout. Fun feet!

name: 401k
description: Start right crimp, left side pull. Long move up and finish on 1.5 Kids' topout.

name: Remy's Spuddies
description: Sit start on the large flake and follow the arete to the top using the occasional foot and hand hold on the left face

name: Reza’s Hole
description: This route is a traverse Start is the same as Remy’s spuddies with low feet to the right then right hand goes up to a 2 finger pocket and left hand goes to the left onto a decent hold with a thumb catch re - position feet and stretch your left hand out pretty far into another 2 finger pocket bring left foot farther out onto what’s basically a smear and you will be in the splits cross right hand under left onto a crimp and use pockets all the way up to Where 1.5 kids finished

name: Uptight Neighbors
description: Cross start on pocket and crimp, work your way up the arete with an undercling and some fancy footwork.

name: Walk the Plank
description: This low ball is great! Sit start on the far right hand side on an incut crimp. Walk your heels and toes along the plank until you get to the end where a big move pulls you over the lip and on top!

name: Flight Pattern
description: grade should reflect difficulty once cleaned up. Start matched on jug. Traverse right to left along the rim. Start from the walk off area, around the beak feature to top out above the beak. Low boulder feature underneath beak, as well as small out cropping on ledge around the beak are on (pictured). Once clean, removal of the Boulder feature underneath beak  and the outcropping for the left foot on the ledge should make this climb significantly harder.

name: The Parrot
description: Start on jug, make large left hand move to decent hold.  Move to the beak looking feature and then top out.

name: Polly
description: Start on the same starting jug as the parrot, but move straight up the right face

name: Pinocchio's Whale
description: Sit start beneath the little overhang. Start with your right hand on the good sidepull and sort out how to pull over the bulge.

name: Climbin in Sperrys
description: Start on the lowest ledge with your right foot in the pocket. Continue following the ledges to the lip. This was first done in Sperrys

name: Floating Bridges
description: Stand start at bottom of sloping arete, move through edge and pocket to middle of arete. Figure out your feet to gain jug ledge and top out.

name: In Transit
description: Start low squeezing feature climb straight up using feature and a couple face holds.

name: Jitterbug Jive
description: Start on the farthest right ledge and trend left to merge in to "Climbin in Sperrys"

name: Keel Hulled
description: Start on high crimps with good feet on the left hand side of the face, make a long move right to a good crimp before finishing with some delicate movements

name: Reel-ly Retired
description: Start as low as you can on the right arete and follow it to the top using good feet on the face.

name: Don't Be a Pirate
description: Double hand low start using horizontal slot. Climb straight up the arete and top out. Try to stay in between the two vertical cracks on the left and right side of the arete.

name: I Believe In You
description: Sit start low on horizontal ledge. Climb up on right side of arete. Top out.

name: Left Crack Route
description: Climb the crack starting as low as possible. The lower you start, the harder it is. Top out through the depressed ledges.

name: Never Leave Neverland
description: Start in double handed shield plate down low and right. Traverse left while moving slightly up until you reach the blanker section of wall. Head up and top out.

name: Think Happy Thoughts
description: Sit start low using telephone-isa hold on left side of platform, climb straight up, using only holds on the left of the vertical crack. Top out.

name: Tick Tock Traverse
description: Mantle start on the short rock in between the down paths, work your way clockwise around the entire boulder. End on the mantle you start on.

name: Tinker Toes
description: Start low on slanted ledge, move up through thin pockets to bomber left hand. Use pig nostrils for full effect and top out.  Tinker Nose variant without left jug is harder (probably in the V3 range).

name: Billy Bones Last Words
description: Start low in depression with your hand in lowest slot. Move up through the pockets, and then top out on some suspicious rock.

name: Buried Treasure
description: Double hand start in slot with feet tucked under rock on small ledge. Move out from underneath rock to good hands halfway up. Balance over feet to move over bulge onto top. Watch out for loose rocks on top holds.

name: Hidden Gems
description: Low start on the corner with the two handed diagonal slot. Follow the diagonal crack up and right until it ends. Climb up using pockets and jugs to finish to the top.

name: Treasure Map
description: Double hand undercling on the far right side low on the rock. Stay low, traverse through the depression and around the bulging corner. Don't go up until you pull the corner. Up easy pockets to the finish.

name: Dr. Evil
description: Not really any great holds until the anchors.

name: Fat Bastard
description: Far left route. .

name: Frau Farbissina
description: Basically a boulder problem off the large rock protected by one bolt. Easy ground to anchors.

name: Minime
description: Technical start to a diamond finish.

name: Scotty Boy
description: Start in the alcove ( w/o the boulder)  and use the crack to gain pockets and edges. A nice side-pull uptop eases you to the anchors. Check out the high right ledge above.

name: Cutlass
description: Start on two good pockets below the shelf, gain the face using your choice of holds. Move up and right to a nice top out.

name: Mutiny
description: Start on a jug at the back of the overhang, make a couple moves up on big holds to get past the overhang, then finish on big and dirty holds.

name: Silhouette
description: Start on flat jug on arete climb left onto face then straight up. Crux moves down low, easy top out.

name: Electric Boogaloo
description: Sit start using large right hand pocket and smaller left pocket. Move up to ledges below blank section, plan your feet, because they will disappear. Use high feet to get to crux, and work your way through to the top out.

name: Electric Love
description: Sit start at the obvious crack on the right side of the wall, follow the crack line to the top, two move traverse left to mantle top out.

name: Kirchoff's Loop Law
description: Climb in a perpetual loop.  Start where you want; the Engineer in me  says start in one of the bottom corners though. Option 1) Climb up, traverse, climb down, traverse, repeat.  Option 2) Traverse, climb up, traverse, climb down, repeat. How many times can you complete the loop without coming off the wall?  Really hard to grade this climb as it gets harder with each loop completed!

name: Warning: Low Voltage
description: Start on the juggy set of slots just to the right of the circled start holds for Kirchoff's loop law. Climb straight up and top out. This route serves as a good warmup for the other climbs on the wall.FA unknown; if you have any information on who first cleaned and climbed this boulder please share so I can add to the page. The line has very clearly been climbed before and I was surprised to find it not already listed here on MP.

name: Hakuna Matata
description: This is a fun traverse problem about 50' long on the cliff side of the gorge.

name: Boone Saloon
description: This boulder climbs really well.  It is one of my favorites in the mad.  It's high in the air but the landing is nice and flat.  Be careful at the top, the climbing gets easy but  the rock quality gets questionable.  Same start as Social Distancing.

name: Social Distancing
description: This climb is okay.  It makes a good warmup if you're going to try Boone Saloon.  From the start holds, make a  few moves to get a huge left hand jug-sidepull and then reach up with your right hand to a high jug rail.  The rest is just an easy and sketchy top out.  Same start holds as Boone Saloon.

name: Mug Thug
description: Mug Thug is the V3 maybe a 4 that starts on the central low arete with one hand on the good lip and the other on top as a pinch. Then move straight up to the flake above the start and work your way a little to the right to find the big pocket on the vertical face. It's a little throw to find the monster jug that you use to pull yourself up onto the slab section. Lastly navigate your way straight to the top right up the middle of the slab.

name: Zen-N
description: Start on far right side on low vertical ledge. Then move to the left on some nice pocket/jugs and pull the slab section from the protruding arete with the chicken head on top. Finish at the peak of the slab where it becomes a triangle.

name: Blue
description: Start on left corner, stay low, traverse right using pockets until around arete, topout on arete

name: Green
description: Start on flake, climb up and left to the easy topout.

name: Orange
description: Start low on arete staying off the rail, low traverse in pockets to far left, topout over the corner.

name: Purple
description: Sit start with feet to right, climb through pockets

name: Red
description: Start on flake, climb up and right to the easy topout

name: Yellow
description: Start low on arete, climb the overhang and topout over the bulge

name: Ape Index Apparatus
description: Same start as Riptide. Pull left to undercling, make big move to slopers and top out.

name: Beach Patrol
description: Start on The Surfing Raptor and continue around the arete, traversing low with your feet on the ramp.  Once you encounter a good slot and left hand side pull pinch, cross up to a crimp, then move left to a ledge.  Traverse left into Gaston Bone and top out on the arete.

name: Chundercling
description: Right of shark week.  Right hand Undercling to left hand funk knob to jug rail.

name: Crinoid Temptations
description: Microcrimp left hand, and right hand on a small nub pinch. First move crux to a right hand sidepull. Continue straight up avoiding the arete to the left. Potential for a hard low start.

name: Everything is Matter
description: Traverse left and dyno to topout.

name: Feather Galaxy
description: This is an extension to Feather Star. Start using the same starting hold for Shark Week. Traverse to the right to link into Feather Star

name: Feather Star
description: The easiest line to the top. Follow the flakes to the lip.

name: Feather Universe
description: This is a long extension into Feather Star. Start by using a left side pull and a flake, then traverse right into Feather Star.

name: Gaston Bone
description: I didn't see any chalk on this route, and the landing is really bad so I may have been the first to put this up, not sure though. Some techy moves up a block. Possibly some loose holds, be careful. Also, top out is scary.

name: Michael Jordyno
description: Start with left hand on a geometric ledge and right on an incut within the seam above the rightmost death block on the left side of the boulder. Place a high foot and launch past Everything is Matter and Rest Day, Best Day's rail to dunk on the good spot on the lip. Mantle on secure holds and reflect on the vast oceans that once occupied the Ohio Valley.

name: Molera
description: Start on obvious flat jug follow good holds straight up the face to top out.

name: Peace
description: Hey all, there was no description of this route despite some of the holds having chalk already on them. My guess is that it's either been worked on and not posted/sent (top jugs have no chalk) and/or the holds on this route are used on lines to the left and right of this problem. That said, if you know someone that has climbed this before me, send me a message and I'll change the FA accordingly. (10/3/20)Start on the relatively easy bottom holds and work your way into the leaning rail just above. There's the 'triangle' holds for your right and the crux is figuring out wha tot do with your left hand... many options there, the fun is finding out what works best. Throw to a right hand (side pull?) that fits a full pad and then bring your left hand up to the hold directly left of it. Finish on bucket and top out.

name: Remora
description: Somewhat contrived. Stay in narrow lane, don't use holds out left on "Shark Week". Start on jug and climb straight up blank steepness through a couple small holds.

name: Rest day, best day
description: Long but secure moves to the top, fun top out.

name: Riptide
description: Problem working the left most arete of the Crinoid Cove Boulder.  Decent exposure on this route as a few of the moves have your weight shifting out left into a sloped drop, however the holds are great and it is a well-sequenced relatively static line.  Sit start from the shelf, moving up to the jug then trend left and in to hit a small undercling on the corner. Pull into the right sidepull at the base of the flake and then tense in to hit the edge up and around the arete. Hit another great sidepull and top out directly over the arete using good hands.

name: Shark Week
description: Start on the same hands as Everything is Matter. Move up to a gaston with your left to a pinch on a tooth. Get a hand on a less-than-ideal crimp and finish with a topout.

name: The Surfing Raptor
description: Start at the far right with both hands in the two small pockets. Traverse to the left until you reach corner where most people will down climb to get off the boulder. Top out from there.

name: Turd Burglar
description: Left of shark week. The harder line up the middle. Pop to a good right hand side pull halfway up.

name: “Let’s make our own line”
description: Yellow is a V0+ with two good solid crimps and then big move into a crack (can’t really see it when on the wall) and then climb up and top out to the right. The blue holds make it a V2 variation with a quick move to the yellow right hand start and then follow the yellow route. The bottom blue circle is the foot.

name: Borgin
description: Sit start on a low ledge right of the arete.  This is the same starting hold as Burkes.  Move left on pockets and crimps, then right to a large gaston.  Continue past a hueco to good ledges before topping out.

name: Burkes
description: Sit start on a low ledge right of the arete.  This is the same starting hold as Borgin.  Move up to a pocket with your left, the right to flat, gaston.  Follow the sidepulls past a hueco to the top.  Aim for a notch.

name: Ollivanders
description: Sit start on pocket mini jugs.  Move up and left to a long, incut jug and continue up to the highest point on the boulder.

name: Greenhorn
description: Once you get your feet off the bottom, use vertical slots, side pulls and jugs to get to the top. Feet are lacking at the bottom, but improve as you climb. For more of a challenge, don't use the side pulls on the arete.    Downclimb off the back of the boulder.

name: Pearl-Handled Revolvers
description: Double undercling start with questionable feet climb up through side pulls and an undercling dancing your feet until your able to grab the rail at the top. Hueco is out.     Easy down climb off the back of boulder after topping out.     Variant (V1)- Same climb but hueco is in.

name: Rough Riders Ride Again
description: Start on the right side of the face, and walk your hands up the arete as you climb to the top.

name: Trigger's Tricks
description: Start with your left hand in low side pull hole and right hand on the thin flake and work your way up the main face using the large right hand side pulls, large hole, and then thin ledges up top to great rails to top out. Arete is out.     Easy down climb on opposite side of rock.

name: Bad Astrology
description: Start on large flat jug. Traverse left on decent holds to finish jug.

name: On The Cusp
description: Start same as Relatable Mystics but continue climbing up instead of traversing. Finish on flat jug.

name: Relatable Mystics
description: Low start on your choice of block jugs. Pull through roof and traverse feature on slots and pockets to jug at lip.

name: Skin-Walker
description: Start on jug just above cave on the right side of the roof. Climb through decent holds in roof to tricky move around the lip. Keep it together to the finish.

name: Telekinized
description: Start on jug at back of roof climb through good holds in roof and crimps to pull the lip.

name: Busted
description: Stand start on sloper and traverse right. Pull two powerful moves to gain jug at lip.

name: Dusted
description: Start on sloper same as Busted. Traverse left and finish on same jug as Mixtape.

name: The Invention
description: Stand start matched on crimp/sloper, make big move to jug and follow holds to lip.

name: Madrugada
description: Start same as Mixtape, climb up and right through crimps to sloper. Finish on Busted.

name: Mixtape
description: Start on two mini- jugs, climb straight out the roof on crimps. Finish on jug at lip.

name: Palm Flapper
description: Start low on two parallel crimps. Climb out through two sharp pockets to a huge move to the jugs. Finish at the lip and drop off.

name: Seeking Asylum
description: Start same as The Invention and make big move straight out roof to lip. Climb through a couple more crimps above the lip to flat finish hold.

name: E-Z Path
description: Start on pockets right of UP! and move up on the blank-ish face to the top.

name: Finger Twist
description: Route follows vertical crack on main face of boulder. V3-4 if you use crack for hands and feet. If you use face of boulder for feet and only use crack for hands, it eases the grade to V1/2.

name: UP!
description: Start on pockets right of Finger Twist and climb straight up on blank-ish face.

name: Abandon Ship
description: Start low and left and traverse over to the arete. Then work your way up the arete and take advantage of the great holds when you can find them.

name: Beached Whale
description: Start either in pockets under the ledge or out right following the thin crack (more difficult), climb up through pockets to surmount the ledge, elegantly or like a beached whale, then continue using a shared bolt and anchors finishing to right of anchors.

name: Blowhole
description: Look for good pockets down low and utilize side pulls and bomber ledges up high.

name: Minute Man
description: This route is an obvious severely overhanging prow a bit past the Recycler area. Was shown to me by Jim and Josh, and I tried several times over a couple of years while visiting family in the area. Felt mid-5.13 until I finally unlocked the beta and sent.  Originally graded 12d/13a, I have decided to just call it 13a (15 May 2019).

name: Narwal
description: Technical face climbing.

name: Sea Legs
description: Decide left or right sequence on big pockets to ledge. Make a couple easy moves to anchors.

name: She is very gorgeous to me
description: Sit start with right hand in two one finger pockets, left hand in good slot. Use arete and face to top out.  Part of effort to put up some more easy low commitment boulders for beginners.

name: Undertow
description: True start slightly left under bolt 1 with high heel hook on buldge. Climb to ledge and clip shared bolt and anchors staying left at anchors.  Alternate start to right of buldge in depression. Use pockets and side pulls until you traverse left to bolt line. Makes start less muscular but should be about the same grade.

name: White Whale
description: Start low and left of the bolt line in the depression for full effect.  Traverse right down low then flow up using balance moves on bolt line. Crux movements just below bolt.

name: Bloodmutt
description: Classic climb (and is definitely hard for the grade in comparison to other 5.8s at the Mad). Climb fun and easy bulges after a challenging start.

name: Chin Chimney
description: Classic climb (and is definitely hard for the grade in comparison to other 5.8s at the Mad). Moderate climbing on good edges and pockets. Start slightly left of bolts and continue on some thin moves at top for a more exciting 5.10a. variation.  Original route is right of bolt line.

name: Coon Scat
description: Stay off the big stuff at the bottom and make sure you snag the very top ledge for the tick.

name: Digitalis
description: Furthest east sport route on the cliff line. Direct start off the ground. Avoid the detached boulder on the right. Reach to mono is the crux. Two moves past the anchor gets the tick. Make sure to check bolts before climbing here as this area has not yet been rebolted.

name: Double Overhangs
description: This is the second from the right route in the Trash Shoot area. It is located directly to the right of Bloodmutt. It follows a line just to the left of the bolts over two small bulges. Boulder through a tricky start (a tall person may have an easier time here), then pull over two separate bulges to reach the anchors.

name: Expectation Moderation
description: This is the second bolted route on the right-most wall of the Trash Shoot Area. Follow the bolt line through small crimps and balancy foot work to the second bolt. From there make the big reach to the ledge just above the anchors.

name: Garburator
description: Sit start on jug outside of break in cliff. Climb right on jug blocks through the break making big move to ledge and topping out.

name: Hellstrong
description: Start directly under overhang. Short powerful route with barn door finish. Watch the tree if you blow it at the anchors.

name: Jacob's Ladder
description: Fun beginner route with big pockets and ledges. Start just below or slightly left of bolts. Trend right as you move up on great holds past two bolts to the top. Possibly the easiest route currently bolted at the Mad. Would be great for a first-time leader.

name: La Basura
description: Same start as Garburator but climbs right before the big ledge through jug gaston. Climb up and right through crimps to top out.

name: Left Eye
description: Layaway to the left with a high right foot and no LF to nail the far right of horizontal.. Don't follow the chalk on the right. The original start makes the route. Also don't cheap out and go right at the top. Otherwise consider it a 5.9.

name: Mad Corner
description: This is the first bolted route on the right-most wall of the   Trash Shoot area. Walk past Hellstrong and Lefteye to reach this section. Mad Corner   follows the arete on the left side of the wall. Climb either left on the arete   or right into the alcove, then make several moves to surmount the large bulge   to reach the anchors.

name: Muchos Bufos
description: Start on the crack with body down in the depression under the bulge. Move up the crack to the left of the bolt line. Pick a good spot to traverse right to clip the anchors.  Finish jugs are directly above the anchors.Alternate start with a 5.11c'ish move: Start under bolt line slightly to the right directly under the bulge.  Move up using small two finger ledges and pockets and a great lean back side pull.  Very hard to get feet up.  Finishes the same after the first bolt. **Note: Top roping this route after a leader can be more challenging than leading due to rope pull and small swing into the alternate start if you fall off.

name: Pancake Propelled
description: Tricky start with undercut feet. If you can make it to the first bolt, it should be smooth sailing to the end.

name: Pyrrharctia isabella
description: Reachy start to great crack, steep bulge to big holds at top.

name: Raining Buckeyes
description: Start in depression area on bolt line, ascend up on fun moves, and figure out the middle crux before moving to finish.

name: Slug Buddy
description: Kinda tricky start to  fun pockets and a little crack.

name: Capacity
