description: Start right hand jug and left hand crimp, move through sharp pockets to jug. Make a few more moves to finish.

name: Object Permanence
description: Start on two slots move to side pull and go big to dish, follow good holds to finish.

name: Pisces Mode
description: Start left hand flat undercling right hand side pull crimp, make big move to dish and finish on jug.

name: Swiss These
description: Start on pockets just above small roof, climb straight up pockets to finish.

name: Tread Water
description: Start on two large pockets, climb pockets to flat jug.

name: Buckeye Buttress
description: Straight forward, follows the arete up pockets and crimps.

name: 4 Leaves
description: Directly to the right of Clover is this similar, but harder climb.  Named after the 4 side pulls used in the original beta.  The rock quality is just as good as it's sister climb and it leaves the hardest move for last!

name: Against the Law
description: Chimney climb to a corner crimp and pull hard till your feet touch. Traverse slab right and climb over. Climbing shoes not necessary, barefoot falls can hurt

name: Antechamber of Commerce
description: Refrigerator climb to the top, don't use the pillars to the left and right. Top out provides a nice view but can be quite wet if it's rained recently. There is a structure at the bottom of this one that's impossible to protect, so be cautious because a shallow fall could be dangerous.

name: Art School Topout
description: Very similar route to "Rainbow Orca" but more accessible from the road + slightly worse holds and a slightly more challenging topout. Don't use the garage lettering

name: Burnet Bend
description: Start and end in a sit start and move from the outside of the East side of the semicircle to the opposing side using any holds and feet (no walking up the pillars, obviously). Kind of a dumb traverse, but it's just something to do if you're over by this polylith for the other climbs.

name: Campus Campus
description: Start standing as low as you can and monkey up the proudest boulder-esque face on campus and top out. Climbing shoes not necessary, pad recommended. A bit of a slug fest, can't make very many attempts on this one in a session with how it treats your skin

name: Campus Recreation (Overhung)
description: Start with both hands under the pool window to a shouldery gaston press, make your way under the overhang and come out the other side for a nice top out. DON'T use the large ledge underneath (see photo). One of my favorites.

name: Chamber of Commerce
description: Go up the letters. Top out provides a nice view but can be quite wet if it has rained recently. Easily doable barefoot, street shoes will be a challenge, pad recommended

name: Climb Crimps, Man (CCM)
description: Quarter pad crimps to top out

name: CLOVER
description: This is a classic to campus. It's a super consistent and diverse line that takes a bit of solving. There is a chalk drawing of a clover on the route and "CLOVER" written so I guessed that was the name. If you FA'd this boulder or have climbed it please comment!

name: Educator (Overhung)
description: Sit start at the bottom of the stairs, climb underneath, traverse the bridge, find feet + a tiny crimp on the wall, and dyno from there to top out. Use the fence for V1 (climbing shoes not necessary for V1 variant)

name: Free Parking
description: Crimps and side pulls lead to a very fun, body tension-reliant deadpoint and topout. One of the most dynamic and satisfying boulders around campus

name: GEO-PHYS
description: Dihedral turns into a narrow chimney climb and top out. Start with low feet for a couple starting slab moves or jump and slap your foot right up into the windowsill. Fun and consistent route with a little flaking towards the middle to watch out for.

name: High Note
description: A little less than 30 feet of quarter pad crimps on the same size feet all the way up to the sloper jug rail. Not beta intensive by any means, but it takes a certain amount of focus at height. I strongly advise you be confident enough to climb this without relying on pads because they won't help you much unless you downclimb. You should be able to do laps on The Sound of Music before attempting this. I have not attempted the dihedral but I'm guessing that's about V1

name: New Chemistry (Overhung)
description: Sit start underneath as low as possible on either side and traverse left or right to top out, be careful of the low risk but long fall on either side of the top out. The only boulder to use a metal structure on campus (the handrail for the top out), climbing shoes not necessary

name: Old Chemistry
description: Start with a right hand on the bomber corner and use either of the crimpy rails to shimmy feet up and top out. Quite fun for how short it is. Climbing shoes not necessary

name: Rainbow Orca
description: Mini slopers and side pulls to top out. Good texture. There is the eponymous rainbow orca on the opposite side of the wall that you top out on and a not-so-fun chossy chimney climb that's probably not worth it.

name: Sound of Music
description: Start with wide legs and climb up to the same topout as "Climb Crimps, Man". Do not use the south-facing wall/corner with feet or hands (see image).

name: Stadium View
description: Hug the corner and use the square metal plates as feet. One move to the left and top out. Do not use the white bit on the bottom left (see image).

name: Touchdown
description: Start with right hand on side pull crimp and left hand in a gaston palm to top out. Climbing shoes not necessary

name: Black Lung
description: Climb the shaded left side of the arête. The route is loaded with amazing limestone holds, but still has a lot of black dirt on it. I cleaned it as best as I could..... Hence the name...

name: Rusty Pin
description: Locate the crack in the middle of the boulder. Follow the path of least resistance to the top. Wiggle the old piton for good luck.     Caution: loose rocks

name: Grease Lightening
description: Follow the rightward leaning pillar until it ends and then send the face.

name: Dirty Blonde (1a)
description: This is a good warm up located on Frathouse Rock.  It's on the dry corner most people like to climb.  Start with both hands on the undercling.  For the easier start, start above the undercling in the finger pockets on the right and side-pull on the left.  Work your way to the top.  This is an easy top off.

name: Douchebag's Folly (1c)
description: Easy climb with slight cheese grading possibility.  We've seen many douchbags climb this with tennis shoes.  Problem is located on the rear-right corner.  Easy start and easy climb.  The height is a little sketchy due to the angle of the rock face.

name: Major Payne Stewart
description: Overhung side of Frathouse Rock.  Big moves on great holds.  Fun short problem.  Very good chance it is wet.

name: Toofless Wonder (1b)
description: Starts on the dry corner most climbers prefer on this rock.  Lots of good holds and a fun climb.  Start in the same holds as Dirty Blond (1a) and finishes a little right of Dirty Blonde (1a).  Fun climb and another easy top off.

name: Parental Getaway
description: An oddball for the area, this crimpier problem is a fun change of pace in style. Start low on the juggy ledge (or the one below that if you like doing pullups) and stand up on the huge ledges-for-feet to some generous crimps. Gain the face proper with yet more generous crimps and then drift right to a mossy topout. Avoid going straight up for the topout as there is a lot of moss and loose dirt.I can't really tell if this has been climbed before so if anyone has any info like a route name or FA if this has (probably) already been done, please comment and I'll update the page.

name: Capt. Crunch
description: Overhung start to bulge crux.  Typical problem for Veteran's Park.

name: Col. Mustard
description: Techy short problem. Can be done several ways to make it easier or harder.

name: Lightpost lowball traverse
description: Start anywhere on the face of the small boulder sitting next to the light post. Traverse the entire boulder CCW back to the holds you started on. The top of the boulder is off, but any lower steps are in (see picture). Removing the use of any hold which does not have rock above it like the steps would probably bump the grade to V1.I made up the name because I like the alliteration but if anyone knows if this has already been named, please comment and I'll update the page.

name: No Pain No Gain
description: Low start to an already established dyno, super burly and shouldery moves up to the ledge where the dyno leads to a relatively easy top out.

name: pocket watch
description: crux midway,bomber pockets,really clean thru the climb but dirty top out.in the picture it looks dirty but its clean and dry.

name: Pvt. Benjamin
description: Smooth traverse along rail of pockets.  Keep from swinging and you are fine.

name: Unnamed
description: Start on the giant jugg-slot thing on the right face of the boulder. Stay low and traverse left until you're directly below the bulge. Figure out your feet whether you can see them or not and tackle the bulge head on to be rewarded with an easy topout.If anyone has any information on what the route name is, FA, etc, please leave a comment and I'll update the page.
